<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>First Stop: Licensing of Stallions & Certificate of Registration for Foals</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#004080" LINK="#004080" VLINK="#0080C0" ALINK="#0080C0">

<img src="/dcca/graph/fs/fslogosm.gif" alt="First Stop Logo" width=171 height=120 align=left>
<h3 align=center>Department of Commerce & Community Affairs
<hr>
First Stop Business Information Center<br>
Business Requirement
</h3>
<hr>
<br clear=all>

<H3>I.  Business Requirement Profile:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Licensing of Stallions & Certificate of Registration for Foals
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>II.  Agency:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Illinois Department of Agriculture<BR>
Bureau of County Fairs & Horse Racing<BR>
P.O. Box 19281<BR>
Springfield, IL 62794-9281<BR>
(217) 782-4231<BR>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>III.  Statute:</H3>
<DL><DD>
230 Illinois Compiled Statutes Sections 5/30, 31, 33.1 & 40.
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>IV.  Requirement Description:</H3>
<DL><DD>
This Act applies to equine breeding farms, stables, race tracks, veterinarians practicing at race tracks, and all concessionaires doing business at race tracks.  (Of the businesses covered by this Act, only equine breeding farms businesses are regulated by the Department of Agriculture. The other businesses are regulated by the Illinois Racing Board.)<P>

Owners electing to participate in specially restricted races or breeder incentive programs in Illinois (for Illinois Bred and Foaled Standardbreds, Illinois Bred and Foaled Thoroughbreds, or Illinois Foaled Thoroughbreds) must comply with the provisions of this Act, which allows owners to license stallions and register foals that meet the requirements of the Act.<P>

The part of the Act regulated by the Department allows registered horses to race in special Illinois races and to participate in the breeders funds (the Illinois Standardbred Breeders Fund and the Illinois Thoroughbred Breeders Fund.  These funds are made up of 8 1/2 % of all the monies received by the State of Illinois as privilege taxes on racing meetings.).  Any horse not registered as required by the Act may not participate in the specially restricted races in Illinois.<P>
  
Registration of a foal is valid for the life of the horse.  A stallion must be licensed each year.  Licenses are valid for a calendar year and stallions must be re-licensed by January 1st of each year.<P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>V:  Approval Process:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Applicants may contact the Department and request these forms:<P>

Annual Application for Stallion Eligibility-Standardbred<BR>
Annual Application for Stallion Eligibility-Thoroughbred<BR>
Foal Registration, Conceived and Foaled-Standardbred<BR>
Foal Registration, Foaled Only-Standardbred<BR>
Foal Registration, Conceived and Foaled-Thoroughbred<BR>
Foal Registration, Foaled Only-Thoroughbred<P>

An application must be completed and filed with Department, which will then conduct an investigation to determine eligibility of the stallion.  Applications for a foal must be made within 10 days of foaling.  Applications for eligibility and registration for stallions and foals usually take only a few days.  Denied applications may be appealed to the Bureau Chief of Horse Racing at the Department.<P> 
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>VI.  Pre-Requisites, Co-Requisites & Post-Requisites:</H3>
<DL><DD>
None.
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>VII.  Fees:</H3>
<DL><DD>
None.
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<STRONG>| <a href="/dcca/home.htm">DCCA Home Page</a> | <A HREF="/dcca/menus/fsm1.htm">First Stop</a> | <A HREF="/dcca/menus/fsbr.htm">Business Requirements</a> |</STRONG>

