<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>First Stop: Electric or Gas Service: Certificate of Public Convenience and Necessity for Operation of a Public Utility</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#004080" LINK="#004080" VLINK="#0080C0" ALINK="#0080C0">

<img src="/dcca/graph/fs/fslogosm.gif" alt="First Stop Logo" width=171 height=120 align=left>
<h3 align=center>Department of Commerce & Community Affairs
<hr>
First Stop Business Information Center<br>
Business Requirement
</h3>
<hr>
<br clear=all>

<H3>I.	Business Requirement Profile:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Electric or Gas Service: Certificate of Public Convenience and Necessity for Operation of a Public Utility
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>II.	Agency:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Illinois Commerce Commission<BR>
527 East Capitol, P.O. Box 19280<BR>
Springfield, IL 62794-9280<BR>
Public Utilities Division<BR>
(217) 785-5432<BR>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>III.	Statute:</H3>
<DL><DD>
220 Illinois Compiled Statutes 5/8-406.  (Public Utilities Act)
</DD></DL>
<H3>Regulation:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Title 83 Illinois Administrative Code Part 200 (Rules of Practice)
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>IV.	Requirement Description:</H3>
<DL><DD>
A Certificate of Public Convenience and Necessity ("Certificate") issued by the Commission allows a public utility* to provide electric, natural gas, or water and sewer service and/or to construct new plants, equipment, and facilities for providing such service.<P>

Certificates remain effective as long as the service is considered a public convenience or necessity.<P>

* A "public utility" is an investor owned business that sells or delivers electricity, gas, water or sewer service for public use.<P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>V.	Approval Process:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Applicants for a Certificate must file a Petition with the Illinois Commerce Commission.  No forms are available, but applicants or their attorney may follow the process described in the Commission's "Rules of Practice".  The Commission will hold a public hearing and will grant a Certificate if it determines that utility service proposed by the applicant is necessary to promote the public's convenience. <P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>VI.	Pre-Requisites, Co-Requisites & Post-Requisites:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Applicants for a Certificate have the legal burden of proving before the Commission that issuance of  a Certificate will promote the public convenience and necessity.<P>

Public Utilities must pay an annual regulatory tax of 0.1% on gross revenues.<P>

Public Utilities must file an annual report.  Gas & Electric Public Utilities use Form# 21 ILCC.<P>

Public Utilities must file tariffs, or any changes in its tariffs, before providing service.<P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>VII.	Fees:</H3>
<DL><DD>
There are no fees for a certificate.  (However, the Public Utilities Act requires a public utility receiving permission from the Commission to issue stock, bonds, notes or other instruments of  indebtedness to pay a fee on each issuance.)
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<STRONG>| <a href="/dcca/home.htm">DCCA Home Page</a> | <A HREF="/dcca/menus/fsm1.htm">First Stop</a> | <A HREF="/dcca/menus/fsbr.htm">Business Requirements</a> |</STRONG>

</BODY>
</HTML>
</DOC>
