<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>First Stop: Emergency Planning & Community Right-to-Know Act (EPCRA)</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#004080" LINK="#004080" VLINK="#0080C0" ALINK="#0080C0">

<img src="/dcca/graph/fs/fslogosm.gif" alt="First Stop Logo" width=171 height=120 align=left>
<h3 align=center>Department of Commerce & Community Affairs
<hr>
First Stop Business Information Center<br>
Business Requirement
</h3>
<hr>
<br clear=all>

<H3>I.  Business Requirement:</H3>
<DL><DD>Emergency Planning & Community Right-to-Know Act (EPCRA)</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>II. Agency:</H3>
<DL><DD> Illinois Emergency Management Agency (IEMA)<BR>
110 E. Adams<BR>
Springfield, IL 62701<BR>
(217) 782-4694<BR></DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>III. Statute Citation:</H3>
<DL><DD><H3>Illinois:</H3></DD></DL>
<DL><DD><DD>430 Illinois Compiled Statutes 100/1</DD></DD></DL>
<DL><DD><H3>Federal:</H3></DD></DL>
<DL><DD><DD>Title III, Superfund Amendments and Reauthorization Act of 1986 (SARA).  42 USCA 11001.</DD></DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>IV. Requirement Description:</H3>

<DL><DD>The purpose of EPCRA is to provide
information to the public that can help protect private citizens and
property against adverse effects of an inadvertent release of an extremely
hazardous substance into the environment and to minimize the likelihood of
such an occurrence. The Act requires businesses to file reports identifying
hazardous substances, chemical locations, chemical properties, etc., at
their facilities in amounts above established threshold quantities.  EPCRA
requires the State Emergency Response Commission (SERC) and the Local
Emergency Planning Committee (LEPC) to make these reports available to the
public upon request.  Because this information is accessible and useful, it
provides local citizens and local government officials an opportunity to
mitigate and prepare for any contingency involving a release of a hazardous
substance into the environment.  A business must notify immediately the
National Response Center, IEMA and the LEPC, and give pertinent information
about any inadvertent release of a hazardous substance into the environment
in reportable quantities.</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>V. Approval Process:</H3>
<DL><DD>N/A</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>VI. Pre-Requisites, Co-Requisites & Post-Requisites:</H3>

<DL><DD><P>1. Any facility with quantities of 500 pounds, or a threshold quantity of
an extremely hazardous substance (as defined by the USEPA), must file with
the SERC and the LEPC an emergency planning notification and either a list
of  chemicals or Material Safety Data Sheet (MSDS), and an annual Hazardous
Chemical Inventory (Tier) report.

<P>2. Any facility with 10,000 pounds or more of a hazardous substance (as
defined by the USEPA) must file either a list of chemicals or a MSDS, and
an annual "Tier" report to the SERC, the LEPC and the local fire
department.

<P>3. Any facility that releases into the environment reportable quantity of
either an extremely hazardous or hazardous substance must report this
release immediately to the National Response Center, the SERC and the LEPC.
A written follow-up notice is also required to be filed with these agencies
as soon as practical after the initial notification.</DD>
</DL>
<HR>
<H3>VII. Fees:</H3>
<DL><DD>None.</DD></DL>

<HR>
<STRONG>| <a href="/dcca/home.htm">DCCA Home Page</a> | <A HREF="/dcca/menus/fsm1.htm">First Stop</a> | <A HREF="/dcca/menus/fsbr.htm">Business Requirements</a> |</STRONG>

</BODY>
</HTML>
