<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>First Stop: Alien Labor Certification</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#004080" LINK="#004080" VLINK="#0080C0" ALINK="#0080C0">

<img src="/dcca/graph/fs/fslogosm.gif" alt="First Stop Logo" width=171 height=120 align=left>
<h3 align=center>Department of Commerce & Community Affairs
<hr>
First Stop Business Information Center<br>
Business Requirement
</h3>
<hr>
<br clear=all>

<h3>  I.  Business Requirement Profile:  </h3>
 <dl><dd>
Alien Labor Certification
         </dd></dl><hr><h3>
II.  Agency:               </h3>
                                <DL><DD>
Illinois Department of Employment Security<BR>
Alien Labor Certification Unit                <BR>
401 South State Street; 3-S                       <BR>
Chicago, Illinois  60605                              <BR>
(312)-793-6830                                            <BR>
</DD></DL><HR><H3>                                                             
III. Statute:     </H3>
                       <DL><DD>
8 USC  1182(a) (5) (A) The Immigration and Nationality Act
                           </DL></DD>    <P><H3>
     Regulation:                      </H3>
                                     <DL><DD>
20 Code of Federal Regulations 656 (Occupational Labor Certification Determinations)
                                             </DL></DD><HR><H3>
IV.  Requirement Description:                                  </H3>
  <DL><DD>                                                                  
  To hire an alien, an employer must demonstrate that no U.S.  workers are available, and that the employment of the alien will not adversely affect working conditions of similarly employed U.S. workers. 

As a first step in the U.S. Immigration process, an employer must file a Labor Certification request with the Illinois Department of Employment Security (IDES), the agent for the U.S. Department of Labor (IDOL).
Hiring an alien without  authorization subjects an employer to fines (and in some cases is a felony).  
          </DL></DD><HR><H3>
V.   Approval Process:      </H3>
                                 <DL><DD>
Application forms ETA 750 and ETA 750A must be completed and filed with the Illinois Department of Employment Security, Alien Labor Certification Unit.

The average processing time for applications is between 6 months and 1 year.

An employer must specify the job description, job hours, the prevailing wage and education requirements on Form ETA 750, and the alien's education and experience on Form ETA 750A.

The employer must post the position within his company, enter a job order into the Statewide Job Service system, and advertise the job in a publication identified by the Alien Certification Unit. The employer will be sent resumes of U.S. workers submitted through IDES and must interview qualified applicants.

If an employer fails to hire U.S. workers referred by IDES or any individuals submitting resumes, he/seh will be directed to document, in detail, why the U.S. worker had been rejected. IDES will follow-up with those applicants referred for their insight into the interview with the employer. If an employer fails to comply with the directives of IDES, the case will be referred directly to the U.S. Departmen of Labor Certifying Officer for a ruling, thereby delaying the hiring process. If the Labor Certification for an alien worker is not granted by the USDOL, the employer may appeal directly to the USDOL, Alien Labor Certification Unit.
                                         </DL></DD><HR><H3>
VI.  Pre-Requisites, Co-Requisites & Post-Requisites:      </H3>

Upon approval of the Labor Certification, the process continues at the jurisdiction and direction of the U.S. Department of Justice, Immigration and Naturalization Bureau.
                                                  </DL></DD> <HR><H3>
VII. Fees:                                                           </H3>
                                                                          <DL><DD>
None.
     </DL></DD>





<HR>
<STRONG>| <a href="/dcca/home.htm">DCCA Home Page</a> | <A HREF="/dcca/menus/fsm1.htm">First Stop</a> | <A HREF="/dcca/menus/fsbr.htm">Business Requirements</a> |</STRONG>

</BODY>
</HTML>
