<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>First Stop: Drinking Water Operator Certification Program  </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#004080" LINK="#004080" VLINK="#0080C0" ALINK="#0080C0">

<img src="/dcca/graph/fs/fslogosm.gif" alt="First Stop Logo" width=171 height=120 align=left>
<h3 align=center>Department of Commerce & Community Affairs
<hr>
First Stop Business Information Center<br>
Business Requirement
</h3>
<hr>
<br clear=all>

<H3>I.  Business Requirement Profile:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Drinking Water Operator Certification Program  
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>II.  Agency:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Illinois Environmental Protection Agency<BR>
Compliance Assurance Section/Bureau of Water<BR>
2200 Churchill Road<BR>
Springfield, IL 62794-9276<BR>
(217)785-0561<BR>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>III.  Statute:</H3>
<DL><DD>
415 Illinois Compiled Statutes 45, Section 1.
</DD></DL>
<H3>Regulation:</H3>
<DL><DD>
35 Illinois Administrative Code 680  Water Supply Operator Certification Rules and Regulations<P>

35 Illinois Administrative Code 60 - 611.870 Pollution Control Board<P>

35 Illinois Administrative Code 651-654, Technical Policy Statements<P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>IV.  Requirement Description:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Drinking Water Operators must be certified to supervise the operation of a potable water treatment plant or a water distribution system.  Every public water supply must have at least one person certified under this program.  Public Water Supplies includes distribution systems where water is purchased from a nearby community and pumped to the outlying town and/or subdivision.  Certification requirements assure the safety and health of the population served by a public water supply.  Operating a water supply without a properly certified operator may result in fines by the Illinois Pollution Control Board.  Operator certification is effective for a period of three years.<P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>V.  Approval Process:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Applications for certification must be notarized and submitted with a Letter of Verification filed with the  Bureau of Water, Compliance Assurance Section, Drinking Water Operator Certification. Applications are usually processed in 30 days.  Applicants may be denied if they do not have  a specified amount of experience with water treatment or distribution or if they have had typhoid fever, amoebic dysentery, or lived with an individual having either of these without an affidavit from a health official establishing they are not carriers of the disease.  Denied applications may be appealed to the certification Advisory Board.<P>    
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>VI.  Pre-Requisites, Co-Requisites & Post-Requisites:</H3>
<DL><DD>
None.
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>VII.  Fees:    </H3>
<DL><DD>
Application:   		$30<P>
Written Examination:	$10<P>
Certificate Renewal 	$10<P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<STRONG>| <a href="/dcca/home.htm">DCCA Home Page</a> | <A HREF="/dcca/menus/fsm1.htm">First Stop</a> | <A HREF="/dcca/menus/fsbr.htm">Business Requirements</a> |</STRONG>

</BODY>
