<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>First Stop: Permit for discharge of process wastewater to waters of the United States.</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#004080" LINK="#004080" VLINK="#0080C0" ALINK="#0080C0">

<img src="/dcca/graph/fs/fslogosm.gif" alt="First Stop Logo" width=171 height=120 align=left>
<h3 align=center>Department of Commerce & Community Affairs
<hr>
First Stop Business Information Center<br>
Business Requirement
</h3>
<hr>
<br clear=all>

<H3>I. Business Requirement Profile:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Permit for discharge of process wastewater to waters of the United States.
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>II. Agency: </H3>
<DL><DD>
Illinois Environmental Protection Agency <BR>
Division of Water Pollution Control <BR>
2200 Churchill Road<BR>
Springfield, IL 62794-9276<BR>
(217)782-0610  <BR>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>III. Statute:</H3>
<DL><DD>
415 ILCS, Act 5, Section 13.
</DD></DL>

<H3>Regulation:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Title 35, Subtitle C, Chapter 1, Part 309 Subpart A   
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>IV. Requirement Description:</H3>
<DL><DD>
A Permit is required when there is a discharge* of any contaminant or pollutant into the waters of the State or into a well (unless authorized by an Underground Injection Permit).  A new business or business relocating to a new site must file an application with the Agency and obtain a Permit before discharging wastewater.  Discharging a contaminant or pollutant without a permit is subject to a civil penalty up to  $10,000  for each day that the violation occurs. <P> 

Permits are valid for a maximum of five (5) years.  *Discharges included are:  a. Discharge of process wastewater;  b. Discharge of storm water from:  Areas where storm water is associated with industrial  activity for industries with certain Standard Industrial Classification (SIC) codes,  Construction sites where the project will result in  the disturbance of 5 (five), or more acres total land area;  Activities which are known to cause violations of State water quality.<P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>V. Approval Process:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Applicants must file a National Pollutant Discharge Elimination System (NPDES) Permit Application together with any additional information that the agency may require to assure the discharge will be in compliance with  State and Federal requirements.  Applications are available from the Agency's Division of Water Pollution Control.  After making a tentative decision as to issue or deny the permit, the Agency will issue public notice of the proposed permit and accept comments or suggestions from interested parties.<P>  
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>VI. Pre-Requisites, Co-Requisites & Post-Requisites:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Permits are subject to limitations, extensive monitoring and reporting requirements which will be stated in the permit, and administered by the Agency's Bureau of Water, Compliance Assurance Section.
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>VII. Fees:</H3>
<DL><DD>
None.
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<STRONG>| <a href="/dcca/home.htm">DCCA Home Page</a> | <A HREF="/dcca/menus/fsm1.htm">First Stop</a> | <A HREF="/dcca/menus/fsbr.htm">Business Requirements</a> |</STRONG>

</BODY>
</HTML>
