<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>First Stop: Permit to haul (transport) special waste</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#004080" LINK="#004080" VLINK="#0080C0" ALINK="#0080C0">

<img src="/dcca/graph/fs/fslogosm.gif" alt="First Stop Logo" width=171 height=120 align=left>
<h3 align=center>Department of Commerce & Community Affairs
<hr>
First Stop Business Information Center<br>
Business Requirement
</h3>
<hr>
<br clear=all>

<H3>I.	Business Requirement Profile:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Permit to haul (transport) special waste
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>II.	Agency:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Illinois Environmental Protection Agency (Agency)<BR>
Bureau of Land / Solid Waste Mgt. Section <BR>
1340 N. Ninth St.
Springfield, IL 62703	<BR>
(217) 785-8604  <BR>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>III.	Statute:</H3>
<DL><DD>
415 Illinois Compiled Statutes 5/21 (g) and (j) 
</DD></DL>
<H3>Regulation:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Title 35 Illinois Administrative Code Part 809.
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>IV.	Requirement Description</H3>
<DL><DD>
A special waste hauling permit allows a person to transport any special waste (including hazardous waste*) generated  in, or to be disposed of, stored or treated in Illinois. Transporting special waste without a permit may constitute criminal activity as either a Class A misdemeanor or Class 1-4 felony and conviction may result in prison terms.  (Criminal actions include knowingly transferring waste and accepting payment without the required permit.)<P>

Special waste hauling permits are valid for one year. <P>

Each trailer/truck must be registered with Agency.<P>

A Conditionally Exempt Small Quantity Generator (anyone who generates less than 100 kg of waste in a calendar month) may transport his own waste without a permit.<P>

* If the waste is hazardous, a federal I.D. number is required, and may be obtained by filing a completed  USEPA form #8700 with the Agency.<P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>V.	Approval Process:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Applicants must file a Form # LPC-37. The Agency usually processes applications in about two weeks. Common reasons applications are denied include previous violations of  laws, regulations or ordinances governing the operation of waste disposal sites, felony convictions; or gross carelessness in handling, storing, processing, transporting or disposing of hazardous wastes. If the Agency denies an application or imposes conditions on a Permit, the Applicant may appeal the decision and petition for a hearing before the Pollution Control Board.  Before the hearing date the parties are free to negotiate terms of the dispute which may result in a revised permit.  In a hearing before the PCB, the petitioner has the burden of proof. 
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>VI.	Pre-Requisites, Co-Requisites & Post-Requisites:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Facilities must be available for inspection by the Agency. A special Waste Hauling Permit must be displayed on any vehicle used to transport special waste, bearing  a seal and a number issued by the Agency, and the words, "Licensed Special Waste Hauler:  (number)" in numbers & letters at least two inches high.  	Permit holders must have insurance  and an Emergency Contingency Plan. A manifest must be in the vehicle during transportation of the special waste, which documents (for tracking) all shipments of waste within the State of Illinois.  The manifest must be written on a form prescribed by and available from the Agency.<P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>VII.	Fees:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Processing Fee					$250  (annually)<P>
Trailer/Truck Registration Fee	$ 20  (annually)<P>
Manifest Form Fee				$  1<P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
