<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>First Stop: Carnival and Amusement Ride Inspection</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#004080" LINK="#004080" VLINK="#0080C0" ALINK="#0080C0">

<img src="/dcca/graph/fs/fslogosm.gif" alt="First Stop Logo" width=171 height=120 align=left>
<h3 align=center>Department of Commerce & Community Affairs
<hr>
First Stop Business Information Center<br>
Business Requirement
</h3>
<hr>
<br clear=all>

<H3>I.	Business Requirement Profile:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Carnival and Amusement Ride Inspection
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>II.	Agency:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Illinois Department of Labor<BR>
Amusement Ride Inspection Division<BR>
1 West Old State Capitol Plaza, Room 300<BR>
Springfield, IL  62701 <BR>
(217) 782 - 9347<BR>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>III.	Statute:</H3>
<DL><DD>
430 Illinois Compiled Statutes 85/2-1
</DD></DL>
<H3>Regulation:</H3>
<DL><DD>
56 Illinois Administrative Code, Chapter XIII, Part 6000.
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>IV.	Requirement Description:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Any Amusement Ride or Amusement Attraction must be inspected by the Department and a Permit must be issued before it may be operated in Illinois.<P>

Applicants must show proof of liability insurance before a permit will be issued.<P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>V.	Approval Process:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Applicant must file with the Department an "Application for Permit to Operate" (Form # IL 452-0005), a "Route Sheet" (Form # IL 452-0004), a Certificate of Insurance and, where appropriate, a "Nondestructive Test Report". This information should be submitted to the Department at least two weeks prior to the date scheduled to begin operation of  the ride or attraction.  Upon receipt of the documents, and verification of the information, the Department will schedule a physical inspection of the ride or amusement equipment. A permit will be issued if the inspector determines the equipment to be safe. If it is found to be unsafe, and cannot be made safe while the inspector is on site, a "Stop Operation Order" will be issued prohibiting operation. A permit may be issued when the unsafe condition has been corrected and a satisfactory reinspection has been completed.<P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>VI.	Pre-Requisites, Co-Requisites & Post-Requisites:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Permits are prominently affixed to the ride or attraction.  Injuries resulting from the operation of an amusement ride or amusement attraction must be reported to the Department of Labor.  The Department conducts follow-up inspections and monitors the operation of those rides/attractions.<P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>VII.	Fees:</H3>
<DL><DD>
(Annually, for each ride or amusement:)<P>

A. PERMIT FEES<P>
<DL><DD>
	1) Kiddie Rides: $10.<BR>
	2) Major Rides: $25.  <BR>
	3) Amusement Attractions: $25.  <BR>
	4) Ski Lifts, Aerial Tramways, Rope Tows: $25.<BR>
	5) Inflated Amusement Attractions: $10.<BR>
	6) Permit issued after a Stop Operation Order: $10.<P>
</DD></DL>
B. INSPECTION FEES:<P>
<DL><DD>
	1) Kiddie Rides: $20.   <BR>
	2) Major Rides: $50.  <BR>
	3) Amusement Attractions: $50. <BR>
	4) Ski Lifts, Aerial Tramways, Rope Tows: $50  <BR>
	5) Inflated Amusement Attractions: $20. <BR>
	6) Reinspection  after a Stop Operation Order: $250. <BR>
	7) Reinspection: $20.<P>
</DD></DL>
C. FEES DOUBLE IF NOT PAID WITHIN 30 DAYS.<P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<STRONG>| <a href="/dcca/home.htm">DCCA Home Page</a> | <A HREF="/dcca/menus/fsm1.htm">First Stop</a> | <A HREF="/dcca/menus/fsbr.htm">Business Requirements</a> |</STRONG>

</BODY>
