<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>First Stop: Illinois Worker Right to Know Program (Trade Secret Provisions)</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#004080" LINK="#004080" VLINK="#0080C0" ALINK="#0080C0">

<img src="/dcca/graph/fs/fslogosm.gif" alt="First Stop Logo" width=171 height=120 align=left>
<h3 align=center>Department of Commerce & Community Affairs
<hr>
First Stop Business Information Center<br>
Business Requirement
</h3>
<hr>
<br clear=all>

<H3>I.	Business Requirement Profile:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Illinois Worker Right to Know Program (Trade Secret Provisions)
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>II.	Agency:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Illinois Department of Labor<BR>
Safety Inspection and Education Division<BR>
1 West Old State Capitol Plaza<BR>
Springfield, IL 62701<BR>
(217) 782-9386<BR>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>III.	Statute:</H3>
<DL><DD>
820 Illinois Compiled Statutes 255.
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>Regulation:</H3>
<DL><DD>
56 Illinois Administrative Code 205.290.
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>IV:	Requirement Description:</H3>
<DL><DD>
The Act requires employers to give employees notice of exposure to toxic substances they work with that pose known or suspected health hazards, and which may cause death or serious physical harm.  <P>

A manufacturer, supplier, or importer (MSI) may withhold the precise chemical name of a toxic substance from the Material Safety Data Supply Sheet (MSDS) only if the Department recognizes the substance qualifies as a "trade secret" ("trade secret" is defined 	in 820 Illinois Compiled Statutes 255/13).  <P>

MSI's found to be in violation of the Act are subject to a fine of $1,000 for each violation.  Willful or repeated violations of the Act, or an order of the Director, are subject to a $10,000 fine for each violation.  Punitive damages may apply.  <P>

A list of toxic substances is published by and available from the Department. <P>

Final decisions of the Department may be appealed to the circuit court. <P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>V.	Approval Process:</H3>
<DL><DD>
MSIs of toxic substances must file with the Department a MSDS for each toxic substance used, produced or stored in the workplace to which employees may be exposed. (A federal Occupational Safety and Health Administration "Form 174- Material Safety Data Sheet" may be used for this purpose. <P>

To protect a "trade secret", applicants must provide the Department with specific information including a copy of the MSDS, the precise identity of the chemical withheld as a trade secret, and an affidavit supporting the claim that the information is protected as a "bona fide" trade secret.<P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>VI.	Pre-Requisites, Co-Requisites & Post-Requisites:</H3>
<DL><DD>
The MSI must contact the Illinois Department of Labor prior to submitting the trade secret request.<P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>VII.	Fees:</H3>
<DL><DD>
None.
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<STRONG>| <a href="/dcca/home.htm">DCCA Home Page</a> | <A HREF="/dcca/menus/fsm1.htm">First Stop</a> | <A HREF="/dcca/menus/fsbr.htm">Business Requirements</a> |</STRONG>

</BODY>
</HTML>
</DOC>
