<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>First Stop: The Prevailing Wage Act</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#004080" LINK="#004080" VLINK="#0080C0" ALINK="#0080C0">

<img src="/dcca/graph/fs/fslogosm.gif" alt="First Stop Logo" width=171 height=120 align=left>
<h3 align=center>Department of Commerce & Community Affairs
<hr>
First Stop Business Information Center<br>
Business Requirement
</h3>
<hr>
<br clear=all>

<H3>I.	Business Requirement Profile:</H3>
<DL><DD>
The Prevailing Wage Act
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>II.	Agency:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Illinois Department of Labor Conciliation & Mediation Division
<PRE>
160 N. LaSalle St, C-1300   1 W. Old State Capitol Plaza   2309 W. Main St.
Chicago, Illinois 60601	    Room 300	 	           Marion, IL 62959
(312) 793-2814		    Springfield, IL 		   (618) 993-7271
		            (217) 782-1710
</PRE>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>III.	Statute:</H3>
<DL><DD>
820 Illinois Compiled Statutes 130/1-12
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>IV.	Requirement Description:</H3>
<DL><DD>
The Act requires that contractors on public works projects must pay the prevailing rate of wages paid to the workers performing similar work, and to keep records of the names of  employees, their trades or occupations, and hourly wages paid.  (The prevailing wage for construction work is determined on a county-by-county basis.) The Act prohibits contractors from under-bidding public works projects by paying less than the prevailing  wages to their workers.  A contractor found to have paid less than the prevailing wage is required to pay workers the difference between the wage paid and the prevailing wage, and  may be penalized 20% of those unpaid wages.  A contractor found to have violated the Act on two occasions may be barred from public works projects for two years.<P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>V.	Approval Process:</H3>
<DL><DD>
A list of current prevailing wage rates for the county in which a public works project is located is available from the Department at its offices in Chicago, Springfield, or Marion, or from the government body letting the contract.<P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>VI.	Pre-Requisites, Co-Requisites & Post-Requisites:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Contractors  must keep accurate payroll records and make them available to the Illinois Department for inspection.<P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>VII.	Fees:</H3>
<DL><DD>
None.
</DD></DL>


<HR>
