<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>First Stop: Aquaculture Permit</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#004080" LINK="#004080" VLINK="#0080C0" ALINK="#0080C0">

<img src="/dcca/graph/fs/fslogosm.gif" alt="First Stop Logo" width=171 height=120 align=left>
<h3 align=center>Department of Commerce & Community Affairs
<hr>
First Stop Business Information Center<br>
Business Requirement
</h3>
<hr>
<br clear=all>
<H3> I.   Business Requirement Profile:
    </H3><DL><DD>
Aquaculture Permit
                 </DD></DL><HR><H3>
II.  Agency:                       </H3><DL><DD>

Illinois Department of Natural Resources        <BR>
Conservation Division                               <BR>
License Unit     <BR>
524 S. 2nd Street, Room 210   <BR>
P. O. Box 19458                   <BR>
Springfield, IL 62794-9458            <BR>
(309) 968-7531                            <BR>
                                              </DD></DL><HR><H3>
III. Statute:                                                   </H3>
<DL><DD>
515 Illinois Compiled Statutes 5/20-90
        </DD></DL><H3>
Regulation:           </H3>
                           <DL><DD>
17 Illinois Administrative Code 870</DD></DL>
                                             <HR><H3>
IV.  Requirement Description:                        </H3>
                                                          <DL><DD>
A permit is required to breed, hatch, propagate or raise aquatic life species including, but not limited to, amphibians, reptiles, crustaceans, mussels, clams, gastropods, fish and aquatic plants.  

Permits are issued for one year, and are valid from February 1 of the year issued and expire the following January 31.
</DD></DL><HR><H3>
V.   Approval Process:</H3>
                           <DL><DD>
A permit will be issued by the Department upon receipt of a completed and signed Application for Aquaculture Permit, together with the necessary fees.  

Applications require approval by a Department biologist, which includes an inspection of proposed facilities if an application involves a species not named on the Department's "Aquatic Life Approved Species List".  

Applications may be denied (or consideration of an application may be postponed) if applicant has not provided sufficient information regarding risks associated with a species not named on the Department's "Aquatic Life Approved Species List".  In such instances, applicant may appeal the denial to the Chief of Fisheries.

The Department cautions applicants that no authority is granted to operate an aquaculture facility until a permit actually is issued.  The mere filing of an application or  possession of a canceled check representing payment of fees does not entitle a person to operate an aquaculture facility.

Typically, permits are issued approximately 2 to 3 weeks following receipt by the Department.
                                   </DD></DL><HR><H3>
VI.  Pre-Requisites, Co-Requisites & Post Requisites:</H3>
                                                          <DL><DD>
None.     </DD></DL><HR><H3>                                                        

VII. Fees:                  </H3>
                                 <DL><DD>
$50 annually.                            

Payment may be made by check, draft or money order payable to the Department of Natural Resources.
                                    </DD></DL>






<HR>
