<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>First Stop: Certification of Underground or Surface Coal Mine Personnel</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#004080" LINK="#004080" VLINK="#0080C0" ALINK="#0080C0">

<img src="/dcca/graph/fs/fslogosm.gif" alt="First Stop Logo" width=171 height=120 align=left>
<h3 align=center>Department of Commerce & Community Affairs
<hr>
First Stop Business Information Center<br>
Business Requirement
</h3>
<hr>
<br clear=all>

<H3>I.	Business Requirement Profile:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Certification of Underground or Surface Coal Mine Personnel
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>II.  Agency:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Illinois Department of Natural Resources<BR>
Office of Mines & Minerals  (OMM)<BR>
Mine Safety & Training Division<BR>
503 East Main Street<BR>
Benton, Illinois 62812<BR>
(618) 439-9111<BR>
TDD:  (217) 524-4626<BR>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>III. Statute:</H3>
<DL><DD>
225 Illinois Compiled Statutes 705/5, 6, 7 & 38 (Illinois Coal Mining Act)
</DD></DL>
<H3>Regulation:</H3>
<DL><DD>
62 Illinois Administrative Code 190
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>IV.	Requirement Description:</H3>
<DL><DD>
All mine personnel overseeing construction and mine operations must be certified by the Office of Mines & Minerals (OMM). No mine may begin operation without certified personnel. The purpose for certification is to ensure that coal mines have competent, qualified people.  <P>

Supervisory Certification is required for a surface mine. A Certified Surface Supervisor is required for strip mine operations, drilling and shooting operations, pit coal loading operations and reclamation work. (Certification is obtained separately for each task by passing an applicable exam.) <P>

During underground mine construction, Shaft-Slope Supervisor certification is required to oversee the construction of a shaft or slope entrance and for the Shaft-slope Examiner Certification is required to examine the construction areas of a shaft or slope. <P>

At Underground Mine Operations, certification is required for the Mine Manager overseeing the operations of the mine and the Mine Examiner inspecting the underground areas. <P>

All areas of a mine are required to be inspected. Other underground mine operations may require certifications, such as for use of explosives, shot firer, or hoisting miners in and out of a mine, hoisting engineer certification. OMM's Mine Safety and Training Division certifications  are permanent. <P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>V.  	Approval Process:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Applicants must file an "Application for Mine Examiner, Mine Manager, State Mine Inspector, Electrical Hoisting Engineer, Surface Mine Supervisor, Shaft & Slope Supervisor or Shaft & Slope Examiner", and pass a written exam.  <P>

Common reasons for denial include failure to have  required experience. Denied applications may be appealed to the Illinois State Mining Board. <P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>VI. 	Pre-Requisites, Co-Requisites & Post-Requisites:</H3>
<DL><DD>
<EM>Surface Supervisor:</EM>  Minimum of 2 years of surface mining experience.<P>

<EM>Shaft-Slope Supervisor:</EM>  At least 3 years underground experience in shaft, slope or underground construction, or holds an undergraduate degree in Mining or Civil Engineering with 18 months experience in shaft, slope or underground construction, and has a Certificate of Competency as a Shaft-Slope Examiner. <P>

<EM>Shaft- Slope Examiner: </EM> 2 years of shaft, slope or underground construction experience or an undergraduate degree with 1 year of experience in shaft, slope or underground construction, and evidence of completing a course in first aid. Mine Manager:  Minimum 23 years old, at least four years underground mining experience, has a "Certificate of Competency as Mine Examiner", completed a course in first aid and mine rescue. (Applicants with a degree in engineering or an approved 4 year program in coal mining technology from an accredited college or university are required to have only 2 years underground experience.) Applicants with a 2-year Associate's Degree in Applied Science or Coal Mining Technology are required to have 3 years underground experience.<P>

<EM>Mine Examiner: </EM> Requisites are the same as for a Mine Manager except that the applicant must be at least 21 years old and have a "First Class Certificate of Competency". <P>

<EM>Electrical Hoisting Engineer:</EM>  Must be 21 years old, have 2 years experience with electrical hoisting equipment or completed training course on the operation and maintenance of electrical hoisting equipment, or applicants must have completed a training course and perform 30 hours of electrical hoisting equipment operation under the supervision of a certified Electrical Hoisting Engineer.<P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>VII. Fees:</H3>
<DL><DD>
None.
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<STRONG>| <a href="/dcca/home.htm">DCCA Home Page</a> | <A HREF="/dcca/menus/fsm1.htm">First Stop</a> | <A HREF="/dcca/menus/fsbr.htm">Business Requirements</a> |</STRONG>

</BODY>
