<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>First Stop: License for Possession, Use, Purchase or Transfer of Explosive Materials</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#004080" LINK="#004080" VLINK="#0080C0" ALINK="#0080C0">

<img src="/dcca/graph/fs/fslogosm.gif" alt="First Stop Logo" width=171 height=120 align=left>
<h3 align=center>Department of Commerce & Community Affairs
<hr>
First Stop Business Information Center<br>
Business Requirement
</h3>
<hr>
<br clear=all>

<H3>I.	Business Requirement Profile:</H3>
<DL><DD>
License for Possession, Use, Purchase or Transfer of Explosive Materials
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>II.	Agency:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Illinois Department of Natural Resources<BR>
Office of Mines and Minerals<BR>
Explosives Division<BR>
503 East Main Street<BR>
Benton, Illinois 62812<BR>
(618) 439-4320<BR>
TDD: (217) 524-4626 <BR>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>III. Statute:</H3>
<DL><DD>
225 Illinois Compiled Statutes 2/2000-2011 (Illinois Explosives Act)
</DD></DL>
<H3>Regulation:</H3>
<DL><DD>
62 Illinois Administrative Code 200.100-108
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>IV. 	Requirement Description:</H3>
<DL><DD>
A license is required to handle explosive materials.<P>

The purpose of licensing is to ensure that an individual is knowledgeable in the use and handling of explosive materials. <P>

Licensure is intended for those who will use small quantities of explosives within a specific timeframe.<P>

Businesses such as construction companies, quarries or mines are not required to have persons with explosives licenses if the business has a current explosive storage certificate. If the company or business, is not exempt, however, then a licensed person is required. <P>

If a license holder fails to comply with or satisfy the requirements of any provision of the Act or its rules and regulations, the Department may refuse to issue or renew a license or may take any other appropriate disciplinary action, including imposing fines. <P>

Licenses are valid for 3 years. the The Office of Mines & Minerals (OMM) also issues temporary licenses which remain effective for no more than 3 months. <P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>V.  	Approval Process:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Applicants must submit an "Explosives License Application" and be fingerprinted. Fingerprints must be on file prior to issuance of the license.<P>

Failure to provide all information/documents will result in the rejection of the application. If rejected, OMM provides a written list of additional materials needed. A license will also be denied if the individual fails a background check or fails to pass the written exam which is given by the Explosives Unit Inspector. <P>

A temporary license may be issued to any non-Illinois resident who intends to possess, use, purchase or transfer explosive materials in Illinois on a limited basis. Applications for this temporary license requires the same information as for an state resident.<P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>VI.  Pre-Requisites, Co-Requisites & Post-Requisites:</H3>
<DL><DD>
None.
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>VII. Fees:  </H3>
<DL><DD>
	Fingerprinting 	$36<BR>
	License 			$75<BR>
	Temporary License 	$75<BR>
	Re-examination		$25<BR>
	License renewal	$75<BR>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
