<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>First Stop: Nursing Home Administrator License, Temporary Nursing Home Administrator License and Continuing Education Sponsor </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#004080" LINK="#004080" VLINK="#0080C0" ALINK="#0080C0">

<img src="/dcca/graph/fs/fslogosm.gif" alt="First Stop Logo" width=171 height=120 align=left>
<h3 align=center>Department of Commerce & Community Affairs
<hr>
First Stop Business Information Center<br>
Business Requirement
</h3>
<hr>
<br clear=all>

<H3>I. 	Business Requirement Profile:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Nursing Home Administrator License, Temporary Nursing Home Administrator License and Continuing Education Sponsor 
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>II. 	Agency:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Department of Professional Regulation<BR>
Licensing & Testing Division<BR>
Health Services Section<BR>
320 West Washington, 3rd Floor<BR>
Springfield, Illinois 62786<BR>
(217) 524-7540<BR>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>III. Statute:</H3>
<DL><DD>
225 Illinois Compiled Statutes 70/1-37
</DD></DL>
<H3>Regulation:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Title 68 Illinois Administrative Code, Chapter VII, Subchapter b, Part 1310
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>IV. 	Requirement Description:</H3>
<DL><DD>
A License is required for Nursing Home Administrators who plan, organize, direct or supervise the operation of a Nursing Home (facilities licensed by the Illinois Department of Public Health under the Illinois Nursing Home Care Act). <P>

The Department may issue a one year Temporary License  as a nursing home administrator in its discretion, without an examination, if the applicant provides satisfactory proof that the candidate has satisfied the qualifications.<P>

Practicing without a license is a Class A misdemeanor for the first offense and a Class 4 felony for subsequent violations.<P>

The Department also certifies Continuing Education Sponsors for Nursing Home Administrators. Continuing Education Sponsors provide a course of instruction for individuals whose  Nursing Home Administrator license has expired. The Department determines how many hours of continuing education is required, based on how long a license has been expired. Anyone sponsoring a continuing education course in nursing home administration must receive approval from the Department.<P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>V.  	Approval Process:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Applicants should contact the Department to request an application. All applicants are required to pass a written examination. The exam is open to all applicants with a baccalaureate degree from an accredited college or university. <P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>VI. 	Pre-Requisites, Co-Requisites & Post-Requisites:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Applicants must be at least 21 years of age and be a  U.S. citizen. Also, applicants must have a bachelors degree, from an accredited  college or university or have completed a course of instruction, approved by the Department, including topics related to the operations of a nursing home facility. In some cases, the Department will allow a combination of education and work experience to satisfy the education requirements. <P>

To renew a license, 36 hours of continuing education is required in the past two years.<P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>VII. Fees:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Nursing Home Administrator License: 	$100<P>
Temporary License:				$75<P>
Continuing Education Sponsor		$500<P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<STRONG>| <a href="/dcca/home.htm">DCCA Home Page</a> | <A HREF="/dcca/menus/fsm1.htm">First Stop</a> | <A HREF="/dcca/menus/fsbr.htm">Business Requirements</a> |</STRONG>

</BODY>
</HTML>
