<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>First Stop: Order For Withholding Wages For Child Support</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#004080" LINK="#004080" VLINK="#0080C0" ALINK="#0080C0">

<img src="/dcca/graph/fs/fslogosm.gif" alt="First Stop Logo" width=171 height=120 align=left>
<h3 align=center>Department of Commerce & Community Affairs
<hr>
First Stop Business Information Center<br>
Business Requirement
</h3>
<hr>
<br clear=all>
<H3>I. Business Requirement Profile:</H3><dl><dd>

Order For Withholding Wages For Child Support</dd></dl><hr>

<H3>II. Agency:</H3>
<dl><dd>
Illinois Department of Public Aid <BR>
Child Support Enforcement Division<BR>
<pre>
For State Wide Assistance:           For Cook County Assistance:
Employer Verification Unit           Income Withholding Unit
PO Box 19405                         32 West Randolph Street, Room 700
Springfield, Illinois 62794-9405     Chicago, Illinois 60601
Voice: 217-782-1380                  Voice: 312-793-3289
TDD:  217-524-3148                   TDD:  312-917-1580
</pre></dd></dl><hr>
<H3>III.   Statute:</H3>
<dl><dd>
750 Illinois Compiled Statutes 5/706.1 (Illinois Marriage and Dissolution of Marriage Act)<BR>

750 Illinois Compiled Statutes 15/4.1 (Non-Support of Spouse and Children Act)<BR>

750 Illinois Compiled Statutes 20/26.1 (Rev. Uniform Reciprocal Enforcement of Support Act)<BR>

750 Illinois Compiled Statutes 45/20 (Illinois Parentage Act of 1984)<BR>

305 Illinois Compiled Statutes 5/10 - 16.2 (Illinois Public Aid Code)<BR></dd></dl><hr>

<H3>IV.Requirement Description:</H3>
<dl><dd>
Federal and state law require judges in domestic relations cases to order employers to withhold a portion of an employee's income for payment of child support. Whenever an Order for support is entered, a separate Order for Withholding must be entered also. The Order for Withholding is served on the employer immediately unless the parties agree and an alternative arrangement that insures payment of support is secured. An employer may not fire, discipline, deny employment or otherwise penalize an employee because he or she is subject to an Order for Withholding. Employers have 10 days after being served with the Order to comply. Non-compliance with the Order may result in a fine on the employer of $100 per day plus payment of the amount of the order.
</dd></dl><hr>
<H3>V. Approval Process:
</H3><dl><dd>
Illinois courts, the Illinois Department of Public Aid (IDPA), or administrative agency or court of another state may issue a Support Order and an Order for Withholding and have it served on an employer. Upon receipt of a Support Order and an Order for Withholding from another state, an Illinois employer must treat it as if it had been issued by an Illinois tribunal, provide a copy of the order to the employee, and distribute the funds as directed in the order.<P>

The employer may withhold from the employee's pay the amount(s) stated in the Order, but not more than the limit allowed by the Federal Consumer Credit Protection Act (FCCPA). Some Orders will state that the employer must enroll minor children as beneficiaries in the company's health insurance plan. The employer must send withheld child support amount(s) to the Clerk of the Circuit Court, the IDPA, the court or administrative agency of another state and/or the child's custodial parent, as directed in the Order. The withheld insurance premium is sent to the insurance carrier.<P></dd></dl><hr>

<H3>VI. Pre-Requisites, Co-Requisites & Post Requisites:</H3>
<dl><dd>
In cases where insurance coverage is mandated, employers must notify the custodial parent, IDPA, or the court or administrative agency of another state, of the date when coverage begins, information on the dependent coverage plan and all necessary claim forms within 15 days of enrollment (or upon request).  Employers must notify the office that served the Order when an employee is no longer employed. If available, employers must provide a new address, name of a new employer and other information that may be necessary to continue the withholding process. If health coverage is terminated or changed for any reason, the employer must notify the custodial parent, the IDPA, or the court or administrative agency of another state of the change and any conversion privileges within 10 days of the change date. For each deduction, the employer must provide the Clerk of the Circuit Court, the IDPA in direct pay cases, or the court or administrative agency of another state with the date the employee was paid. The employer must pay the amount withheld to the custodial parent, IDPA, the Clerk of the Circuit Court, or the court or administrative agency of another state in accordance with the court's Order or Administrative Order for Withholding, within 10 calendar days of the date the employee is paid.<p></dd></dl><hr>

<H3>VII. Fees:</H3>
<dl><dd>
An employer can deduct a fee of up to $5 per month for each Order for Withholding. The fee is to be deducted from the employee's remaining pay (wages excluding the amount withheld). This fee must be within the limits of the Federal Consumer Credit Protection Act.
</dd></dl>







