<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>First Stop: Certificate of Approval for the Microbiological Analyses of Milk</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#004080" LINK="#004080" VLINK="#0080C0" ALINK="#0080C0">

<img src="/dcca/graph/fs/fslogosm.gif" alt="First Stop Logo" width=171 height=120 align=left>
<h3 align=center>Department of Commerce & Community Affairs
<hr>
First Stop Business Information Center<br>
Business Requirement
</h3>
<hr>
<br clear=all>

<H3>I.  Business Requirement Profile:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Certificate of Approval for the Microbiological Analyses of Milk
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>II.  Agency:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Illinois Department of Public Health<BR>
Office of Health Protection / Division of Laboratories <BR>
825 North Rutledge<BR>
Springfield, IL 62794<BR>
(217) 782-6562<BR>
TDD:  1-800-547-0466 (for hearing impaired use only)<BR>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>III.  Statute:</H3>
<DL><DD>
20 Illinois Compiled Statutes 2310/55.10; 2310/55.11
</DD></DL>
<H3>Regulation:</H3>
<DL><DD>
77 Illinois Administrative Code 463 (Standards for Approval of Milk Laboratories)
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>IV.  Requirement Description:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Laboratories performing microbiological analysis of milk may have a Certificate of Approval from the Department acting under the authority of the US Food & Drug Administration (USFDA). Certificates are granted on the basis of a  laboratory's facilities, quality control records, equipment and the performance of the analysts. This requirement applies to laboratories at dairies, commercial milk laboratories, and health departments.<P> 

Certificates name the analysts who have demonstrated the ability to properly perform representative test procedures with which they are involved while under observation of the certification officer. Each new analyst must meet the certification requirements and demonstrate competency prior to performing milk tests.<P> 

Violations may result in a 60 day suspension from testing all milk products subject to rules under the Grade A Pasteurized Milk Ordinance.<P> 

Department evaluations of facilities and all analysts are given every 2 years.<P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>V.  Approval Process:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Applicants must submit an "Application for Milk/Dairy Microbiological Laboratories under USFDA/IMS Regulations" with personnel and Laboratory information forms.<P> 

Following a Department review an on-site evaluation is scheduled. Applicants either must pass the evaluation or employ analysts who accurately test a set of split milk samples from the Department before being conditionally certified to test milk samples. Full certification is granted when the split milk samples and the evaluation are successfully completed.  The Department schedules another  on-site evaluation before the expiration date of the Certificate.<P> 

The most common reason for denial of Certification is the inability of the analyst to correctly perform the procedures during the on-site evaluation, failure to properly analyze split milk samples, malfunctioning equipment, or inadequate records.<P> 

Applicants may reapply after 60 days, once the deficiencies from the original evaluation have been corrected. Upon certification, certificate holders are given a guidebook on the USFDA's statutes and regulations which must be followed.<P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>VI.  Pre-Requisites, Co-Requisites & Post-Requisites:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Laboratory supervisors must have a minimum of a Bachelor's Degree in microbiology, biology, chemistry, or a closely related field. Laboratory analysts must have a minimum of 6 months bench experience in a microbiological analytical laboratory.  Analysts must be under the direct supervision of the laboratory supervisor. 
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>VII.  Fees:</H3>
<DL><DD>
None.
</DD></DL>


<HR>
<STRONG>| <a href="/dcca/home.htm">DCCA Home Page</a> | <A HREF="/dcca/menus/fsm1.htm">First Stop</a> | <A HREF="/dcca/menus/fsbr.htm">Business Requirements</a> |</STRONG>

</BODY>
</HTML>
