<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>First Stop: Lead Abatement Contractor's License</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#004080" LINK="#004080" VLINK="#0080C0" ALINK="#0080C0">

<img src="/dcca/graph/fs/fslogosm.gif" alt="First Stop Logo" width=171 height=120 align=left>
<h3 align=center>Department of Commerce & Community Affairs
<hr>
First Stop Business Information Center<br>
Business Requirement
</h3>
<hr>
<br clear=all>

<H3>I.  Business Requirement Profile:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Lead Abatement Contractor's License
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>II.  Agency:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Illinois Department of Public Health<BR>
Office of Health Protection<BR>
Division of Environmental Health / Lead Abatement Program<BR>
525 West Jefferson<BR>
Springfield, IL 62761<BR>
(217) 782-5830<BR>
TDD:  1-800-547-0466 (for hearing impaired use only)<BR>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>III.  Statute:</H3>
<DL><DD>
410 Illinois Compiled Statutes 45/1 et seq. (Lead Poisoning Prevention Act)
</DD></DL>
<H3>Regulation:</H3>
<DL><DD>
77 Illinois Administrative Code 845 (Lead Poisoning Prevention Code)
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>IV.  Requirement Description:</H3>
<DL><DD>
A License is required to contract and conduct lead mitigation activities in dwellings and day care facilities. Mitigation activities requiring a license include the destruction or disturbance of any leaded surface. These services must be conducted by  licensed lead abatement workers under supervision of a licensed lead abatement contractor/supervisor. Providing these services without a license, is a Class A misdemeanor.<P> 

Licenses are valid for one year, and expire May 31.<P> 

Licenses that have been expired for 3 years or less may be reinstated upon application.  Licenses expired for more than 3 years are not eligible for reinstatement, but require a new application.<P> 
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>V.  Approval Process:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Applicants must submit an application to become a licensed lead abatement contractor together with other information including a certificate of financial responsibility documenting liability insurance, a letter of credit or bond (minimum $250,000), a copy of a valid Lead Abatement Contractor/Supervisor's License issued to the contractor or the name of a Lead Abatement Contractor/Supervisor employed by the contractor, the contractor's written statement that only licensed lead workers will be employed, a copy of the contractor's written standard operating procedures and employee protection plans, which include specific reference to medical monitoring and respirator training programs as required in OSHA regulations at 29 CFR 1910.1001 and 29 CFR 1926.62 (1993), and; a description detailing all legal proceedings, lawsuits or claims which have been filed or levied against the contractor or any of his past or present employees or companies in regard to construction related activities. Applicants licensed or certified as Lead Abatement Contractor in another state may request reciprocal licensure. IDPH evaluates the requirements for licensure in the other state and issues a license if IDPH determines that the requirements for licensure in the other state are equal to the requirements for licensure in Illinois. If an application to become licensed is denied, the applicant may attempt to correct any deficiencies found in the application and then reapply. To renew a contractor license, applicants must submit an application and a certificate of completion of an Illinois-approved refresher Lead Abatement Contractor/Supervisor 8-hour (1 day) course that is issued to the contractor or a contractor/supervisor employed by the contractor. The average  processing time for the contractor license is approximately 1 week. The most common reason for denial of the license application is missing or incorrect information provided with the application. 
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>VI.   Pre-Requisites, Co-Requisites & Post-Requisites:  Co-Requisite:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Information submitted with the initial application must be kept current or updated where necessary. A current certificate of insurance shall be on file with IDPH at all times. Post-requisite: The contractor shall notify IDPH of any change in the status of the insurance certificate which has been filed, including expiration, renewal, or alteration of the terms of the certificate. 
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>VII.   Fees:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Applicants must submit to IDPH, a non-refundable fee of $500 for a Lead Abatement Contractor license. Out-of-state applicants who request a reciprocal license must submit a non-refundable fee of $250, plus an additional $500 non-refundable license fee. The annual non-refundable renewal fee for a lead abatement contractor licensure is $500. If a renewal application is received after April 30, the applicant must pay a non-refundable late fee of $100 in addition to the renewal fee of $500. Reinstated licenses are $100 plus all lapsed license fees.
</DD></DL>

<HR>
