<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>First Stop: Lead Inspector's License</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#004080" LINK="#004080" VLINK="#0080C0" ALINK="#0080C0">

<img src="/dcca/graph/fs/fslogosm.gif" alt="First Stop Logo" width=171 height=120 align=left>
<h3 align=center>Department of Commerce & Community Affairs
<hr>
First Stop Business Information Center<br>
Business Requirement
</h3>
<hr>
<br clear=all>

<H3>I.    Business Requirement Profile:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Lead Inspector's License
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>II.   Agency:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Illinois Department of Public Health<BR>
Office of Health Protection<BR>
Division of Environmental Health / Lead Abatement Program<BR>
525 West Jefferson St.<BR>
Springfield, IL 62761<BR>
(217) 782-5830<BR>
TDD: 1-800-547-0466 (for hearing impaired use only)<BR>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>III.  Statute:</H3>
<DL><DD>
410 Illinois Compiled Statutes 45/1 et seq. (Lead Poisoning Prevention Act)
</DD></DL>
<H3>Regulation:</H3>
<DL><DD>
77 Illinois Administrative Code 845.28 (Lead Poisoning Prevention Code)
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>IV.  Requirement Description:</H3>
<DL><DD>
A License is required to act as a Lead Inspector, whether working for the Department or the private sector. (Department personnel inspect dwellings where a child has been identified to have an elevated blood lead level. Private Lead Inspectors may perform such inspections, however, their primary activity consists of identifying lead bearing substances in dwellings, day care facilities, and commercial buildings.)<P> 

Conducting lead inspections without a license is a Class A misdemeanor.<P>  

Licenses expire January 31 of each year. Licenses that have been expired for more than 2 years may be restored by passing a Department approved lead inspection training course.<P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>V.  Approval Process:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Applicants must file an application to become a licensed lead inspector, together with a certificate demonstrating completion of an approved lead inspector 3-day course. Applicants licensed or certified in another state may request a reciprocal license. (The Department will issue a reciprocal license if the other state's requirements are equal or greater than Illinois's.)<P> 

The Department may issue licenses with restrictions based on safety precautions or inspection methods.<P> 

The average processing time for a private Lead Inspector License application is 3 to 4 days.<P>

The most common reason for denial of an application is incomplete or incorrect information (such as failure to provide a copy of a course certificate, or an instructor for requisite training was not approved by the Department).<P>

Applicants may reapply after correcting any deficiency.<P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>VI.  Pre-Requisites, Co-Requisites & Post-Requisites:</H3>
<DL><DD>
To renew a license Lead Inspectors must take an 8-hour (1 day) Department approved Lead Inspector annual refresher course.
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>VII.  Fees:</H3>
<DL><DD>
<STRONG>Lead Inspector License annual fee:</STRONG> $100.<P>

<STRONG>Renewal fee for Lead Inspector License:</STRONG> $100.<P>

(The Department and local health department employees are exempt from the fee if the license is for work conducted in line with their duties at the health department.)<P>

<STRONG>Reinstatement of lapsed license additional fee:</STRONG> $15.<P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
