<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>First Stop: I.  Permit to construct new Campground/Recreational Areas/ II.  License to Operate a Campground.</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#004080" LINK="#004080" VLINK="#0080C0" ALINK="#0080C0">

<img src="/dcca/graph/fs/fslogosm.gif" alt="First Stop Logo" width=171 height=120 align=left>
<h3 align=center>Department of Commerce & Community Affairs
<hr>
First Stop Business Information Center<br>
Business Requirement
</h3>
<hr>
<br clear=all>

<H3>I.  Business Requirement Profile: </H3>
<DL><DD>
I.  Permit to construct new Campground/Recreational Areas<P>
II.  License to Operate a Campground.<P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>II.   Agency:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Illinois Department of Public Health<BR>
Division of Environmental Health / Office of Health Protection<BR>
Campground Program<BR>
525 West Jefferson St.<BR>
Springfield, IL 62761<BR>
(217) 782-5830<BR>   
TDD:  1-800-547-0466 (for hearing impaired use only)<BR>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>III.  Statute:</H3>
<DL><DD>
210 Illinois Compiled Statutes 95/1-32 (Campground Licensing & Recreational Area Act)
</DD></DL>
<H3>Regulation:</H3>
<DL><DD>
77 Illinois Administrative Code 800 (Recreational Area Code)
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>IV.  Requirement Description:</H3>
<DL><DD>
I. A permit is required to construct a new campground or expand an existing campground (by constructing a sewage system, swimming facility, food service establishment, etc.).<P> 

II. An annual license is required to operate a campground with 3 or more camp sites that is open 6 or more days a year. Licenses must be renewed yearly.<P> 

Failure to comply with these requirements is a Class B misdemeanor.<P>

(Recreational areas other than campgrounds must meet minimum sanitation & safety standard requirements described in the Recreational Area Code, but do not have to be licensed.   Campgrounds located in Home Rule Units are exempt from the requirements of this law.<P> 
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>V.  Approval Process:</H3>
<DL><DD>
I. A construction permit is required before construction may begin on a new campground or expansion of an existing campground.  An application must be filed with the Department together with plans for a the new campground or expansion of the existing campground.  Permit applications are usually reviewed within 2 weeks of receipt.  
After the permit is granted, the Department will inspect the campground to determine compliance with the Code. 

II. Applicants to operate a campground with 3 or more camp sites that is open 6 or more days a year must file an application for licensure of a campground or a renewal application in the case of an existing facility. Applications are processed in 2 weeks. 
</DD></DL>
 
<HR>
<H3>VI.  Pre-Requisites, Co-Requisites & Post-Requisites:</H3>  
<DL><DD>
Post-Requisite:  Licensees are responsible for reporting to the Department any deaths or injuries which require a physician's care that occur at the campground.
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>VII.  Fees:</H3>
<DL><DD>
<STRONG>I.   Application fee for a Campground Construction Permit:</STRONG>  $100<P>
   
<STRONG>II. Annual campground license fee:</STRONG>  $100<P>

Late fee (if the license renewal application is not submitted by February 1):  $50 Not-for-profit organizations are exempted from these fees if they submit a copy of the current annual report to the Illinois Secretary of State.  Governmental entities are also exempt from all fees.<P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<STRONG>| <a href="/dcca/home.htm">DCCA Home Page</a> | <A HREF="/dcca/menus/fsm1.htm">First Stop</a> | <A HREF="/dcca/menus/fsbr.htm">Business Requirements</a> |</STRONG>

</BODY>
