<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>First Stop: Residences for Persons with HIV Disease</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#004080" LINK="#004080" VLINK="#0080C0" ALINK="#0080C0">

<img src="/dcca/graph/fs/fslogosm.gif" alt="First Stop Logo" width=171 height=120 align=left>
<h3 align=center>Department of Commerce & Community Affairs
<hr>
First Stop Business Information Center<br>
Business Requirement
</h3>
<hr>
<br clear=all>

<H3>I.     Business Requirement Profile:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Residences for Persons with HIV Disease
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>II.    Agency:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Illinois Department of Public Health<BR>
Office of Health Care Regulation / Bureau of Long-Term Care<BR>
535 West Jefferson<BR>
Springfield, IL 62761<BR>
(217) 782-2913<BR>
TDD:  1-800-547-0466 (for hearing impaired use only)<BR>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>III.   Statute:</H3>
<DL><DD>
210 Illinois Compiled Statutes 65 (Supportive Residences Licensing Act )
</DD></DL>
<H3>Regulation:</H3>
<DL><DD>
77 Illinois Administrative Code 385 (Supportive Residences Licensing Code)
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>IV.   Requirement Description:</H3>
<DL><DD>
A license is required to open, establish, operate or maintain a residential facility for persons with HIV disease. License requirements involve matters such as administration and policies, disaster preparedness, case management, client rights, medication policies and procedures, meal service, and physical plant.<P> 

Licenses are valid for 1 year.<P> 

License holders failing to comply with the Act are subject to an administrative hearing or license revocation.<P> 

Unlicensed persons violating this Act are subject to prosecution for civil or criminal penalties by the Attorney General.<P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>V.    Approval Process:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Applicants must file with the Department a "Supportive Residence License Application", a statement of ownership, the locations of proposed facilities and the name of the manager; and a financial statement.<P>  

Applications usually take 1 month to process.<P> 

If an application package is denied, the applicant may correct any deficiencies and reapply. Inspections may occur as IDPH deems appropriate.<P> 

An application may be denied or a license may be revoked if the applicant, licensee or manager has a disreputable moral character (that is, if he/she has been convicted of a felony or of Medicaid or Medicare fraud, etc.), if the applicant or licensee submits false information, if the licensee refuses to allow an inspection or if the licensee violates the Act or the rules.<P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>VI.   Pre-Requisites, Co-Requisites & Post-Requisites:</H3>
<DL><DD>
None.
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>VII.  Fees:</H3>
<DL><DD>
None.
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<STRONG>| <a href="/dcca/home.htm">DCCA Home Page</a> | <A HREF="/dcca/menus/fsm1.htm">First Stop</a> | <A HREF="/dcca/menus/fsbr.htm">Business Requirements</a> |</STRONG>

</BODY>
</HTML>
