<HEAD><TITLE>First Stop: Motor Fuel Licensing</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#004080" LINK="#004080" VLINK="#0080C0" ALINK="#0080C0">

<img src="/dcca/graph/fs/fslogosm.gif" alt="First Stop Logo" width=171 height=120 align=left>
<h3 align=center>Department of Commerce & Community Affairs
<hr>
First Stop Business Information Center<br>
Business Requirement
</h3>
<hr>
<br clear=all>

<H3>I.	Business Requirement Profile:	</H3>
<DL><DD>Motor Fuel Licensing</DD></DL>
<HR>
<H3>II.	Agency:</H3>
<DL><DD><PRE>Illinois Department of Revenue     Motor Fuel Use Tax (217) 785-1397
Taxpayer Services Bureau           M.F. Review & Corr.	(217) 782-2291
Motor Fuel Division	           Motor Fuel Refunds	(217) 782-7797
101 West Jefferson St.	           Motor Fuel Licensing (217) 785-6593
Springfield, IL 62794</PRE></DD></DL>
<HR>
<H3>III.	Statute:  </H3>
<DL><DD>35 Illinois Compiled Statutes 505. (Motor Fuel Tax Law)</DD></DL>
<HR>
<H3>IV.	Requirement Description:  </H3>
<DL><DD><P>Any person acting as a distributor, supplier, receiver or bulk user of motor fuel in Illinois must apply for and obtain a Motor Fuel License from the Department. A Distributor, is someone involved in one or more of the following:  Has 30,000 gallons of active bulk gasoline storage capacity.  Produces, refines or blends motor fuel.  Compounds or manufactures motor fuel in this state.  Transports motor fuel into Illinois. A Supplier is someone involved in one or both of the following:  Distribution of Special Fuel by tank car or tank truck.  Transports motor fuel into Illinois.

<P>A Receiver is someone involved in one or more of the following:  Has 30,000 gallons of active bulk fuel storage capacity, Produces, refines or blends motor fuel, Compounds or manufactures motor fuel in this State.  Transports fuel into this State.  Exports fuel from this State.  A Bulk User is someone who owns:  Diesel powered highway vehicles, and owns, controls, or operates non-highway storage facilities into which tax free special fuel is delivered.</DD></DL>
<HR>
<H3>V.	Approval Process: </H3>
<DL><DD>Applicants for a Licensed Bulk User License must complete and file form RMFT-64, which authorizes the tax-free purchase of special fuel.  Applicants for a Distributor, Supplier or Receiver License must complete and file form RMFT-2.  The average processing time to issue these licenses approximately two months.  Applicants also must file a bond, or provide surety acceptable to the Department.  Common reasons for denial include:  Failure to complete and/or sign the application.</DD></DL>
<HR>
<H3>VI.	Pre-Requisites, Co-Requisites & Post-Requisites:  </H3>
<DL><DD>An applicant must have an Illinois Business Tax Number (IBT#) to be licensed to sell fuel in Illinois.  Applicant corporations must be registered with the Illinois Secretary of State.  Applicants must have no outstanding or unpaid tax assessments in Illinois or base state.  Applicants must file a bond or surety.</DD></DL>
<HR>
<H3>VII.	Fees:  </H3>
<DL><DD>There are no fees for licensing.</DD></DL>

<HR>
<STRONG>| <a href="/dcca/home.htm">DCCA Home Page</a> | <A HREF="/dcca/menus/fsm1.htm">First Stop</a> | <A HREF="/dcca/menus/fsbr.htm">Business Requirements</a> |</STRONG>

</BODY>
