<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>First Stop: Formation and Registration of Corporations</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#004080" LINK="#004080" VLINK="#0080C0" ALINK="#0080C0">

<img src="/dcca/graph/fs/fslogosm.gif" alt="First Stop Logo" width=171 height=120 align=left>
<h3 align=center>Department of Commerce & Community Affairs
<hr>
First Stop Business Information Center<br>
Business Requirement
</h3>
<hr>
<br clear=all>

<H3>I.	Business Requirement Profile:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Formation and Registration of Corporations
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>II.	Agency:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Secretary of State<BR>
Department of Business Services / Corporation Division<BR>
Room 328 Howlett Office Building<BR>
Springfield, IL 62756<BR>
(217) 782-6961<BR>
TDD:	(800) 252-2904 or (217) 524-1137 (hearing impaired use only)<BR>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>III. Statute:</H3>
<DL><DD>
805 Illinois Compiled Statutes 5 & 105
</DD></DL>
<H3>Regulation:</H3>
<DL><DD>
14 Illinois Administrative Code, Subtitle A, I / 150 & 160
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>IV.	Requirement Description:</H3>
<DL><DD>
To form a domestic corporation or register a foreign corporation to transact business in Illinois, an application must be completed. Foreign corporations must also submit additional documentation. Foreign corporations transacting business in Illinois without registering are subject to monetary penalties. Corporations must inform the Secretary of State regarding changing the name, the corporate purpose, registered agent/office, authorized or issued shares or paid-in capital. If the corporate name is not available or the corporation wishes to do business under a name other than its true corporate name, it may file an application to adopt an assumed name. Corporations are perpetually effective, unless otherwise stated in the Articles.<P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>V.	Approval Process:</H3>
<DL><DD>
To form a domestic corporation, Articles of Incorporation (Form BCA 2.10 for a business corporation and NFP 102.10 for a not for profit corporation) must be completed in duplicate and submitted to the Secretary of State. A foreign corporation seeking to transact business in Illinois must submit an Application for Certificate of Authority (Form BCA 13.15 for a business corporation and NFP 113.15 for a not for profit corporation) in duplicate together with a certified copy of the Articles of Incorporation and all amendments appropriately certified. Articles and applications are usually processed in 3-5 working days. Applications may be denied for non-compliance with the Act. Denied applications may be corrected and resubmitted for approval.<P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>VI.	Pre-Requisites, Co-Requisites & Post-Requisites:</H3>
<DL><DD>
<EM>Pre-Requisite:</EM> Applicants must appoint and maintain a registered agent.<P>

<EM>Co-Requisite:</EM> To remain in good standing, corporations must file an annual report and pay a franchise tax based on the Illinois portion of the corporation's paid-in capital. If an annual report is not filed, the corporation will be dissolved or the certificate revoked.<P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>VII.	Fees:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Applicants should consult the Secretary of State for information on registration fees. Franchise taxes vary according to the amount of paid-in capital, although the minimum tax is $25 and the maximum is $1,000,000.<P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<STRONG>| <a href="/dcca/home.htm">DCCA Home Page</a> | <A HREF="/dcca/menus/fsm1.htm">First Stop</a> | <A HREF="/dcca/menus/fsbr.htm">Business Requirements</a> |</STRONG>

</BODY>
</HTML>
