<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>First Stop: Vehicle Safety Inspection Testing Station  (IVSIP) Certificate.</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#004080" LINK="#004080" VLINK="#0080C0" ALINK="#0080C0">

<img src="/dcca/graph/fs/fslogosm.gif" alt="First Stop Logo" width=171 height=120 align=left>
<h3 align=center>Department of Commerce & Community Affairs
<hr>
First Stop Business Information Center<br>
Business Requirement
</h3>
<hr>
<br clear=all>

<H3>I.   Business Requirement Profile:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Vehicle Safety Inspection Testing Station  (IVSIP) Certificate.
</DD></DL>
	
<HR>		
<H3>II.  Agency:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Illinois Department of Transportation<BR>
Division of Traffic Safety<BR>
3215 Executive Park Drive<BR>
Springfield, IL 62703<BR>
(217) 785-1181<BR>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>III. Statute:</H3>
<DL><DD>
625 Illinois Compiled Statutes 5/Section 13-100.
</DD></DL>
<H3>Regulation:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Title 92 Illinois Administrative Code  Part 451.
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>IV. Requirement Description:</H3>
<DL><DD>
The purpose of the Illinois Vehicle Safety Inspection Program (IVSIP) is to test all second division vehicles with a gross weight of over 8,000 lbs.,  trailers with a gross weight of over 5,000 lbs., school bus, religious organization buses, pole trailers, ambulances, tow trucks and limousines for certain mechanical and structural integrity ensuring safe vehicles on the highways of Illinois.  Certification allows individuals or business entities in private enterprise to receive monetary compensation for conducting vehicle inspections.<P>

Conducting inspections without a Certificate is a petty offense and subject to a fine of $5 to $100 for a first offense, $25 to $200 for a second offense, and $100 to 300 for the third offense.<P>

Certification is valid for one year and may be renewed.<P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>V.  Approval Process:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Applicants must file an application consisting of a completed personal history questionnaire, photographs of the building and all entrances, all necessary equipment needed to conduct the inspections (brake testing machine, side-slip indicator, floor jack), an insurance bond and identification of all proficiency-tested and certified individuals wishing to conduct the inspections.<P>

Applications, proposed building sites and all equipment are inspected by Department personnel who also administer a written exam and proficiency test to those wishing to become testers.<P>  

The approval process depends upon the timely manner in which the applicant submits all required items and how quickly they become familiar and proficient with the rules, policies and procedures.  Generally, this takes about one month, but can vary depending on many things including how quickly the applicant completes the paperwork, passes the test, and properly prepares the premises. The most common reasons that applications are denied are building restrictions, inoperable testing equipment or lack of proficiency on the part of testers.<P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>VI. Pre-Requisites, Co-Requisites & Post-Requisites:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Testers must possess a valid drivers license for the state in which he/she legally resides.<P>

Owners are responsible for the timely submittal of required paperwork and for the upkeep and maintenance of the testing equipment.<P>

Certificates of Safety are affixed to all vehicles successfully completing the inspection and owners must have a sufficient inventory on-hand for each type of vehicle tested.<P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>VII. Fees:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Certificate of Safety:  $1.00/per certificate.
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<STRONG>| <a href="/dcca/home.htm">DCCA Home Page</a> | <A HREF="/dcca/menus/fsm1.htm">First Stop</a> | <A HREF="/dcca/menus/fsbr.htm">Business Requirements</a> |</STRONG>

</BODY>
</HTML>
