<HEAD><TITLE>DCCA: News Release -- November 8, 1996</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#8080C0" ALINK="#8080C0">

<img src="/dcca/graph/logosm.jpg" alt="DCCA Logo" width=165 height=82 align=left>
<img src="/dcca/graph/cbar.gif" width=410 height=4><p>
<h3>
Department of Commerce & Community Affairs<p>
</h3>
<img src="/dcca/graph/cbar.gif" width=410 height=4><p>
<font size=+3>1996 News Releases</font>
<br clear=right>
<hr>
<h3 align=center>
November 8, 1996<p>
Governor Awards $41.5 Million in Grants to Improve Public Infrastructure in 157 Communities Throughout Illinois
</h3>

<strong>SPRINGFIELD, IL</strong> -- Gov. Jim Edgar today awarded grants worth $41.5 million to help 157 Illinois communities improve and expand public water and sewer systems to meet the demands of economic growth while protecting the state's environment.<p>

"If Illinois communities are to thrive and grow, they must have adequate and safe water and wastewater treatment systems," the Governor said.  "Through the Community Development Assistance Program, smaller communities throughout Illinois can get the help they need to pay for costly improvements to public infrastructure, a financial challenge that few smaller communities can meet on their own.<p>

"Beyond demands of economic growth, improved water and sewer systems also are crucial to protecting the Illinois environment and the health and safety of Illinois residents.  We want to help Illinois communities build a brighter economic and environmental future."<p>

CDAP grants are available to most Illinois communities with populations of 50,000 or less.  The grants are administered by the Department of Commerce and Community Affairs (DCCA).<p>

The Governor pointed to projects in Hillsboro and Carthage as examples of improvement needs funded across Illinois.<p>

The City of Hillsboro will receive a $375,000 grant to help improve sand filters at its wastewater treatment plant.  The city has not met Illinois Environmental Protection Agency standards because wastewater volumes have overtaxed the existing filter system.  The improvements will eliminate the discharge of inadequately treated wastewater and bring the plant into compliance with state environmental guidelines.<p>

The City of Carthage will receive $50,000 in CDAP grant funding to help replace a key sewer main.  The existing line is too small to handle current sewage volume.  It is deteriorating and is exposed in several locations along a drainage ditch.  Sewage backups have occurred in several homes in the service area, creating hazards to public health and safety.<p>

Lt. Gov. Bob Kustra, the Governor's senior adviser for economic development, said the funding is a sound investment in the future of Illinois.<p>

"Smaller communities must be prepared for economic expansion," Kustra said.  "Infrastructure improvements set the stage for development, improve the quality of life, and protect the health and safety of our citizens."<p>

DCCA officials received 308 requests for CDAP funding, totaling $89.7 million.<p>

CDAP grants are funded through the U.S. Department of Housing and Urban Development (HUD).  The grants are awarded on a competitive basis to cities outside the seven most populous Illinois counties.  Low to moderate income benefit is a primary factor in awarding the grants.<p>

A list of project grants awarded today is attached.<p>

