<HEAD><TITLE>DCCA: News Release -- October 11, 1996</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#8080C0" ALINK="#8080C0">

<img src="/dcca/graph/logosm.jpg" alt="DCCA Logo" width=165 height=82 align=left>
<img src="/dcca/graph/cbar.gif" width=410 height=4><p>
<h3>
Department of Commerce & Community Affairs<p>
</h3>
<img src="/dcca/graph/cbar.gif" width=410 height=4><p>
<font size=+3>1996 News Releases</font>
<br clear=right>
<hr>
<h3 align=center>
October 11, 1996<p>
Governor Announces $5 Million Investment to Expand, Push Marketing of Illinois Coal
</h3>

<strong>CARBONDALE, Ill.</strong> -- Gov. Jim Edgar today unveiled a sweeping multi-million-dollar plan to expand markets for Illinois coal and improve the state's coal transportation, export and delivery systems.<p>

"The Illinois coal industry faces some tough challenges.  By moving forward with a sharply focused and aggressive marketing effort, we believe Illinois can solidify and expand its coal market opportunities," the Governor said. <p>

Edgar announced the state will spend $5 million to support coal marketing and transportation improvements, including $2 million for the Illinois Coal Marketing Campaign. The grant through the Department of Commerce and Community Affairs goes to the Illinois Coal Development Board.<p>

The proposed Illinois Coal Marketing Campaign includes two main components:  The Market Development Program and the Strategic Projects Program.<p>

The Market Development Program includes coal market research and analysis.  Analysts will identify promising domestic and international markets and provide the Illinois coal industry with information and strategies to tap those markets and to increase the value of Illinois coal.  Market Development analysts also will evaluate improvements needed to more efficiently transport Illinois coal to U.S. and global markets.<p>

The Strategic Projects Program will analyze infrastructure needs to improve coal transportation, export and delivery systems in Illinois.  State dollars will be used to leverage private and public investment to improve infrastructure and to increase coal shipments from Illinois.<p>

For instance, the Strategic Projects Program will look at ways to improve Illinois rail and barge loading facilities.  The idea is to move ore coal at lower costs to the Gulf of Mexico and on to international markets.<p>

"We have an opportunity to greatly expand our domestic markets as U.S. electric utilities restructure to comply with Clean Air Act rules," the Governor said.  "In addition, the global market potential for coal is only beginning to be realized as the demand for coal increases, particularly in developing countries.  This strategic marketing plan will help the Illinois coal industry take full advantage of changing market conditions around the world."<p>

State Senator Dave Luechtefeld (R-Okawville) joined the Governor in announcing the marketing plan.<p>

"I am proud to work with the Governor in developing this plan," Luechtefeld said.  "Coal production is the major economic force in many of the Southern Illinois communities I represent.  This plan will push us toward our goal of developing new markets for Illinois coal and developing systems for the most cost-efficient movement of coal to foreign markets."<p>

Lt. Gov. Bob Kustra, the Governor's senior adviser for economic development, said international markets show great promise. <p> 

Working with leaders of the Illinois Coal Association and the United Mine Workers of America, Kustra last year created the Illinois Coal Strategy Group, whose goal is to seek ways to improve the economic viability of Illinois coal and ensure positive impacts on local communities.<p>

"Illinois coal exports are up," Kustra said.  "Exports in 1995 increased 10-fold over 1994 levels and current analysts' projections indicate that we could double foreign export sales by the year 2000."<p>

The Governor asked that the Illinois Coal Development Board act quickly to approve the Illinois Coal Marketing Campaign.  The board reviews and approves all coal research, development and demonstration projects, as well as all expenditures from the Coal Technology Development and Assistance Fund and the Coal and Energy Development Bond Fund.<p>

<center><strong>###</strong></center>
	 
