<HEAD><TITLE>DCCA: News Release -- September 16, 1996</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#8080C0" ALINK="#8080C0">

<img src="/dcca/graph/logosm.jpg" alt="DCCA Logo" width=165 height=82 align=left>
<img src="/dcca/graph/cbar.gif" width=410 height=4><p>
<h3>
Department of Commerce & Community Affairs<p>
</h3>
<img src="/dcca/graph/cbar.gif" width=410 height=4><p>
<font size=+3>1996 News Releases</font>
<br clear=right>
<hr>
<h3 align=center>
September 16, 1996<p>
Local Officials Urged to Attend Revolving Loan Fund Workshops
</h3>

<strong>SPRINGFIELD, ILL.</strong> --  Public officials, bankers, economic development professionals, revolving loan fund administrators and others involved in financing for economic growth are encouraged to attend one of a series of workshops on the management of a successful revolving loan fund system.<p>  

Effective use of revolving loan fund dollars is critical to stimulating job creation and retention in an era of limited financial resources for economic development.  The one-day workshops have been developed to assist administrators and community representatives in designing and administering a successful revolving loan portfolio at the local level.          
Topics to be covered include revolving loan fund design, credit analysis based on sound lending principles, loan closing and documentation, servicing the loan portfolio and tips on working with problem loans.<p>

The first workshop was held September 17 in Crystal Lake.  In addition, workshops are scheduled on October 9 in Effingham, October 23 in Peoria and November 6 in Carterville.<p>

Each of the workshops will cover the same agenda, with representatives from the Illinois Department of Commerce and Community Affairs (DCCA) and the Illinois Revolving Loan Fund Association available to answer questions and discuss strategies.  DCCA and the Illinois Revolving Loan Fund Association are sponsors of the workshops, in cooperation with Western Illinois University.<p>

For more information or to register, contact WIU's Center for Management and Professional Development at 309/298-1555.<p>

<center>###</center>


	 
