<h3 align=center>
August 22, 1996<p>
Breakfast Meetings Help Small Businesses Learn About Environmental Compliance, OSHA
</h3>

<strong>SPRINGFIELD, Ill.</strong> -- Environmental regulations, safety and health requirements, plus many other local, state and federal requirements, are often seen as burdensome to small businesses and entrepreneurs.  In an effort to help ease compliance and understanding, the Department of Commerce and Community Affairs (DCCA) is teaming with the National Federation of Independent Business (NFIB) to host a series of regulatory compliance breakfasts in nine locations around the state.<p>

At the breakfast meetings, experts from the Illinois Environmental Protection Agency; Illinois State Fire Marshal's office; and DCCA's On-Site Health and Safety Consultation Program, Small Business Environmental Assistance Program and First Stop Business Information Center will discuss environmental compliance and OSHA's most frequently cited standards.  Topics include safety and health training, hazard identification, emergency preparation, the impact of the Clean Air Act amendments on small business, underground storage tank requirements for 1998, an update on the status of the LUST fund, and the new Brownfield legislation's impact on cleanup.<p>

After the presentations, participants will be able to discuss their concerns one-on-one with the regulatory experts.  These informal, confidential consultations will be for informational purposes only.  No punitive actions will be undertaken as a result of the consultations.<p>

The breakfast meetings will begin at 7:30 a.m. and conclude at noon.  Cost to attend is $25.00 per person and  pre-registration is suggested.  To register, or for further information, contact Dave Voepel of the NFIB at 217/523-5471 or Annette Lingleo of DCCA at 800/252-3998 (TDD users call 800/785-6055). <p>

A list of seminars and locations is attached.<p>

<center><strong>###</strong></center>

<hr>
