<h3 align=center>
August 7, 1996<p>
GOVERNOR ANNOUNCES $3 MILLION GRANT FOR DEMOCRATIC NATIONAL CONVENTION
</h3>





<STRONG>CHICAGO, ILL.</STRONG>  --  Gov. Jim Edgar today announced a $3 million grant to help offset the City of Chicago's expenses for hosting the 1996 Democratic National Convention, bringing the state's total contribution to the event to nearly $7 million. <P>

"Illinois is fortunate to have an opportunity later this month to showcase our State and the City of Chicago to the world," the Governor said.  "It should be a major boost for the local economy, as well with the 35,000 visitors we expect producing $360 million in economic benefits.   <P>

"Our investment in helping the city put on a premier event will pay immediate dividends as the convention takes place.  In the future, tourism should increase because of heightened interest in Chicago and Illinois as travel destinations."<P>

The $3 million grant to the City of Chicago was awarded through the Tourism Private Sector Grant Program, administered by the Illinois Department of Commerce and Community Affairs (DCCA), Illinois Bureau of Tourism.  <P>

In addition to the fiscal year 1997 grant announced today, the City of Chicago received $2.75 million in fiscal year 1996 and $1.2 million in fiscal year 1995 for convention activities and planning.<P>

Lt. Gov. Bob Kustra, the Governor's senior advisor for economic development, said the grant program is designed to help attract national and international events to Illinois. <P>

"Tourism is a $16 billion industry in Illinois," Kustra said.  "To help keep those numbers growing, this supports public/private partnerships that are key to bringing major conferences, conventions and sporting events to our communities."<P>

The private sector grant program, funded entirely by taxes generated by the hospitality industry, was made possible through legislation approved in 1993 that increased the percentage of the state's hotel/motel tax designated for tourism promotion.  Grants provide a 50/50 match to applicants who can document matching private sector investment.<P>




