<h3 align=center>
August 5, 1996<p>
ALCOA CHOOSES DANVILLE FOR NEW PLANT SITE
</h3>





<STRONG>SPRINGFIELD, IL</STRONG> -- Gov. Jim Edgar today congratulated Alcoa on the company's decision to invest $48 million in a 165,000 square-foot manufacturing facility in Danville, initially creating 35 new jobs with the potential for further growth.<P>

"Illinois is beating the competition for new industry," the Governor said.  "Alcoa reviewed more than 100 sites in five Midwestern states before making a final decision, and we are delighted that this facility is coming to Danville.  Our commitment to providing a skilled workforce and maintaining a high quality of life in our communities played key roles in Alcoa's choice of location."<P>

Alcoa's Aerospace/Commercial Rolled Products Division has purchased nearly 96 acres of land south of I-74 in Danville's Southgate Industrial Park.  The facility will house an automotive aluminum sheet finishing operation and feature state-of-the-art technology and equipment.<P>

Tim Wilkinson, Vice President of the Division, indicated that a site search had been underway since May.<P>

"Our need was for speed and Danville is a community with a vision and the strategies to meet our needs," Wilkinson said.  "The educational facilities are exactly what we need and there is a strong sense of family values here.  Danville is clearly the number one place to build a facility in the Midwest."<P>

Danville Mayor Robert E. Jones and Vicki Stewart, President of the Danville Area Economic Development Council, praised the team effort that brought the facility to Danville.<P>

"Funding and timely completion of all infrastructure to the site was of vital importance to this project," said Stewart.<P>

The Illinois Department of Commerce and Community Affairs (DCCA) and the Illinois Department of Transportation (IDOT) will provide funding totaling nearly $1 million for road, sewer and water line development.  DCCA also has committed to provide up to $70,000 in Industrial Training Program (ITP) funds for worker training at the new facility.<P>

Alcoa's expansion is prompted by expected growth in the North American automotive market.  The Danville facility will provide just-in-time delivery to customers in the U.S. and Canada.  <P>

A groundbreaking for the facility is planned later this fall.<P>





