<h3 align=center>
August 1, 1996<p>
WEBER TO EXPAND IN ILLINOIS, CREATE 225 JOBS
</h3>





<STRONG>HUNTLEY, IL</STRONG> -- Gov. Jim Edgar today announced that Palatine-based Weber-Stephen Products Company will invest up to $14 million to build a 300,000 square-foot manufacturing and distribution facility for its barbeque grills, creating 225 jobs and significantly expanding the company's presence in Illinois.<P>

"Illinois continues on a record-setting pace for business expansions and relocations," the Governor said.  "Weber is the most recent company to recognize that our friendly business climate, sophisticated transportation system and support of worker training are excellent reasons to stay and grow in Illinois."<P>

Lt. Gov. Bob Kustra, the Governor's senior advisor for economic development, unveiled the project at ceremonies in Huntley.<P>

"We weekend barbecue experts look for the best grills for our backyards.  When Weber looked around for the best place to expand, Weber found it right in its own backyard.  Today's announcement is a tribute to the strength and productivity of the Illinois workforce," Kustra said.<P>

"We are delighted to be expanding our operations into Huntley and look forward to a long relationship with the village of Huntley," said Jim Stephen, President of Weber-Stephen Products Company.  "We are thankful to the State of Illinois for its assistance."<P>

Huntley Village President Jim Dhamer commended the cooperation of state and local officials in putting the project together.  "Everyone involved in bringing this facility to Huntley put in long hours and showed tremendous determination.  I am thrilled that the Weber-Stephens project will soon become a reality."<P>

In conjunction with The Prime Group, Inc., Weber will build a combined manufacturing facility and Midwest/international distribution facility on the 33-acre site, located two miles north of the Northwest Tollway and Illinois Route 47 in Huntley.  Construction will begin this month with completion of the buildings expected in the second quarter of 1997.<P>

The Illinois Department of Commerce and Community Affairs (DCCA) will provide a $287,500 Industrial Training Program grant for worker training at the new facility.  In addition, the Illinois Department of Transportation (IDOT) will provide $530,000 for improvements to Illinois Route 47 and construction of Oak Creek Parkway from Rt. 47 to the site.<P>

George Stephen invented Weber Kettle in the late 1950s.  Now headquartered in Palatine, Weber-Stephen manufactures charcoal and gas grills and accessories that are internationally distributed.<P>



