<h3 align=center>
July 1, 1996<p>
Governor Announces $1.3 Million in State Recycling Program Grants
</h3>

<strong>SPRINGFIELD, Ill.</strong> -- Gov. Jim Edgar today announced more than $1.3 million in grants to help Illinois communities, businesses and organizations expand or establish recycling programs.<p>

"Recycling is an important part of our effort to promote a clean environment," the Governor said.  "These grants will help us reduce our reliance on landfills by encouraging the collection and processing of recyclable commodities and supporting the practice of recycling in the home and workplace."<p>

The grants provide capital needed to improve and expand recycling services to Illinois consumers.<p>

Administered by the Department of Commerce and Community Affairs (DCCA), the grants will fund 30 projects, including residential recycling projects such as curbside and multi-family collection programs, commercial programs for business, health care, educational and recreational facilities, and primary processing facilities.<p>

Grants are awarded competitively and may total no more than 50 percent of a project's cost.  Individuals may receive up to $50,000 for a residential or commercial project, while primary processing facilities may receive up to $100,000.  An amount equal to 10 percent of the money awarded must be used to purchase products containing recycled materials.<p>

DCCA's recycling programs are funded through the Solid Waste Management Fund.  Revenues in the fund are generated by a surcharge on the tipping fee on landfill disposal and are earmarked specifically for the programs. <p> 

Since the recycling grants program began in 1987, more than $12 million in state grants has been awarded to 316 recycling projects -- projects which have attracted more than $52 million in matching funds.  The 30 new projects are expected to attract more than $12.5 million in matching funds.<p>

