<h3>
Department of Commerce & Community Affairs<p>
</h3>
<img src="/dcca/graph/cbar.gif" width=410 height=4><p>
<font size=+3>1996 News Releases</font>
<br clear=right>
<hr>
<h3 align=center>
June 26, 1996<p>
Grant to Help Displaced AATCOM Workers
</h3>

<strong>SPRINGFIELD, Ill.</strong> -- Gov. Jim Edgar today announced that Illinois will work with the State of Missouri to administer a $5.85 million federal grant intended to provide job training and assistance to workers dislocated by the closing of the Army Aviation and Troop Command facility in St. Louis.<p>

"Last year, when the Department of Defense issued its recomendations for base closures, we successful argued the case for keeping several Illinois military facilities open, including Scott Air Force Base and the Rock Island Arsenal," the Governor said.  "Because approximately 800 of the 4,200 workers employed at the AATCOM facility were Illinois workers, we also teamed with the State of Missouri to try to keep that facility open, to no avail.  Now we must do all we can to help the workers being dislocated to find new employment.  <p>

"Illinois officials worked closely with their Missouri counterparts to pursue federal assistance for the workers who will lose their jobs as a result of this closing.  This grant ensures that these workers will be able to access the services they need to find new, productive employment."<p>

Edgar was notified of the grant's approval by U.S. Secretary of Labor Robert Reich.  Funds were allocated from Title III Defense Conversion Program funds under the Job Training Partnership Act (JTPA).  The grant is expected to provide services to approximately 1,500 of the 2,000 workers who do not transfer to other defense installations or retire.<p>  

Under terms of the grant agreement, the State of Missouri will receive the grant, and will contract with the Illinois Department of Commerce and Community Affairs (DCCA) to provide services to the Illinois workers affected by the closing.  <p>

Services to be provided include assessment of job skills, career counseling, job search assistance, job development and placement, classroom training, on-the-job training, and supportive services such as child care and transportation assistance. <p>

Because the dislocation was related to a base closing, workers can be eligible for assistance up to 24 months prior to the closure date.<p>

Training will be administered through Madison County Employment and Training Department (Service Delivery Area 22) and the St. Clair County Intergovernmental Grants Department (Service Delivery Area 24). <p>

Closure of the U.S. Army Aviation and Troop Command in St. Louis is slated for completion by December 15, 1997.<p>



