<HEAD><TITLE>DCCA: News Release -- June 24, 1996</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#8080C0" ALINK="#8080C0">

<img src="/dcca/graph/logosm.jpg" alt="DCCA Logo" width=165 height=82 align=left>
<img src="/dcca/graph/cbar.gif" width=410 height=4><p>
<h3>
Department of Commerce & Community Affairs<p>
</h3>
<img src="/dcca/graph/cbar.gif" width=410 height=4><p>
<font size=+3>1996 News Releases</font>
<br clear=right>
<hr>
<h3 align=center>
June 24, 1996<p>
Edgar Signs Kustra-Backed Coal Legislation; Measure Provides Tax Relief
</h3>

<strong>CHICAGO, Ill.</strong> -- Lt. Governor Bob Kustra today lauded Governor Jim Edgar for signing into law coal legislation granting tax fairness and relief to Illinois' coal producers.<p>

The legislation is a product of Kustra's "Coal Strategy Group" formed in 1995 to identify ways to improve the economic viability of Illinois coal.  The group is comprised of leaders of the Illinois Coal Association, United Mine Workers of America and state agencies.<p>

"Our coal producers and miners are doing their best to meet the current challenges of today's marketplace," said Kustra.  "The tax savings will help to make the cost of Illinois coal more competitive with Western coal and encourage coal producers to invest in new equipment."<p>

The legislation signed by the Governor removes a current 6.25 percent tax on purchases of coal mining equipment and spare parts valued at less than $250.  Kustra noted that similar thresholds on the purchase of farm and manufacturing equipment were removed by the legislature in the 1980s.<p>  

"Today we are extending the same tax fairness enjoyed by other Illinois industries to coal.  I am grateful to Governor Edgar, the legislature and members of the Coal Strategy Group for making today's signing a reality," said Kustra.  "The elimination of this use tax is the first of many recommendations the strategy group will make as we look to improve the economic viability of Illinois coal and work to ensure its positive impact on our local communities."<p>

Kustra also commended the legislation's chief sponsors, Senator Dave Luechtefeld (R-Okawville) and Representative Mike Bost (R-Murphysboro) for securing legislative passage of the measure.<p>



