<h3>
Department of Commerce & Community Affairs<p>
</h3>
<img src="/dcca/graph/cbar.gif" width=410 height=4><p>
<font size=+3>1996 News Releases</font>
<br clear=right>
<hr>
<h3 align=center>
June 24, 1996<p>
Governor Signs Tax Relief Bill for Illinois Coal Industry
</h3>

     <strong>CARBONDALE, Ill.</strong> -- Gov. Jim Edgar today signed legislation saving Illinois coal producers about $2.5 million a year by eliminating the remaining sales tax on coal mining equipment and spare machinery parts.<p>

     "The coal industry in Illinois continues to face some very tough challenges," the Governor said.  "This legislation gives our coal producers the same tax benefits other industries already enjoy, and these tax savings will free up capital resources for maintenance, investment and potential expansion."<p>

     The legislation, developed by a coal task force organized by Lt. Gov. Bob Kustra, eliminates the sales tax on coal mining equipment costing less than $250, the same tax advantage given to manufacturers and farmers during the 1980s.  Equipment costing more than $250 already was exempt from the sales tax.<p>

     "This legislation is good for Illinois coal miners, it is good for Southern Illinois, and it is good for Illinois as a whole," Edgar said.<p>

     Edgar noted the Illinois coal industry has annual sales of about $1.5 billion and employs more than 6,600 workers in the state.  Another 20,000 jobs are supported by the coal industry.<p>

     "Today's bill signing is the best example of the good that comes when industry, labor and government work together to keep our workers and industries competitive," Kustra said.  "I am grateful to Gov. Edgar, the legislature and members of the coal strategy group for making this a reality."<p>

     Chief sponsors of the legislation, Senate Bill 1361, were Sens. Dave Luechtefeld (R-Okawville), Bill O'Daniel (D-Mt. Vernon), and Jim Rea (D-Christopher) and Reps. Mike Bost (R-Murphysboro), Bill Black (R-Danville), Terry Deering (D-Nashville), John Jones (R-Mt. Vernon) and Ron Stephens (R-Troy).<p>

     It is effective immediately.<p>


