<h3>
Department of Commerce & Community Affairs<p>
</h3>
<img src="/dcca/graph/cbar.gif" width=410 height=4><p>
<font size=+3>1996 News Releases</font>
<br clear=right>
<hr>
<h3 align=center>
June 21, 1996<p>
State to Assist Mine Workers Affected by CIPS Fuel Switch
</h3>

     <strong>SPRINGFIELD, Ill.</strong> -- Gov. Jim Edgar today directed the Illinois Department of Commerce and Community Affairs (DCCA) and the Illinois Department of Employment Security (IDES) to move immediately to assist workers affected by Central Illinois Public Service Co.'s plan to cease taking delivery of high-sulfur coal from the Delta mine near Harrisburg.<p>

     "Our response to this announcement is already underway," the Governor said.  "State government agencies will coordinate efforts to begin providing unemployment and job training assistance to the Delta mine workers, and we have applied for federal assistance under provisions of the Clean Air Act.<p>

     "While we applaud CIPS's effort to lower customers' utility costs, we are disappointed that it comes at the expense of Illinois mine workers and their families.  My administration is committed to finding new markets and exploring new technology that will shape a brighter future for the Illinois coal industry."<p>

     CIPS announced today that it will switch to burning out-of-state coal at its Newton Power Station Unit 1 in Jasper County.  CIPS had purchased 1.3 to 1.5 million tons of coal annually from the Delta mine of Amax Coal Co., a Cyprus Amax Minerals company.<p>

     Lt. Gov. Bob Kustra, the Governor's senior advisor for economic development, explained that once the displaced workers are identified, DCCA will deploy a Rapid Response Team to visit the Delta mine and conduct pre-layoff meetings.<p>

     "Services provided to Delta workers will include assessments of job related skills, job development, search and placement, and supportive services such as child care and transportation allowances," Kustra said.  "Workers will also have access to classroom and vocational training, and IDES will make staff available for on-site filing of unemployment claims."<p>


