<h3>
Department of Commerce & Community Affairs<p>
</h3>
<img src="/dcca/graph/cbar.gif" width=410 height=4><p>
<font size=+3>1996 News Releases</font>
<br clear=right>
<hr>
<h3 align=center>
May 9, 1996<p>
Lt. Governor Kustra Announces Production of Chrysler Neon for Overseas Markets
</h3>

<em>BELVIDERE, IL</em> - Lt. Governor Bob Kustra today joined Chrysler officials at the Belvidere Assembly Plant to unveil a new right-hand-driven Dodge and Plymouth Neon designed for export to overseas markets.<p>

"Consumers in the global marketplace have come to expect quality and value when they purchase products made in Illinois," said Kustra, who heads economic growth and job creation efforts in Illinois.  "With record-setting exports in 1995 of $32.6 billion, Illinois has become a leader in producing the goods and services in demand abroad.  I am confident the new Neon will be another example of the manufacturing excellence of our Illinois companies and workers."<p>

The Belvidere Chrysler facility will be able to produce approximately 90 right-hand-drive models daily, or 32,000 annually, for shipment to markets in eight counties: Japan, Australia, United Kingdom, South Africa, New Zealand, Cyprus, Cayman Islands, and Thailand.<p>

Chrysler invested more than $500 million in the plant to produce the first Neon, which rolled off the Belvidere assembly line in November of 1993.  The company subsequently announced plans to invest an additional $20 million in capital improvements and add 300 jobs at the Belvidere facility.<p>

Kustra noted that the Illinois Department of Commerce and Community Affairs (DCCA) has provided $5.9 million dollars in Industrial Training Program (ITP) funds to ensure employees of the Belvidere plant have the necessary skills to work in state-of-the-art auto plant.<p>

"Chrysler made a tremendous commitment to Illinois when the Belvidere plant was retooled to build the Neon," Kustra said.  "Our commitment was to provide Chrysler workers with the hi-tech skills needed to build the best possible automobiles.  It was a win-win proposition, and we are seeing the results in this announcement."<p>

The Chrysler Belvidere plant currently employs 3,700 workers and produces approximately 267,000 Dodge and Plymouth Neons annually.<p>

"The addition of right-hand-drive Neons to Belvidere will add incremental units to our production, but it means more than that," said Belvidere Assembly Plant Manager John Felice.  "Our ability to produce left and right-hand drive vehicles on the same line affords us additional flexibility in terms of responding to the global marketplace." <p>


