<HEAD><TITLE>DCCA: News Release -- May 2, 1996</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#8080C0" ALINK="#8080C0">

<img src="/dcca/graph/logosm.jpg" alt="DCCA Logo" width=165 height=82 align=left>
<img src="/dcca/graph/cbar.gif" width=410 height=4><p>
<h3>
Department of Commerce & Community Affairs<p>
</h3>
<img src="/dcca/graph/cbar.gif" width=410 height=4><p>
<font size=+3>1996 News Releases</font>
<br clear=right>
<hr>

<h3 align=center>
May 2, 1996<p>
Governor Announces Buyer for Spartan Printing Plant
</h3>

<em>SPRINGFIELD, IL</em> - Gov. Jim Edgar today announced that a Mexican company will invest $6 million in the purchase of the former Spartan Printing facility in Sparta, Illinois, creating 300 new jobs and ensuring the continued  economic health of the southern Illinois community.<p>

"This is great news for Sparta and southern Illinois," the Governor said.  "The closure of Spartan printing was a severe blow to this small community, but our determination to find a buyer for the facility and provide new job opportunities for the affected workers has paid off.<p>

"My administration has also recognized the importance of maintaining excellent economic relationships with our top trading partners, including Mexico.  I am pleased that those ties have contributed to creating more Illinois jobs."<p>

Grupo Serla S.A. de C.V. will invest $1 million in the purchase of the Spartan Printing facility.  The company will also invest a minimum of $5 million in the purchase of state-of-the-art printing equipment.<p>

Grupo Serla S.A. de C.V. will be eligible for up to $360,000 in Industrial Training Program (ITP) funds provided by the Illinois Department of Commerce and Community Affairs (DCCA).  Grupo Serla will be encouraged to make every effort to re-employ individuals previously employed at the Spartan Printing Company.  In addition, DCCA will provide a list of those employees to Grupo Serla S.A. de C.V. for consideration for re-employment.<p>

Grupo Serla S.A. de C.V. is also eligible for up to $500,000 in Community Development Assistance Program (CDAP) funds.  The funds would be granted to the City of Sparta, which in turn would loan the funds to Grupo Serla S.A. de C.V.<p>

Spartan Printing shut down earlier this year, laying off more than 800 workers by early February.<p>

DCCA has received $1 million in federal emergency funding from the U.S. Department of Labor to assist dislocated workers in returning to the workforce.<p>

Governor Edgar directed his staff to become personally involved in the negotiations leading to the purchase of Spartan Printing, including traveling to Mexico City to conclude an agreement.<p>


