<HEAD><TITLE>DCCA: 1996 News Release --</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#8080C0" ALINK="#8080C0">

<img src="/dcca/graph/logosm.jpg" alt="DCCA Logo" width=165 height=82 align=left>
<img src="/dcca/graph/cbar.gif" width=410 height=4><p>
<h3>
Department of Commerce & Community Affairs<p>
</h3>
<img src="/dcca/graph/cbar.gif" width=410 height=4><p>
<font size=+3>1996 News Releases</font>
<br clear=right>
<hr>
<h3 align=center>
March 14, 1996<p>
KUSTRA ANNOUNCES JOB RETENTION INITIATIVE
</h3>

<em>CHICAGO, ILL.</em> - Citing recent pro-business legislation and national studies that rank Illinois as a top location for business expansion, Lt. Governor Bob Kustra today announced a new initiative to retain Illinois jobs by alerting companies to new advantages to staying in Illinois.<p>

"In recent weeks, three national surveys ranked Illinois and the Chicago area among the top locations for business growth, "Kustra said.  "A few months ago, Industry Week magazine did the same.  There has been a sea-change in business that keeps getting better."<p>

"Illinois companies considering a relocation or other change affecting Illinois jobs could be strongly influenced by the vote of confidence expressed in these impartial survey results.  In the next year, the Illinois Department of Commerce and Community Affairs (DCCA) will contact 1,000 Illinois businesses to make sure they've heard about the great new business climate in Illinois, the new legislation enacted and the consistently high rankings we have earned.<p>

"By analyzing Dunn and Bradstreet data and looking at sales trends, we will target companies that are likely to outgrow their current facilities or show other potential need for the state's attention.  We'll make sure they know what they already have here in Illinois, and we'll make sure they know how DCCA can help them prosper in the years to come."<p>

The surveys reflecting Illinois' economic strength are:<p>
	
CFO Magazine, in January 1996, ranked Illinois among the top ten states for effective business retention strategies.  Said CFO: "Some states are doing a better job at (business retention) than others... While there is no way to scientifically rank the quality of retention efforts... 10 states, based on interviews with tax experts, stand out for their diligent efforts to cater to home-based companies."<p>

Site Selection Magazine last month published its annual survey of business relocations and expansions.  Illinois ranked in the top five, up form 21st just two years ago.  The Chicago metropolitan area ranked first in the nation among metro regions.<p>

Atlas Van Lines, the moving company, in recent weeks released a study of corporate executive relocations it was hired to perform.  The Chicago metro area ranked among the top destinations for corporate executives.<p>

Industry Week Magazine last summer surveyed its readers.  Illinois was preferred as a relocation and expansion site more than any other Midwest state, ahead of Indiana, Ohio and Wisconsin.  Chicago was ranked as the third-most-popular city in the nation, beating out 16 other cities.<p>
	
"Taken together these surveys show an indisputable trend," Kustra said.  "We are reaping the benefits of our economic development policies emphasizing the things most important to business retention growth-including worker training, infrastructure improvement, export development, regulatory reform, and high-technology initiatives.<p>

"New legislation enacted in Springfield has given our state the most aggressive business growth strategy in a generation.  We are attacking unemployment insurance and workers comp cost. We are putting a stop to silly lawsuits without sacrificing legitimate legal rights.  We are holding the line on taxes.  Illinois has a whole new environment for business growth and we need to make sure business knows it," Kustra said.<p>

<HR>
