<HEAD><TITLE>DCCA: 1996 News Release -- March 1, 1996</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#8080C0" ALINK="#8080C0">

<img src="/dcca/graph/logosm.jpg" alt="DCCA Logo" width=165 height=82 align=left>
<img src="/dcca/graph/cbar.gif" width=410 height=4><p>
<h3>
Department of Commerce & Community Affairs<p>
</h3>
<img src="/dcca/graph/cbar.gif" width=410 height=4><p>
<font size=+3>1996 News Releases</font>
<br clear=right>
<hr>
<h3 align=center>
March 1, 1996<p>
GOVERNOR'S EXPORT AWARDS
</h3>

<em>CHICAGO, ILL.</em> - Gov. Jim Edgar today urged Illinois businesses and trade organizations to apply for the 1996 Governor's Export Awards.<p>

"International trade is one of the foundations of the Illinois\rquote  economic growth," the Governor said.  "The Governor's Export Awards recognize companies that have made outstanding contributions to this key segment of Illinois' diverse economy and encourage other firms to expand into overseas markets."<p>

"Our aggressive export assistance programs aid Illinois firms in trading with new established markets.  A recent $450,000 grant from the U.S. Department of Commerce for export development, one of only eight such grants awarded this year, will help businesses target emerging markets, including China And Mexico.  All of these efforts reinforce Illinois' status as an important presence in the global marketplace."<p>

"Illinois products are recognized throughout the world for their value and quality.  Once again this year, the Governor's Export Awards will honor our most successful Illinois exporters and encourage other firms to enter the global marketplace."<p>

Lt. Gov. Bob Kustra, the Governor's senior advisor for economic development, said Illinois continues to be a national leader in the export field.<p>

"Illinois firms have what it takes to compete in the global marketplace," Kustra said.  "More than one-half million jobs in Illinois are related to exports, and one in four manufacturing jobs here are tied to exports.  Illinois exports consistently outpace the nation, thanks in part to our commitment to helping businesses maximize their export opportunities."<p>

The Governor's Export Awards program is administered by DCCA.  Awards will be given in three categories:  New to Export, awarded to Illinois companies that have successfully exported Illinois products for one to five years; Continuing Export Excellence, awarded to Illinois companies successfully exporting for more than five years; and Export Awareness and Development, recognizing Illinois-based not-for-profit organizations involved in the promotion of Illinois exporting and raising export awareness.<p>

Applications for the Governor's Export Awards are available from DCCA;  the state's five International Trade Centers which are located at the College of DuPage in Glen Ellyn, NORBIC in Chicago, Bradley University in Peoria, the University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign and Southern Illinois University at Edwardsville or from trade organizations or clubs.<p>

Companies and organizations may be nominated for the award by others or complete the applications themselves.  Applications should be submitted to DCCA's International Business Division, Suite 3-400, James R. Thompson Center, 100 W. Randolph St., Chicago, IL 60601, or phone 312/814-2325.<p>

Deadline for applications is March 29, 1996.  The awards will be presented at the 2nd annual "Crossing International Borders" conference co-sponsored by DCCA and Arthur Anderson on May 16, 1996.<p>


