<HEAD><TITLE>DCCA: 1996 News Release -- February 22, 1996</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#8080C0" ALINK="#8080C0">

<img src="/dcca/graph/logosm.jpg" alt="DCCA Logo" width=165 height=82 align=left>
<img src="/dcca/graph/cbar.gif" width=410 height=4><p>
<h3>
Department of Commerce & Community Affairs<p>
</h3>
<img src="/dcca/graph/cbar.gif" width=410 height=4><p>
<font size=+3>1996 News Releases</font>
<br clear=right>
<hr>
<h3 align=center
February 22, 1996<p>
GOVERNOR ANNOUNCES ENERGY GRANTS TO HELP 13 HOMELESS SHELTERS
</h3>

<em>SPRINGFIELD, ILL.</em> -- Gov. Jim Edgar announced today that $259,000 has been awarded to 13 homeless shelters to reduce their utility bills.<p>

"This is the fourth consecutive year the state of Illinois has provided funds to make homeless shelters more energy efficient and less expensive to operate, the Governor said.  The money saved on heating and lighting bills can be put into services that help homeless families and individuals get back on their feet.<p>

Support for the energy grants comes form the Homeless Shelter Energy Conservation Program operated By the Department of commerce and Community Affairs (DCCA) and taxpayers' contributions to the Homeless Assistance Fund administered by the Department of Public Aid.<p>

"The combined effort of DCCA and Public Aid allows the State to upgrade homeless shelters and  reduce their annual operating expenses, which frees up funds to serve people in need every day of the year," said State Public Aid Director Robert W. Wright.<p>

DCCA Director Dennis Whetstone said, "The cost of major energy improvements often exceeds the financial means of community organizations.  Offering this assistance is an investment in the future of these facilities and the homeless families and individuals they serve."<p>

Frank Marshall, operations manager for the Chicago Christian Industrial League, said, "A portion of the grant will allow us to insulate on of our nine buildings that was constructed more than 80 years ago.  We expect a major energy cost savings which we'll be able to reinvest into our job training programs."<p>

"A new, efficient lighting system that we will install will mean a savings of $7,400 a year," said Russell Kinzinger, executive director of the Home Sweet Home Mission in Bloomington.  "Money provided by the state for these improvements allows us to replicate savings over the years."<p>

Rebecca Payne, executive director of the Woman's Center in Carbondale, said, "We're delighted to receive funding from the state, which has been instrumental in supporting homeless shelters with these energy grants."<p>

Since fiscal year 1993, the state has provided a total of $1.1 million for 64 energy conservation projects at homeless shelters.<p>

This year taxpayers can again help the homeless by contributing $1 or more to the Homeless Assistance Fund on line 15d of the 1040 - Illinois individual income tax form or on line 7d of the 1040EZ form.  Taxpayers using the Illinois Department of Revenue's TeleFile program also cam make a contribution.<p>

Contributions are either deducted from a tax refund or added to the taxes owed.<p>


