<HEAD><TITLE>DCCA: 1996 News Release -- February 15, 1996</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#8080C0" ALINK="#8080C0">

<img src="/dcca/graph/logosm.jpg" alt="DCCA Logo" width=165 height=82 align=left>
<img src="/dcca/graph/cbar.gif" width=410 height=4><p>
<h3>
Department of Commerce & Community Affairs<p>
</h3>
<img src="/dcca/graph/cbar.gif" width=410 height=4><p>
<font size=+3>1996 News Releases</font>
<br clear=right>
<hr>
<h3 align=center>
February 15, 1996<p>
CHICAGO METRO AREA RANKS FIRST IN NATION FOR FACILITY LOCATION AND EXPANSION; ILLINOIS IN TOP FIVE
</h3>

<em>SPRINGFIELD, ILL.</em> -- Gov. Jim Edgar today announced the Chicago metropolitan area is ranked first in the nation in the categories of metropolitan area new/expanding facilities, and new manufacturing plants, in a n annual survey conducted by Site Selection magazine.  Illinois as a whole ranked in the top five in both categories.<p>	

"Illinois isn't just a great place to do business, it is becoming the place to do business," the Governor said.  "We offer manufacturers the advantages of a central location, an excellent transportation system and a superior workforce.  We invest in highly valued infrastructure improvements and worker training and we have enacted significant pro-business reforms that encourage growth.<p>

"Hundreds of companies have located new or expanded facilities in Illinois during the past year, more than half of them in the Chicago metropolitan area.  These expansions have created thousands of job opportunities for our citizens.  There is no better testimony to the overall success of our economic development policies."<p>

Site Selection ranked the Chicago metropolitan area first among metropolitan areas for new and expanded facilities with 265, and first in metropolitan area new manufacturing plants with 101.<p>

In the category of statewide new and expanded facilities, IIlinois is ranked fifth, with 451.  In the category of statewide new manufacturing plants, Illinois ranks fourth, with 142.<p>

"During the past two years we have seen our rankings improve dramatically, reflecting the economic comeback that Illinois has made," Edgar said.<p>

The survey also notes the strongest regional contender for new plants and expansion was the East North Central Region, led by Ohio, Michigan and Illinois.<p>

The Site Selection rankings echo the recent findings of other national surveys.  Illinois was first in the East North Central region in a relocation and expansion study conducted for Industryweek.  The same study ranked Chicago second only to Atlanta when companies were asked what major cities they would consider for new or additional sites.  In addition,  Illinois remains the corporate-transfer capital of the Midwest, according to a survey of household-goods shipments by Atlas Van Lines.<p>

Lt. Gov. Bob Kustra, the Governor's senior advisor for economic development, said the Department of Commerce and Community Affairs (DCCA) has worked diligently to assist companies expanding or locating new facilities in Illinois.<p>

"It's clear our efforts to build public/private partnerships and be more responsive to our business customer have paid off, " Kustra said.<p>

Published by Conway Data, Site Selection has tracked industry location trends for more than four decades.  The annual tally is based in the company's New Plant Database, which counts new and expanded corporate facility investments of at least $1 million, involving at least 20,000 sq. ft. and employing 50 or more workers.  The annual survey of new and expanded manufacturing facilities appears in the February issue.<p>

