<h3><center>January 8, 1996</center></h3>

<h3>GOVERNOR APPLAUDS PRODUCTION OF NEW ETHANOL POWERED FORD; ALSO AWARD JOB TRAINING GRANT</h3>

CHICAGO, ILL. --  Gov. Jim Edgar today joined officials from Ford Motor Company and the corn industry in launching production at Ford's Chicago Assembly Plant of a redesigned flexible fuel Ford Taurus optimized for the use of ethanol.<p>

The Governor also awarded the company an $800,000 job training grant to upgrade the skills of nearly 3,000 workers at the plant, the Chicago Stamping Plant and five supplier companies.<p>

"Illinois continues to be the nation's leader in promoting the production and use of ethanol," the Governor said.  "Illinois has the largest government fleet of ethanol-powered cars in the country.  We are the top producer of ethanol fuel, and motorists in Illinois pump more ethanol blended-fuel into their gas tanks than in any other state.<p>

"Ford's production of a new vehicle designed specifically for optimal operation with ethanol is another milestone in efforts to increase the use of this clean, renewable fuel derived from corn.  We are especially proud that a vehicle that can run on ethanol produced from Illinois corn is being manufactured by Illinois workers right here in Chicago."<p>

The new flexible fuel Tauruses are optimized for the use of E-85 fuel, a blend of 85 percent ethanol and 15 percent gasoline.<p>

Rand Griffin, Chicago Assembly Plant manager, said "The Taurus in known to meet a wide variety of customer needs, a tradition that has made it America's best selling car for four years in a row.  With out latest flexible fuel Taurus, customers will have another way of making this car fit for their lifestyles."<p>

The Illinois Department of Central Management Services (CMS) has already ordered 40 of the flexible fuel Taurus models, and additional orders are expected.  Currently, there are 139 ethanol-powered vehicles in the state fleet.  Local governments throughout the state have purchased an additional 25 ethanol vehicles through CMS.  The state has also established 11 ethanol refueling stations for the government vehicles.<p>

 Vic Riddle, President of the Illinois Corn Growers Association, voiced appreciation for Edgar's efforts on behalf of ethanol.<p>

"The Governor has been a champion for this Illinois-made fuel.  He has put the backing of his administration and his political influence behind ethanol at the state and national level,"  Riddle said.<p>

Up to 6,000 of the ethanol-powered vehicles are expected to be produced.  The Chicago Assembly Plant produces a total of more than250,000 vehicles a year which are distributed throughout the United States and 17 other countries.<p>

The $800,000 Industrial Training Program grant will be used by Ford to train employees in areas such as the use of technical equipment, preventive maintenance and leadership skills.<p>

Lt. Gov. Bob Kustra, the Governor's senior advisor for economic development, said the grant strengthens the state's partnership with Ford.<p>

"The Edgar administration is committed to investing in a highly-trained workforce," Kustra said.  "Production of the redesigned Ford Taurus and Mercury Sable vehicles at the Chicago Assembly Plant, and so many key pieces at the Chicago Stamping Plant, required the installation of significant new technology.  Stringent export standards also contribute to Ford's need to consistently upgrade the skills of its own employees and those of its suppliers.  I am pleased we can assist Ford in helping workers meet this challenge."<p>

The Industrial Training Program, administered by the Illinois Department of Commerce and Community Affairs (DCCA), is a state-funded program that assists employers with the training and retraining of their workforce.  ITP grants may be awarded to individual employers, as well as multi-company employee training projects.<p>


