<h3>
Department of Commerce & Community Affairs<p>
</h3>
<img src="/dcca/graph/cbar.gif" width=410 height=4><p>
<font size=+3>1996 News Releases</font>
<br clear=right>
<hr>
<h3><center>January 8, 1996</center></h3>

<h3>DCCA RECEIVES GRANT FOR EXPORT DEVELOPMENT</h3>

<strong>SPRINGFIELD, ILL.</strong> -- Gov. Jim Edgar announced today the state has been awarded a $450,000 grant by the U.S. Department of Commerce for export development.<p>

"Exporting is one of Illinois' greatest economic strengths," the Governor said.  "We manufacture products that are in demand in the global marketplace, and one in eight Illinois jobs is dependent on exporting.  It is crucial that Illinois continues to expand and explore markets which have untapped potential.  This grant will help Illinois businesses identify those markets and sell their products in foreign markets that are emerging as significant trading partners with our state."<p>

The grant awarded to the Illinois Department of Commerce and Community Affairs is one of only eight Market Development Cooperator Program Competitive grants awarded this year by the U.S. Department of Commerce for export development.<p>

Lt. Gov. Bob Kustra, the Governor's senior advisor for economic development, said the program DCCA will implement with the grant stresses the importance of cooperation.<p>

"This program is an intergovernmental private/public partnership," Kustra said.  "The Illinois Manufacturers Association, the Illinois State Chamber of commerce and the Chicagoland Chamber of Commerce supported our proposal and will promote the services to be offered to their members and other interested companies.  Small and medium sized businesses, in particular, will benefit from the extensive assistance we will be able to provide with this grant."<p>

The program will assist Illinois firms in the targeted industries of environmental, health and information technologies.  The markets to be targeted are China, Mexico, Poland, South Africa, South Korea and Turkey.<p>

Marketing assistance will be offered at three levels:<p>

State Level -- Trade and catalog shows for export ready companies will be organized by DCCA's International Business Division.  IBD is also responsible for the overall administration of the program.<p>

Regional Level -- Seminars on market opportunities and export training for new-to-export and new-to-market companies will be provided by Illinois' four regional International Trade Centers, which are located in Glen Ellyn, Peoria, Champaign-Urbana and Edwardsville.<p>

Local Level -- Electronic database development for trade show recruitment and follow-up matching for new-to-export and export-ready companies in Chicago will be provided by the City of Chicago Department of Planning and Development Office of International Affairs.<p>


