<HEAD><TITLE>DCCA: News Release -- December 11, 1995</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#8080C0" ALINK="#8080C0">

<img src="/dcca/graph/logosm.jpg" alt="DCCA Logo" width=165 height=82 align=left>
<img src="/dcca/graph/cbar.gif" width=410 height=4><p>
<h3>
Department of Commerce & Community Affairs<p>
</h3>
<img src="/dcca/graph/cbar.gif" width=410 height=4><p>
<font size=+3>News Releases</font>
<br clear=right>
<hr>
<h3 align=center>
December 11, 1995<p>
Governor, Motorola Announce Location of Worldwide Sector Headquarters in Elgin                    
</h3>




<EM>ELGIN, ILL</EM>. - Gov. Jim Edgar today joined Motorola officials in announcing the company will locate the worldwide headquarters of its Messaging, Information and Media Sector (MIMS) in Elgin, investing more than $40 million in a northwest suburban plant and creating 1,500 jobs.<P>

"Illinois' reputation as a great place for high-technology firms to do business continues to grow," Governor said.  "Illinois is becoming known as the Silicon Prairie because we deliver on our promise to provide the well-trained workforce, infrastructure improvements and excellent transportation system these companies require.<P>

"Motorola's steady expansion in Illinois has created thousands of high-quality jobs, and demonstrates the confidence of this communication giant tin our economic development policies.  This new expansion will further strengthen Illinois' partnership with a valued corporate citizen."<P>

Robert Growney, Executive Vice President, Motorola Inc., and President and General Manager of MIMS said, "the anticipated growth of Messaging, Information and Media Sector compelled us to find a site where we could support this opportunity.  The site in Elgin provides the ideal environment for us to significantly grow our business.  The interest and support from the State of Illinois, Kane County and the City of Elgin made it an easy decision for us to stay in Illinois."<P>

Lt. Gov. Bob Kustra, the Governor's senior economic development advisor, said the facility will be a tremendous asset to the area.<P>

"The Illinois Department of Commerce and Community Affairs (DCCA) worked diligently to make this project a reality," Kustra said.  "MIMS produces some of Motorola's most innovative products, and we expect the Elgin facility to attract some of our best and brightest Illinois workers as the global demand for the latest in communication technology continues to skyrocket."<P>

The MIMS site meets the investment and job creation requirements for designation as a High-Impact Business Zone, providing the company with $1.7 million in tax exemptions.  In addition, DCCA has allocated $1 million for worker training through the Industrial Training Program.<P>

The Illinois Department of Transportation (IDOT) will provide up to $1.9 million for area infrastructure improvements, and the Illinois Toll Highway Authority will contribute an estimated $200,000 for roadway modifications.<P>

Kane County and the City of Elgin have also committed to invest in transportation improvements in order to make the project feasible.  In addition, an overall transportation plan already in place for the region contributed to Motorola's decision to locate in Elgin.<P>

The MIMS headquarters will be built on a 130-acre parcel near I-90 at the northwest corner of Elgin.  The facility will include general office space, manufacturing, and research and development.<P>

When completed in 1997, it will consolidate 750 jobs currently scattered throughout the Chicago metropolitan area, with an additional 1,500 jobs to be added by the year 2000.<P>
 

