<HEAD><TITLE>DCCA: News Release -- November 13, 1995</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#8080C0" ALINK="#8080C0">

<img src="/dcca/graph/logosm.jpg" alt="DCCA Logo" width=165 height=82 align=left>
<img src="/dcca/graph/cbar.gif" width=410 height=4><p>
<h3>
Department of Commerce & Community Affairs<p>
</h3>
<img src="/dcca/graph/cbar.gif" width=410 height=4><p>
<font size=+3>News Releases</font>
<br clear=right>
<hr>
<h3 align=center>
November 13, 1995<p>
McDonald's to Add Thousands of Jobs in 20-year $500 Million Oakbrook Expansion                    
</h3>




<EM>OAKBROOK, ILL</EM>. - Gov. Jim Edgar today announced McDonald's Corporation will undertake one of the largest business retention and expansion projects in Illinois history, creating thousands of new jobs and investing as much as $500 million during there next two decades at its global headquarters in Oak Brook.<P>

"This expansion will provide McDonald's with the flexibility to keep pace with its accelerated U.S. and international growth and solidify Illinois' partnership with the world's largest food service organization, " the Governor said.  "McDonald's commitment to stay and expand in Illinois is a strong endorsement of the economic development policies my administration has fostered during the last five year," the Governor said.<P>

The long-term development plan is expected to add as many as 7,000 new jobs over the next 20 years,in addition to the 3,000 now employed by McDonald's at its Oak Brook home office.<P>

"Illinois is privileged to count this global business leader among its corporate citizens.  There are 17,400 McDonald's restaurants in more than 86 countries, and growth in the global marketplace continues to explode.  A new McDonald's restaurant opens somewhere in the world about every four hours, and it all begins right here in Illinois."<P>

Mike Quinlan, McDonald's Chairman and CEO, said "With its excellent business climate and emphasis on infrastructure improvements. Illinois provides us with a strong foundation form which we can maximize our Oak Brook home office support t our global food service business.  We appreciate state and local government officials working together to support our investment in Illinois."<P>

The expansion plan approved by Oak Brook officials during the summer enables McDonald's to expand its global home office.  In addition to the 1.2 million square feet already in use, it authorizes an additional 1 million square feet of office space.  The McDonald' office campus includes 128 acres of land, and the planned expansions will take place on that property.<P>

Lt. Gov. Bob Kustra, the Governor's senior economic development advisor, said, "McDonald's will add quality jobs in its Oak Brook development, filled by an experienced and skilled Illinois workforce.  These positions will be in areas such as operation, restaurant development and marketing.<P>

"More than half of McDonald's middle and senior managers started their careers in its restaurants.  McDonald's is renowned for providing a ladder of opportunity for its employees and franchisees around the world.  Many of them receive world-class training at its hamburger University located on the Oak Brook campus," Kustra said.<P>

In addition to jobs at McDonald's' headquarters, it is estimated that an additional 5,000 spin-off jobs will be created by the development in the next several years.<P>

Karen bushy, Oak Brook Village President, said, "By working with state and local government officials - in addition to the jobs that will be created - we have also been able to ease the transportation concerns for people who live and work in the Oak Brook area.  We are indeed pleased that McDonald's has chosen to continue its partnership with the state of Illinois and our village."<P>

The Illinois Department of Transportation will provide $7.6 million to make several infrastructure improvements in the Oak Brook area, including 11 critical roadway and intersection improvements that will be made over the next five years.  The department also plans to conduct a long-term study of traffic flow in the region.<P>

The Illinois State Toll Highway Authority will provide $372,000 to make ramp improvements from westbound I-88 to Spring Road and construct additional right and left turn lanes. <P>
 

