<HEAD><TITLE>DCCA: News Release -- September 21, 1995</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#8080C0" ALINK="#8080C0">

<img src="/dcca/graph/logosm.jpg" alt="DCCA Logo" width=165 height=82 align=left>
<img src="/dcca/graph/cbar.gif" width=410 height=4><p>
<h3>
Department of Commerce & Community Affairs<p>
</h3>
<img src="/dcca/graph/cbar.gif" width=410 height=4><p>
<font size=+3>News Releases</font>
<br clear=right>
<hr>
<h3 align=center>
September 21, 1995<p>
          Governor Announces $2.75 Million Tourism Grant to Help Chicago Host Democratic National Convention          
</h3>




<EM>CHICAGO, ILL</EM>. - Gov. Jim Edgar today announced a $2.75 million tourism promotion grant to assist the City of Chicago with expenses in hosting the Democratic National Convention next summer.<P>

"The 1996 Democratic National Convention promises to showcase Illinois to the 35,000 delegates, alternates, staff, guests and media representatives expected to attend, and to an international audience following the activities," the Governor said.  "This grant is part of our commitment to the City of Chicago to be a partner in hosting a world-class event.<P>

"Sixteen cities competed for the economic benefits and prestige that hosting the convention will bring.  A spirit of teamwork in the public and private sectors helped win the convention for Chicago, and we will continue to work together to prove that Chicago was the right  choice, "Edgar added.<P>

The economic impact of the convention is expected to reach an estimated $122 million.  The grant to the City of Chicago Office of Budget Management is made through the Tourism Private Sector Grant Program, administered by the Department of Commerce and Community Affairs (DCCA), Illinois Bureau of Tourism.<P>

Other grants through the program this year include:<P>
<ul>
<li> $25,000 to the City of Chicago/Department of Cultural Affairs to assist with costs from hosting the fourth International Congress of Educating Cities<p>

<li> $28,961 to the Rockford Area Convention and Visitors Bureau for costs form hosting the 1996 ASA Men's Nationals 40 & Over Softball Tournament<p>

<li> $25,546 to the River Bend Growth Association, headquartered in Alton, which will assist with the expenses of hosting the 1996 U.S. Women's Amateur Public Links Golf Championship.<p>

<li>n $18,400 grant to the Quad Cities Convention and Visitors Bureau for costs associated with hosting the NCAA Division I Women's National Invitational Softball Championship was announced earlier.<p>
</ul>
Lt. Gov. Bob Kustra, the Governor's senior economic development adviser, said the grants are an important part of Illinois' overall tourism promotion effort. 
"Tourism continues to set new records in Illinois," Kustra said.  "Last year alone, travelers to our state spent nearly $16 billion and the travel industry employed more than 240,000 workers.  It just makes sense to encourage development of more public private partnerships to keep those numbers growing."<P>

The Tourism Private Sector Grant Program, funded entirely by revenue generated by the hospitality industry, was made possible through legislation approved in 1993 that increased the percentage of the state's hotel/motel tax designated for the Tourism Promotion Fund.<P>

Grants provide a 50/50 match to applicants who can document matching private sector investment for efforts to attract major national and international events to Illinois.<P>
 

