<HEAD><TITLE>DCCA: News Release -- August 31, 1995</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#8080C0" ALINK="#8080C0">

<img src="/dcca/graph/logosm.jpg" alt="DCCA Logo" width=165 height=82 align=left>
<img src="/dcca/graph/cbar.gif" width=410 height=4><p>
<h3>
Department of Commerce & Community Affairs<p>
</h3>
<img src="/dcca/graph/cbar.gif" width=410 height=4><p>
<font size=+3>News Releases</font>
<br clear=right>
<hr>
<h3 align=center>
August 31, 1995<p>
Wal-Mart to Build Distribution Center in Olney
                    
</h3>




<EM>OLNEY, ILL</EM>. - Gov. Jim Edgar today announced Wal-Mart Stores, Inc. will build a Midwestern Distribution Center in Olney, creating up to 250 new jobs within 18 months and as many as 400 fully operational.<P>

"Illinois is a leader in the warehousing and distribution field," the Governor said.  "our strong central location, coupled with an excellent transportation network, has already made Illinois the choice for nearly 300 Fortune 500 companies that have major regional or national distribution centers in our state.<P>

"One of the world's premier retailer, Wal-Mart Stores, Inc. is known for carefully scrutinizing every detail when making location decisions.  I am delighted that the company's exhaustive review found Olney and Illinois to be the best location for this new facility."<P>

Lt. Gov. Bob Kustra, the Governor's senior economic development advisor, praised the public/private cooperation that made the project possible.<P>

"Officials for the Department of Commerce and Community Affairs (DCCA) and the Illinois Department of Transportation (IDOT) worked closely with Olney Mayor Tom Fehrenbacher and Stan Wieber, Director of the Richland County Development Corporation, to pull together state and local resources to help this company make its decision," Kustra said.<P>

City officials, the Richland County Boar, the Olney Township Board and Road Commissioner, the East Richland School Board and the Illinois Eastern Community College Board also assisted in making needed Enterprise Zone changes.<P>

The private sector played a crucial role in making the project possible, as well.  Central Illinois Public Service Company, the local GTE office and Norris Electric Coop all agreed to make utility improvements necessary to service the facility.  The First National Bank of Olney agreed to provide temporary office and storage space to Wal-Mart to enable the project to get up and running quickly.<P>

"This type of cooperation between the state, the community and the private sector demonstrates the depth of Illinois' commitment to helping businesses achieve success," Edgar said.<P>

DCCA will award a $640,000 Community Development Assistance Program grant to the City of Olney, which will be combined with $900,000 from the City to extend water and sewer lines to serve the new facility.  DCCA will also provide a grant of up to $250,000 from the state's Industrial Training Program to assist in training the new workers.<P>

IDOT will provide $300,000 in Economic Development Program funds to finance 50 percent of the roadway improvements needed to serve the site.  The improvements will include the construction of turn lanes form U.S. 50 into the Wal-Mart facility, and an eastbound truck acceleration lane from the site onto U.S 50.  The Department will also provide $90,000 for the necessary engineering and plan preparation for the project, as well as construction supervision.<P>

In addition, city and county officials have agreed to extend the Olney/Richland county Enterprise Zone to include the site, a move that will enable Wal-Mart Stores, Inc. to benefit from state and local sales tax exemptions and other incentives.<P>

The 830,00-square-foot warehouse and food distribution center will serve Wal-Mart's Supercenter grocery stores throughout the Midwest.  Construction is expected to begin next spring, with completion slated for spring 1997.<P>
 

<HR>
