<HEAD><TITLE>DCCA: News Release -- August 14, 1995</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#8080C0" ALINK="#8080C0">

<img src="/dcca/graph/logosm.jpg" alt="DCCA Logo" width=165 height=82 align=left>
<img src="/dcca/graph/cbar.gif" width=410 height=4><p>
<h3>
Department of Commerce & Community Affairs<p>
</h3>
<img src="/dcca/graph/cbar.gif" width=410 height=4><p>
<font size=+3>News Releases</font>
<br clear=right>
<hr>
<h3 align=center>
August 14, 1995<p>
  Illinois Film Office Sets New Hi-Tech Production Guide Standard                 
</h3>




Illinois Department of Commerce and Community Affairs director Dennis Whetstone announced today that the Illinois Film Office, working with Chicago based Brand X Filmworks, will soon distribute the Illinois Production Guide on CD-ROM.<P>

"The Illinois Film Office is responsible for ringing motion picture and television production to film on-location in Illinois.  Illinois is the first state in the country to digitize their resource manual, vastly expanding the amount and accessibility of information available to national production executives," said Whetstone.<P>

Brand X Filmworks has developed a custom application as an alternative to the printed 250 page Illinois Production Guide.  The CD-ROM offers easy reference on the set, on the road, or anywhere.  The user still has access to the names of local companies and individuals, in addition to newly enhanced information including catalogs, credits, and photographs.  Thousands of easily searchable answers will be at the film industry's fingertips.  Filmmakers will now be able to customize their resource information which can then be printed or saved.<P>

Beginning in October, 2500 discs will be distributed free of charge to motion picture and television industry leaders around the country.  The list will include production executives at the major studios in Los Angeles, independent production companies nationwide, cable producers, location managers, production managers, producers, directors, anyone who might have a say in deciding where a picture will shoot.<P>

"As the competition for on-location production dollars continues to grow, the Illinois Film Office must take an increasingly pro-active position in the marketplace," said Suzy Kellett, director of the Illinois Film Office.  "In addition to offerings the local production industry the opportunity to use the cutting edge technology of CD0-ROM to sell themselves more effectively, the Illinois and Chicago Film Offices have been actively promoting the State through other mediums."<P>

The first Illinois/Chicago Screenwriter Competition has just been completed to rave reviews.  In October, the Film Offices and Chicago labor leader conducted 22 meetings in Los Angeles on a joint sales trip.  Recently a 15-member industry Task Force Was formed to examine the local filming infrastructure and develop an industrywide national marketing campaign.  The Illinois Film Office has dedicated a staff member to be a Community Liaison responsible for monitoring locations and maintaining relationships with location contacts.<P>

All of these activities are designed to keep Illinois in the limelight as an on-location filming choice, because Kellett believes, "If you ain't the lead dog, the scenery never changes."<P>
 

<HR>
