<h3>
Department of Commerce & Community Affairs<p>
</h3>
<img src="/dcca/graph/cbar.gif" width=410 height=4><p>
<font size=+3>News Releases</font>
<br clear=right>
<hr>
<h3 align=center>
August 1, 1995<p>
Armstrong to Expand In Kankakee                    
</h3>




<EM>SPRINGFIELD, ILL</EM>. - Gov. Jim Edgar today congratulated officials of Armstrong World Industries, Inc. on their decision to undertake a $36.5 million expansion at the company's Kankakee facility, retaining 350 jobs.<P>

"My administration has made economic development a top priority in Illinois," the Governor said.  "In our efforts to convince Armstrong to expand in Illinois, we have seen a strong partnership both between state agencies and between state and local government to keep jobs in Illinois.  By choosing Kankakee over other sites, Armstrong has signaled its confidence in our quality workers, our excellent infrastructure and our competitive business climate."<P>

Lt. Gov. Bob Kustra, the Governor's senior adviser on economic development, personally worked with Armstrong World Industries Inc. to help convince the company to choose Illinois for its expansion.<P>

"We have many tools to help companies grow in Illinois," Kustra said.  "From enterprise zones to low-interest loans, infrastructure assistance and workforce training programs, our programs are designed to meet the needs of individual employers, both new companies and firms expanding for th future.  The bottom line is job - retaining jobs for current workers and attracting new jobs for tomorrow's workers.  I am pleased our negotiations with Armstrong World Industries Inc. have resulted in today's announcement."<P>

The Kankakee plant, located at Hobby and Brookmont Avenues, is among Armstrong's oldest vinyl tile production facilities, in operation for more than 47 years.<P>

The project will include construction of a new distribution center and a new commercial floor tile line.  Improvements are slated for completion during 1996.<P>

Several state agencies and officials were involved in the negotiations with the company.  The final incentive package is expected to include tax benefits from the company's location in the Kankakee River Valley Enterprise Zone and worker training assistance through the state's Industrial Training Program administered by the Department of commerce and community Affairs (DCCA).<P>

In addition, the company is expected to receive financial assistance through the Linked Deposit Program administered by State Treasurer Judy Baar Topinka, as well as low-interest financing through the Illinois Development Finance Authority (IDFA).  The Illinois Department of Transportation is working with the company to meet its roadway needs.<P>

The City of Kankakee also has offered assistance through local Enterprise Zone benefits and tax increment financing (TIF).<P>

Steve Husak, Armstrong's Kankakee plant manager, thanked state officials, Mayor Don Green and the plant's employees for their interest and support.
"Without all their help, these projects would not have been approved for our plant," Husak said.  "These projects are very important to the future success of the tile business.  All of us should be proud the Kankakee plant has been selected for these investments."<P>


 

