<HEAD><TITLE>DCCA: News Release -- July 25, 1995</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#0080C0" ALINK="#0080C0">

<img src="/dcca/graph/logosm.jpg" alt="DCCA Logo" width=165 height=82 align=left>
<img src="/dcca/graph/cbar.gif" width=410 height=4><p>
<h3>
Department of Commerce & Community Affairs<p>
</h3>
<img src="/dcca/graph/cbar.gif" width=410 height=4><p>
<font size=+3>News Releases</font>
<br clear=right>
<hr>
<h3 align=center>
July 25, 1995<p>
Governor Announces Infrastructure Grants                    
</h3>





<EM>SPRINGFIELD, ILL</EM>. - Gov. Jim Edgar today announced $2.9 million in grants it help 10 Illinois communities improve their public water and sewer systems.<P>

"Infrastructure is among government's most important responsibilities," the Governor said.  "Citizens turn to government to ensure that the water they drink is healthy and plentiful, and that waste is safely treated.  These grants will help these 10 communities address infrastructure needs that pose a threat to the health and safety of their residents."<P>

Lt. Gov. Bob Kustra, the Governor's senior adviser on economic development, said the grants are awarded through the federally funded Community Development Assistance Program (CDAP).<P>

"This program is among our most important tools to help smaller Illinois communities address their infrastructure and economic development needs," Kustra said.  "With these grants, communities have the funds necessary to undertake public facilities improvement projects needed to preserve the quality of life and help attract new development."<P>

Dennis R. Whetstone, Director of the Department of commerce and Community Affairs (DCCA) which administers the grants, said the 10 projects will be funded through moneys left unspent from other CDAP components.<P>

"These grants are funded through the community Development Block Grant from the U.S. Department of Housing and Urban Development," Whetstone said.  "When we draw up the budget, we allocate our block grant funds among several CDAP components that fund public facilities improvements, planning, housing rehabilitation, economic development opportunities, emergency public facilities needs and other projects.  This year, we determined that the best use for any unspent CDAP funds is to provide grants to deserving communities with qualifying public facilities projects."<P>

Whetstone cited a project in Jerseyville as an example.<P>

Jerseyville's central water supply began operations in 1923.  The average age of water lines in the community is 50 years.  One section"washed out" in 1989 due to its proximity to Otter Creek, and other sections often experience breaks, threatening the reliability of the city's water supply.<P>

Jerseyville will receive a $360,000 CDAP grant to assist with installation of new transmission mains, valves, hydrants and other system needs.<P>

CDAP grants are provided to communities with populations of 50,000 or less that are not within one of the seven urban counties that receive funds directly from HUD.  The maximum grant available under the Public facilities component is $400,000.  At least 51 percent of the project's beneficiaries must be people with low or moderate income levels.<P>

A list of communities receiving funds may be obtained by calling 217/785-6142 (TDD 800/785-6055). <P>
 
