<h3 align=center>
July 7, 1995<p>
     Governor Helps Cut Ribbon on New Motorola Manufacturing Facility               
</h3>




<EM>MCHENRY, ILL</EM>. - Gov. Jim Edgar today joined company officials in ceremonies officially opening Motorola's new multi-million-dollar Cellular Infrastructure Group manufacturing facility in McHenry.<P>

"Motorola is truly an Illinois success story,' the Governor said.  "Headquartered in Schaumburg, the company is known worldwide for its leadership in the fields of wireless communications, semiconductors an advanced electronic systems and services.<P>

"Through the years, Motorola and Illinois have forged a strong partnership based on our state's ability to provide the infrastructure, skilled work force and business climate conducive to growth.  Today, the company employs more than 20,000 Illinois workers, and will create up to 500 new jobs at this facility.  I am delighted that Motorola continues to grow in Illinois."<P>

Lt. Gov. Bob Kustra, the Governor's senior adviser on economic development, said, "This is a great example of our state government working in partnership with local communities and businesses to create economic expansion."<P>

The state provided more than $1.1 million in infrastructure improvements to assist with the project.  The Department of Commerce and Community Affairs (DCCA) provided a $315,000 Public Infrastructure Program grant to the City of McHenry for water and sewer improvements.  The Illinois Department of Transportation contributed $800,000 i matching funds through its Economic Development Program to provide access to the site, which was matched by a $400,00 grant form the City of McHenry and $400,000 form Prime Commercial Corp., the site's developers.<P>

The 217,000 square-foot facility is located on 20 acres in the McHenry Corporate Center.  The new plant will manufacture cellular infrastructure equipment for customers worldwide.<P>

Motorola has facilities in Arlington Heights, Schaumburg, Northbrook, Libertyville, Itasca, Buffalo Grove, Grayslake, Urbana, Vernon Hills and McHenry, and is currently constructing a $100 million cellular phone manufacturing facility in Harvard.<P>

The company also has facilities in Florida, Texas, New York and Arizona.  Motorola's major equipment businesses include cellular telephones and equipment, two-way radios, pagers and data communications, automotive, defense and space electronics and computers.  Communications devices, computers and millions of consumer products are powered by Motorola semiconductors.  The company's 1994 sales totaled $22.2 billion.<P>
 

