<h2 align=center>December, 1996</h2>
<HR>

<h3>JTPA WINNERS DEMONSTRATE ILLINOIS' "CAN-DO" ATTITUDE</h3>

The Twelfth Annual Illinois Job Training Partnership Act (JTPA) Awards Banquet, held in Springfield in October, demonstrated once again why Illinois' workforce development efforts consistently lead the nation:  the attitude of JTPA's administrators, participants and the employers whose support of the program makes it all worthwhile.  Those employers include Kraft Foods, Inc. and WQAD-TV, winners of the 1996 JTPA Private Sector Awards.<p>

Kraft, nominated by the Private Industry Council of Northern Cook County (PIC), sponsors numerous programs designed to promote workforce development efforts.  From an education/teacher training program that encourages minorities to pursue careers in education and provides funds to institutions that concentrate on these programs, to contributing staff, funds and products to support PIC's efforts, Kraft has demonstrated an outstanding commitment to the betterment of the state's workforce.  Kraft also is a significant contributor to the Resource Development Campaign, a pool of funds contributed by private sector firms to provide scholarships for people who do not wish to seek public assistance but need financial aid to pursue skills training.  Kraft's leadership has been instrumental in convincing other companies to participate in the workforce development system.<p>

WQAD-TV, Channel Eight, takes its public service commitment to the Quad Cities area seriously.  When Special Projects Director Clifford Brockman heard that federal funding for the area's Summer Youth Program was unlikely, he approached the Workforce Employment and Training Center with a strategy.  The "Kids Count Job Exchange," using television to match job seekers with available jobs, was born.  WQAD staffers wrote scripts, traveled to local high schools to shoot video resumes from participating youths, amd approached businesses to encourage their participation as employers or sponsors.  A live broadcast, backed by phone banks, featured the video resumes and fielded calls from youths and potential employers.  The Kids Count Job Exchange helped ensure that many Quad City-area youths found the jobs they needed.<p>

Businesses like Kraft and WQAD-TV are instrumental in Illinois' efforts to build a skilled, productive workforce.  Also key are the efforts of individual programs, program staffers and participants.<p>

The TARGET program, operated by DuPage Job Training, is an example.  TARGET is designed to give women the ability to set realistic goals and plan a career path leading to economic independence.  The program includes career guidance, employment and training opportunities, life skills training and job search/placement assistance.  TARGET successfully graduated 93 percent of those enrolled in its 1995 program, with 77 percent of those entering employment.  Thirty-four percent were trained and obtained employment in a non-traditional job, far surpassing the U.S. Department of Labor standard of 6 percent. <p> 
Martha Kahle, Field Office Supervisor for the Northwest Suburban Employment and Training Center, Private Industry Council of Northern Cook County, is one of the JTPA staffers singled out for recognition this year.  As Supervisor, Martha has instituted policies in the Center to ensure that clients are served in a professional, courteous environment.  But beyond her administrative duties, Martha often works 12 hour days, Saturdays and Sundays to accommodate the needs of her clients.<p>

Typical of this year's participant winners was Angela Bowers, a single mother of two.  Although she worked in housekeeping at a local hotel, Angie's salary was not enough -- she needed public assistance to feed and support herself and her children.  Angie realized that her high school diploma would not qualify her for the kind of job opportunities she needed.  With the help of the Business Employment Skills Team, Inc. (BEST), the JTPA  provider serving Bureau, LaSalle, Lee and Putnam counties, Angie enrolled at Sauk Valley College studying medical transcription.  Despite her many responsibilities and the tragic death of her father in an automobile accident, Angie earned high grades.  Today, Angie has realized her dream and is employed full-time as a medical transcriptionist at KSB Hospital.<p>

JTPA's stories are often inspirational and always gratifying.  In Illinois, the private sector, state government, area service providers, staff and participants are dedicated to the concept that training, hard work and opportunities can keep Illinois' workforce among the best qualified in the world.<p>

<center><h4>###</h4></center>

<hr>
<h3>MAPPING PROGRAM WINS NATIONAL RECOGNITION</h3>

The Mapping the Future of Your Community Program, administered by the Illinois Institute for Rural Affairs (IIRA) at Western Illinois University and sponsored by DCCA and the Governor's Rural Affairs Council, recently received the 1996 Innovation Award from the National Association of Development Organizations (NADO).<p>

MAPPING, which is an acronym for Management and Planning Programs involving Non-metropolitan Groups, is a series of community-based strategic visioning and planning sessions designed to help rural community leaders create a long-term focus ad action plan for community and economic development.  Since its inception, the program has worked with approximately 50 communities, as well as more than 20 school districts and health agencies to help them develop integrated decision-making plans.<p>

Norman Walzer, IIRA Director, said MAPPING is an exciting program because it is based on local initiatives and incorporates University talent in addressing local needs.  "We're trying to create a seamless approach," Walzer said.  "We start with the MAPPING program to help a community set its vision.  This can lead to participation with DCCA's Competitive Communities Initiative (CCI) or Lt. Gov. Bob Kustra's Main Street program, helping community leaders take the necessary steps to develop that vision.  Another step may be to bring in a Peace Corps Fellow to provide the necessary technical expertise to help the community further develop its goals and objectives."<p>

Steve Kline, director of the MAPPING effort, said the program often works with clusters of communities rather than individual communities.  "We try to get communities with shared interests to work together; for example, communities within a large rural school district might work together to develop a regional vision, as well as a vision for each community." <p>

Kline said the enthusiasm generated within the communities is encouraging.  "In Havana, community leaders wanted to open a shuttered movie theater.  With permission from the owner, they went in, cleaned up the theater, and held a community meeting there.  They turned on the lights, popped popcorn, and attracted more than 200 people who could see the vision in action and find a way to participate."<p>

IIRA staff work with about six new communities and five school districts each year, as well as following up with technical assistance to communities that have completed the MAPPING program.  A current project involves working with rural communities to help them create community home pages on the World Wide Web.<p>

MAPPING was featured at the NADO national conference as a model program and also will be highlighted in a special report to be distributed to community development professionals throughout the U.S.<p>

<center><h4>###</h4></center>

<hr>
Gov. Jim Edgar visited the SIU-Carbondale campus in October to announce a $2 million coal marketing initiative to be administered by DCCA's Office of Coal Development and Marketing.  The new program will help Illinois coal producers expand their sales into growing domestic and international coal markets, and also address infrastructure limitations that affect the production and movement of coal within and out of Illinois.  Illinois coal exports increased to 2.7 million tons in 1995, up from 236,000 tons in 1994.  The new initiative is expected to increase coal exports to 5 million tons by the year 2000.<p>

<h4 align=center>###</h4>

<hr>
<h3>LOCAL OFFICIALS!<br>
MARK YOUR CALENDARS FOR TUESDAY, FEBRUARY 18, 1997, 4 p.m. to 6 p.m.!</h3>

DCCA's Office of Local Government Services, in conjunction with the University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign and 13 community colleges around the state, will present GRANTS -- WHAT'S OUT THERE AND HOW TO GET THEM.<p>

This special satellite videoconference, the first in a series of training videoconferences, will identify the important grants available to local governments, grant eligibility requirements, application deadlines, who to contact for grant information and ways community leaders can keep informed about future grants.  The program also will discuss community priorities, tips on how to develop a successful grant application and avoid pitfalls, and what to look for in a grant consultant.<p>

Attendance is open to mayors and other elected officials, administrative staff, consulting engineers, economic development officials, regional planners and community leaders concerned about economic development.<p>

To register, contact the participating college in your area.  Colleges include Black Hawk College, Carl Sandburg College, Danville Area Community College, Elgin Community College, John Wood Community College, Joliet Junior College, Kishwaukee College, Lewis & Clark Community College, Rend Lake College, Richland Community College, Rock Valley College, Truman College and Waubonsee Community College.<p>

<h4 align=center>###</h4>

<hr>
<h3>APPLICATIONS AVAILABLE FOR GOVERNOR'S HOME TOWN AWARDS</h3>

It's time once again to think about honoring the commitments made by volunteers in Illinois communities by nominating their efforts for recognition in the 16th Annual Governor's Home Town Awards program.<p>

Any local government, community-based organization or volunteer group within Illinois is eligible to enter the competition.  Successful entries typically involve volunteer efforts to make their communities a better place to live, work and do business.  Projects must demonstrate broad volunteer support and participation.  Although projects that span more than one year are acceptable, judges will only examine activities accomplished within the most recent calendar year.<p>

Projects are judged using four criteria:  addressing a specific community need; heavy involvement of volunteer resources; generating results; and community support.  Projects compete against those conducted in communities of similar population size.  Each population category includes specific categories under which projects may apply.  These include General Awards (efforts on behalf of the community at-large), Youth Involvement (projects selected, planned and carried out by the community's youths and/or projects that directly benefit youths), Economic Development (projects involving volunteers that help create or retain jobs in the community), and Senior Citizen Involvement (projects selected, planned and carried out by the community's seniors and/or projects that directly benefit senior citizens.)<p>

Communities compete for first, second, third and fourth place awards in each of the categories.  First-place winners compete against each other for the coveted Governor's Cup, a traveling silver trophy awarded each year to the project most representative of Illinois volunteerism during that year.  Judging is done by a group of volunteers who represent organizations that have won Governor's Home Town Awards in the past.  Awards are presented during a recognition banquet, which will be held in Springfield in June 1997.<p>

The deadline to apply for the 1997 Governor's Home Town Awards is February 21, 1997.  For further information or an application guidebook, contact Lou Ann Ladage at DCCA, phone 217/785-6154 (TDD users call 800/785-6055).<p>

<h4 align=center>###</h4>


<hr>
<h3>1997 COAL CALENDARS NOW AVAILABLE</h3>
<h4>by Barbara Antonini, Office of Coal Development and Marketing</h4>

The 1997 Coal Calendars are now available!<p>

Each year, hundreds of fifth- and sixth-grade students from throughout the state submit essays and art work about the Illinois coal industry and its importance to our state.  The winning work is displayed in the Illinois Coal Calendar, showcasing their efforts.<p>

This year's calendar, the eighth annual calendar, is particularly noteworthy.  J. Davitt McAteer, Assistant Secretary for Mine Safety and Health at the U.S. Department of Labor, said the calendar reaches out to the mining community and is a daily reminder of the need for safety in our mines.  In fact, McAteer was so impressed with the calendar that he requested the original art work be available for display at the National Mine Health and Safety Academy in Beckley, West Virginia.  Each poster has been matted and placed in an oak frame for the display, which provides an opportunity for many industry students and international visitors to the Academy to view the ways that young Illinoisans communicate important safety messages.  McAteer also sent personal congratulatory letters to the 25 students whose essays and art work are reproduced in the calendar.<p>

The 1997 Coal Calendar Contest was co-sponsored by DCCA's Office of Coal Development and Marketing, and the Coal Research Center, Southern Illinois University at Carbondale.  To request a calendar or for further information about the contest, contact Barbara Antonini, DCCA's Office of Coal Development and Marketing, 325 W. Adams, Springfield, IL 62704, phone 217/524-3280 (TDD users call 217/785-0211).<p>

<h4 align=center>###</h4>

<hr>
<h3>DCCA EFFORTS RECOGNIZED BY ILLINOIS EPA</h3>

DCCA's Small Business Environmental Assistance Program and the Illinois Small Business Development Center Network (ISBDCN) recently received 1996 Certificates of Commendation from the Illinois Environmental Protection Agency (IEPA) for their work in helping implement the "Clean Break" environmental amnesty program in Illinois.<p>

Clean Break, a recently-completed initiative enacted in response to recommendations made by the Governor's Small Business Environmental Task Force, gave auto body, auto repair and printing business owners free technical assistance from IEPA experts while offering them amnesty from fines and penalties resulting from environmental violations uncovered during the review process.  The program was founded on the theory that most small business owners want to comply with environmental regulations but need help to determine what those regulations are.<p>

DCCA's Small Business Environmental Assistance Program served as an initial contact for the program, enabling business owners to seek information on a confidential basis.  The Illinois Small Business Development Center Network sponsored numerous local seminars to explain Clean Break and helped with intake.<p>

The IEPA's Certificate of Commendation recognizes individuals or groups for outstanding contributions to protection of the environment or other significant achievements in Illinois.  DCCA also receoved a Certificate for its work during 1995.<p>

<h4 align=center>###</h4>

