<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#8080C0" ALINK="#004080">

<HR>
<CENTER><IMG SRC="/dcca/graph/dnews.gif" WIDTH=414 HEIGHT=127 alt="DCCA News"></CENTER>
<CENTER><H2>September, 1996</H2></CENTER>
<HR>

<h3>ILLINOIS EMPLOYMENT AND TRAINING CENTERS <br>
PROVIDE "ONE-STOP" ASSISTANCE TO WORKERS AND EMPLOYERS</h3>

All over Illinois, a quiet revolution is taking place in the way our state delivers employment and training services.  In March 1994, the first Illinois Employment and Training Center (IETC) opened, bringing together Job Training Partnership Act (JTPA) services with those administered by the Illinois Department of Employment Security (IDES).  Within a few months, four more centers opened, and more than a dozen  centers were added during 1995.  The timetable is moving even faster today, thanks to a special grant from the U.S. Department of Labor to spur development of additional IETCs throughout the state to help both workers and employers easily access the employment, training and related social services information they need.<p>

IETCs are truly "one-stop" shops.  In the past, a dislocated or disadvantaged individual might have to travel all over town or between several different communities to access needed services.  He or she might need to visit an IDES office to register for unemployment insurance, a Service Delivery Area office to sign up for training and other services under JTPA, a Community College to register for classroom coursework, and to various other agencies to sign up for other services.  Likewise, some employers found it necessary to go to more than one location to obtain the kind of statistical information they needed to find skilled workers, and to access a pool of qualified potential employees.<p>

The IETC concept has changed all that.  IETCs consolidate these services under one roof.  For example, within a few minutes after walking into the IETC, a displaced worker can register for unemployment insurance, access computer job banks, sign up for JTPA programs, review a community college catalog, and receive the kind of detailed, one-on-one assistance needed to help get back into productive work.  At the same time, employers have access to qualified applicants, using Illinois' largest applicant database.  Staff at the IETC can identify individuals who meet a business' specific needs, from managerial to high-tech, to administrative support, and refer the best qualified candidates for the job.  Professional staff in the IETC also can help with specialized services, such as staff recruitment for mass hiring, customized training, and outplacement assistance.  The latest in statistics on the workforce and its skills is available, enabling businesses to locate potential employees.  In addition, employers can work closely with the local IETC to ensure that, as training programs are developed, they are tailored to meet the needs of the local employment community, creating a bank of potential employees armed with the skills local companies need.<p>

IETCs will also be a source of the latest labor market information (LMI) for schools, libraries and students.  LMI products will be available on-site and will be distributed by the IETC in hard copy and via computer.  Students and dropouts may also use the IETC to obtain career counseling and to learn about "second chance" education programs.<p>

IETCs offer an ambitious array of services.  They can provide career counseling to help workers assess their skills and research areas where those skills are needed.  They can help workers analyze their interests and pinpoint training that can help them learn the skills they need to follow their dreams.  They can even help students identify internship and apprenticeship opportunities that can lead to potential employment.<p>
 
Already, more than 40 IETCs are providing services to clients around the state.  <p>

More than 120 other agencies also are located in the IETCs, helping provide a truly comprehensive range of services.  Plans call for 55 full-service centers in Illinois by 1997, with more than 90 additional satellite facilities. <p>

It's easy to locate the IETC nearest you.  Check the IETC section on DCCA's home page on the Internet at http://www.ilcommerce.com/.   You'll find detailed information on the various centers, including addresses, hours of operation and telephone numbers, plus a detailed listing of services available to both employers and employees. <p> 

If you don't have Internet access, you can call 888/FOR-IETC (TDD users call 312/793-3184) to learn the location of the IETC nearest you.<p>

<hr>
<h3>FROM THE DIRECTOR<br>
Dennis Whetstone</h3>

Economic development is clearly a priority in most communities.  Knowing successful economic development techniques, however, may not always be so clear.   That's why, in October, the Illinois Department of Commerce and Community Affairs (DCCA), along with the Illinois Development Council (IDC), will again sponsor the Basic Economic Development Course, designed to help economic development practitioners and community leaders help their communities become more competitive in the process of economic development. <p>

The Basic Economic Development Course is an intensive five-day course, directed by Dr. Robert Koepke of Southern Illinois University at Edwardsville, and coordinated by DCCA's Rich Funderburk and Mary Renner.  Among sessions to be taught are building the foundation of a competitive community, influencing investment location, supporting existing business, stimulating international trade and entrepreneurship.  On Thursday, October 24, a special session will be held on "Servicing the Prospect."  That session is open to anyone interested in attending, even those who cannot attend the other sessions.  All sessions are taught by well-respected economic development professionals from throughout the United States, including Certified Economic Developers David Richmond of Shelbyville, Indiana; M. L. DuBrow of St. Louis; and Dean Whitaker of Holland, Michigan; consultants Kate McEnroe of McEnroe Consulting, Atlanta, Georgia; David Kolzow of Fluor Daniel Consulting, Greenville, South Carolina; and Eric Canada of Blane, Canada Ltd., Wheaton; John Quinn of the University of Illinois Cooperative Extension Service, Carbondale; Doug Dougherty, executive director of the Governor's Rural Affairs Council; Michael Boer of the Greater Springfield Chamber of Commerce; and Jeff Markland of DCCA's Office of Local Initiatives.<p>  

Participation in the Basic Economic Development Course provides graduates with a basic education that they can take back home and use in helping their communities become more successful in the economic development competition.  It also is the first step toward accreditation through the American Economic Development Council (AEDC), because graduates become eligible to attend the Economic Development Institute through the University of Oklahoma, where they can earn the coveted Certified Economic Developer accreditation.<p>

The October course will be the third Basic Economic Development Course DCCA has co-sponsored this year.  Already, nearly 100 DCCA staff people have completed the course, as well as staff people from many of our economic development partners, such as Small Business Development Centers, Community Action Agencies and others.  I feel that the course has been instrumental in helping DCCA staff to better serve you.<p>  

I heartily encourage economic development practitioners, local officials, chamber of commerce executives and others interested in making their communities more competitive to attend the next Basic Economic Development Course.  The course will be held October 21-25 on the campus of the University of Illinois-Springfield.  Registration should be made through the Office of Continuing Education, Campus Box 1084, Southern Illinois University at Edwardsville, Edwardsville, IL  62026.  For further information, contact Dr. Robert Koepke at SIU-Edwardsville, telephone 618/692-2142, or Mary Renner at DCCA, 217/785-6097 (TDD users call 800/785-6055.)<p>  

<hr>
<h3>SMALL BUSINESSES RECEIVE A "CLEAN BREAK"</h3>
<h4>by Annette Lingleo, DCCA Bureau of Business Development</h4>

Nearly 300 Illinois auto body, auto repair and printing businesses have found it easier to comply with environmental laws, thanks to the Clean Break program, an initiative undertaken by DCCA's Small Business Environmental Assistance Program and the Illinois Environmental Protection Agency (IEPA).<p>

Clean Break is a program that gives auto body, auto repair and printing business owners free technical assistance from IEPA experts, while offering them amnesty from fines and penalties for environmental violations uncovered during the review process.  The program is based on the belief that most small business owners sincerely want to comply with environmental regulations, but need help in determining what the requirements are.  <p>

DCCA's Small Business Environmental Assistance Program has served as the initial contact for the program, allowing business people to ask confidential questions while remaining anonymous to the enforcement agency.  Once a business owner feels comfortable in coming forward with environmental concerns, on-site technical assistance visits are arranged with the IEPA experts, who walk through a facility with its owner, discussing the business' specific requirements.  At that point, the owner can choose to go forward with the amnesty compliance agreement, working with the IEPA to set up a reasonable period of time in which to make corrections and achieve compliance with environmental rules.<p>

The Clean Break program was enacted in response to recommendations made by the Governor's Small Business Environmental Task Force, which studied the challenges faced by small businesses in complying with federal clean air standards and other environmental rules.  To date, the program has received overwhelmingly positive response, and plans are now being made to expand it to serve other business segments.<p>

Clean Break also has had another benefit.  Working directly with small business owners gave IEPA officials a first-hand look at the impacts of various rules on businesses.  For example, many wastes from auto body and auto repair shops, such as oil filters and paint filters, are classified as "special waste," subject to additional disposal rules and regulations.  The IEPA discovered that the waste still ended up in the same place, but only after the business filled out mounds of paperwork.  The agency is now using the information it gathered to examine and correct rules that placed extra burdens on businesses while adding no protection to the environment.<p>	

To learn more about Clean Break, contact DCCA's Small Business Environmental Assistance helpline at 800/252-3998.<p>


<hr>
<h3>STATE CLEARINGHOUSE NOW LOCATED AT DCCA'S CHICAGO OFFICE</h3>

Illinois organizations that receive federal funding are familiar with the State Clearinghouse.  Also known as the State Single Point of Contact, the State Clearinghouse must review all applications for federal funds before an organization may be eligible to receive those funds. <p> 

What organizations may not know, is that the State Clearinghouse is now a part of DCCA.  Administered by the staff of the Office of Policy Development, Planning and Research, the State Clearinghouse has recently moved to DCCA's Chicago Office.<p>

All correspondence with the State Clearinghouse should now be directed to:<p>

Virginia Bova, Single Point of Contact, DCCA, James R. Thompson Center, 100 W. Randolph, Suite 3-400, Chicago, IL  60601, phone 312/814-6028, fax 312/814-1800 (TDD users call 800/419-0667).<p>

<hr>
<h3>WHAT IS THE STATE CLEARINGHOUSE?</h3>

Each year, the federal government awards billions of dollars in grants to fund a myriad of projects.  To ensure that state and local governments have a say in those projects, Executive Order 12372 was enacted in 1983, requiring federal agencies to designate certain programs and projects to be eligible for review by the states.  The Executive Order allowed each state to design a process to simplify giving state and local elected officials an opportunity to review and comment on these proposed projects.  Illinois created the Illinois State Clearinghouse, housed at the Department of Commerce and Community Affairs (DCCA), to handle this process.<p>

The process has several steps.  First, local grant applicants are encouraged to contact the State Clearinghouse prior to submitting an application to determine whether the grant they seek has been selected for review.  If so, the grant applicant submits the project proposal to the federal government, and sends the State Clearinghouse a standard form that includes basic project and program information.<p>

While federal officials begin reviewing the project, the State Clearinghouse assigns a State Application Identifier (SAI) number and distributes the project to reviewers representing 19 Regional Planning Commissions and 23 other organizations located throughout the state.<p>

Reviewers have 30 days in which to comment.  Any comments are submitted to both the State Clearinghouse and the applicant.  If no unfavorable comments are received, the State Clearinghouse issues a sign-off letter to the applicant, the applicable Regional Clearinghouse and the federal agency, noting the proposal's compatibility with state, regional and local development plans.  If negative comments are received, the sign-off letter will include suggestions on ways to address the compatibility defects.  Negative comments do not, however, prohibit an applicant from continuing the application process.<p>

The Illinois State Clearinghouse keeps on file a list of current grant applications submitted by various state agencies.  The State Clearinghouse also provides review for Environmental Impact Statements and Environmental assessments.<p>


<hr>
<em><strong>DCCA NEWS</strong></em> is published by the Illinois Department of Commerce and Community Affairs. Dennis R. Whetstone, Director.<p>

Direct all correspondence to Lynn Morford, Editor, 620 East Adams, Springfield, IL  62701.  E-mail:  <a href="mailto:lynn.morford@accessil.com">lynn.morford@accessil.com</a><p>

