<CENTER><H2>June, 1996</H2></CENTER>
<HR>

<h3>DEVELOPMENT CORPORATIONS:  ANOTHER TOOL<br>
FOR ECONOMIC DEVELOPMENT</h3>
<em>by Dale Fesser, DCCA Division of Loan Administration</em><p>

Construction of a new "spec" building in an industrial park.  Financing for a grocery store in a small town.  A business expansion loan to a participant in a "Create Your Own Business" contest.<p>

What do these have in common?  They all are projects completed by various Development Corporations -- regionally-based organizations capitalized partially through DCCA grants -- that provide financing to supplement commercial lending and support economic development in Illinois.<p>

Development Corporations are as varied as their clients.  They may specialize in development and rehabilitation of real estate, investment in or lending to businesses, or related activities.  Most often, Development Corporations are public and bank sponsored and funded financial institutions.  They serve as a source of supplemental business capital for small businesses whose credit requirements cannot be adequately served by conventional lending institutions.<p>

Of the 43 Development Corporations in Illinois, 34 have received DCCA assistance totaling approximately $2.24 million matched by more than $7.5 million in private investment.  Those 34 Development Corporations already have financed more than 89 projects.  Their loans and investments have leveraged private sector loans and investments of more than $59.1 million with total investment of more than $71 million.  Projects funded through state-assisted Development Corporations have resulted in the creation and retention of more than 3,600 Illinois jobs.  The impact will continue to grow as the original loans are repaid and the recaptured funds are used for new loans for future economic development projects.<p>

The Development Corporation program is particularly important to DCCA's strategy to help strengthen regional economic development efforts in rural areas.  Development Corporations are financial intermediary organizations.  By creating new "extra market" institutions, DCCA helps to eliminate the traditional gaps found in asset-based lending at the local level.  At the same time, DCCA itself is taken out of the direct lending business, resulting in more effective delivery of services, greater local access to capital for small and medium-sized Illinois firms, better lending decisions and a better match between the individual needs of businesses and communities.<p>

To learn more about the Development Corporation program or obtain the name of a Development Corporation serving your area, contact Dale Fesser, Development Corporation program manager, at 217/524-0165 (TDD:  800/785-6055) or by E-mail at dale.fesser@accessil.com.<p>

<hr>
<h3>GREAT PRINTERS PROJECT EXPANDS OPPORTUNITIES; PROTECTS ENVIRONMENT</h3>

Protecting the environment is an important concern for everyone.  Today, more than ever, businesses and government must work together to make pollution prevention a key consideration within the nation's industries.  DCCA's Small Business Environmental Assistance Program is part of a team working on a major initiative to help establish pollution prevention as a standard business practice within the lithographic printing industry -- the Illinois Great Printers Project.<p>

Lithographic printing uses a variety of materials and potentially hazardous chemicals, generates wastes and consumes energy.  Although the average small print shop is not a major pollution source, the impact of hundreds of such businesses is substantial.  The Illinois Great Printers Project is researching ways to help printers prevent pollution at the source by focusing on customer demands, regulatory requirements, and access to technology and financial resources.  <p>

A steering committee, which includes representatives from DCCA, the Illinois Environmental Protection Agency, the Center for Neighborhood Technology, the Printing Industry of Illinois and Indiana (PII), and the Hazardous Waste Research and Information Center has identified five groups integral to the project:  printers, customers, suppliers, regulatory agencies, and technical assistance.  <p>

Over the past year, each group has been working to develop programs and policies that can help incorporate pollution prevention into the standard business practices of the lithographic printing industry.  For example, activities undertaken by the Customers group include working with the printing industry to develop environmentally sound printing specifications.  The Suppliers group is working with the printing industry to identify environmentally-friendly materials and equipment, promote and disseminate information concerning environmentally sound alternatives, develop a standard form containing product information and environmental benefits, and adopt a standard protocol to identify potentially hazardous chemicals.  Among its activities, the Regulatory Agencies group is trying to revise existing environmental assessment policies to ensure they support and provide incentives for voluntary auditing and pollution prevention.  The Technical Assistance group is working to establish a Resource Center that would provide pollution prevention information to the lithographic printing industry.<p>

Assisting with the efforts is an Advisory Committee of representatives from the printing industry, printing supply industry, printing customers, financial institutions, citizens groups, relevant government agencies and environmental organizations.  This committee provides a sounding board for exploring relevant issues and reviewing the activities being undertaken.<p>

Although much work remains to be done, educating the public is seen as a key to the project's ultimate success.  Criteria are now being developed under which printers may be designated as "Great Printers."   Efforts will be undertaken to publicize the meaning behind the Great Printers designation and encourage consumers to seek out these printers for their printing services.  It is hoped that the educational effort will reward Great Printers by increasing their customer base.<p>

Illinois is one of four states, including Wisconsin, Minnesota and Michigan, designing pilot programs to standardize pollution prevention as a business practice in the lithographic printing industry.  It's all part of a larger effort started in 1992 by the Council of Great Lakes Governors, the Environmental Defense Fund and the Printing Industries of America.  Called the Great Printers Project, this effort aims to create a business environment conducive to pollution prevention for an entire industry sector, thereby helping to expand a strong regional printing industry while retaining a clean Great Lakes ecosystem.<p>


<hr>
<h3>TOURISM ADS WIN AWARDS, GET RESULTS</h3>

It's summer and time to get away for a weekend or that badly needed vacation.  DCCA's Illinois Bureau of Tourism is out to help you find the perfect getaway in Illinois.  An aggressive television advertising campaign hit the airwaves April 1 reminding tourists that they can travel a "Million Miles from Monday" right in our state.<p>  

The television campaign already has earned both critical acclaim and impressive tourism gains.  The 1995 "Million Miles from Monday" campaign was named the best tourism campaign of the year in a worldwide competition at the New York Festival -- the only U.S. campaign to make the finals.  It also won acclaim as the Best Creative of the Year at the Chicago International Film Festival, and won the 1996 ATLAS Award from the Association of Travel Marketing Executives.<p>

Even more important, the ads have been an integral part of Illinois' success in attracting tourists.  Over the past nine months, calls to the Illinois Travel Counseling System (ITCS) have increased 22 percent compared to the same period a year ago.  Follow-up studies show that 62 percent of callers end up traveling to one or more Illinois destinations.  Since September 1995, calls to the 800 number have broken monthly totals.<p>   

The television ads are part of a $10 million domestic tourism campaign that includes print ads, direct response television and showings of the ads at Chicago's O'Hare and Midway airports.  All of the print ads and several direct response television spots feature the benefits of calling ITCS, which puts callers on the line with an expert travel counselor who can use one of the largest tourism databases in the U.S. to help them with their Illinois tourism plans.<p>

Are you ready for a getaway?  Call 1-800-2-CONNECT and go a "Million Miles from Monday" in Illinois.<p>

<hr>
<h3>BASIC ECONOMIC DEVELOPMENT COURSE<br>
HELPS EXPAND STAFF KNOWLEDGE </h3>

Forty-two DCCA staffers and colleagues from other economic development organizations learned more about the foundations of successful economic development as participants in the Basic Economic Development Course, sponsored by DCCA in March.  The intensive five-day course, presented by Dr. Robert Koepke of Southern Illinois University at Edwardsville, provided the graduates with accreditation through the American Economic Development Council (AEDC) and is the first step toward accreditation as a Certified Economic Developer.<p>

The course included presentations by a wide range of economic development experts from throughout the United States.  Bill Browning, president and CEO of the Heartland Partnership in Peoria, described how to build an effective economic development organization, while Kate McEnroe, a location consultant from Atlanta, Georgia, discussed the use of incentives and tips for working with consultants.  David Richmond, a veteran economic developer from Richmond, Indiana, shared his insight into innovative financing programs.  A highlight of the program was an address by Rick Thrasher, president and CEO of WI/SE Partnership for Growth in Wichita, Kansas.  Thrasher, who serves as first vice chair of the American Economic Development Council, and Lori Healey, president of the Illinois Development Council, joined DCCA Director Dennis Whetstone in awarding certificates of completion to the 42 graduates.<p>

Response to the course was so enthusiastic that DCCA plans to sponsor a second BEDC class in June.  Typical of the comments:  "The BEDC was excellent.  I learned a lot about economic development that I really didn't know.  In addition, it helped me to better understand the overall mission of the agency better than anything I had previously read or heard."<p>

All graduates of the course become eligible to attend further training through the University of Oklahoma toward earning the Certified Economic Developer designation.<p>
 	
<hr>
<h3>DCCA SUPPORTS RESEARCH USING COAL BY-PRODUCTS<br> 
TO PRODUCE ARTIFICIAL MINE ROOF SUPPORTS</h3>

Research, supported by DCCA through the Illinois Clean Coal Institute (ICCI), could soon lead to recycling fly ash, a by-product produced when coal is burned, into artificial timbers to support the roofs of coal mines.<p>

Mining engineering Professor Yoginder P. "Paul" Chugh of Southern Illinois University at Carbondale recently demonstrated the strength of two-foot timbers made of fly ash and other fluidized-bed combustion by-products.  The demonstrations were the first step toward receiving approval from the U.S. Mine Safety and Health Administration to use the new timbers as mine roof supports.<p>

Chugh, chairman of SIUC's mining engineering department, and a team of scientists spent two years developing the timbers.  The timbers are made with about 65 percent fly ash, cement and fibers which are added to give the timbers characteristics similar to wood.  Like ordinary wood timbers, the fibers will "splinter" when the artificial post exceeds its design load capacity, signaling that the timber needs to be replaced.<p>

Chugh says the timbers weigh significantly less than concrete and are as strong as traditional wood timbers.  An economic analysis shows the cost of making the six foot timbers is about the same as making them from wood.  The real benefit comes from conserving trees while using a product that currently goes to landfills.<p>

"Coal-burning utilities from Illinois put more than 3 million tons of fly ash and other coal combustion by-products into landfills each year," Chugh said.  "In addition, more than 60 million cubic feet of wood are used every year as timbers in U.S. coal mines."  Chugh estimates that 2.5 million tons of fly ash would be used each year if every U.S. coal mine switched to artificial timbers.<p>

The study is just one in a series of coal-related by-products management studies being sponsored by the ICCI.  Other projects include using coal combustion by-products in road beds and surfaces, automotive brake shoes and body panels, patio bricks, sewer tiles and flower pots.<p>


<hr>
<h3>DCCA WORKING TO REDUCE COAL-GENERATED AIR POLLUTANTS</h3>

<em>by Gary Philo, DCCA Office of Coal Development and Marketing</em><p>

DCCA's Office of Coal Development and Marketing (OCDM) is actively working to help encourage the development and use of new technologies that reduce hazardous emissions from burning Illinois coal.  As part of that effort, the OCDM recently held a workshop on sulfur dioxide and air toxics control, bringing together representatives from many of the state's electric power generating companies with those from state government and the air pollution control industry to discuss the role of advanced scrubber technologies.  <p>

Illinois coal has a high sulfur content, which has caused the state to lose market share in recent years as many coal-burning companies turned to low-sulfur western coal.  OCDM is working to encourage development and use of technologies that can  make Illinois coal environmentally safe to use.  It also is seeking out new international markets that can utilize these technologies to safely burn Illinois coal.<p>
  
The workshop, held in Springfield, particularly focused on various technologies that can help companies meet sweeping emission limitations on sulfur dioxide that will become effective in the year 2000.  Participants also looked at control strategies for mercury and other hazardous air pollutants that may face future regulation.  <p>

Representatives from Central Illinois Public Service Company, Springfield City Water, Light and Power, Illinois Power Company, the Environmental Element Corporation, the Illinois Clean Coal Institute, and OCDM participated in the workshop.<p>


<em>DCCA NEWS</em> is published by the Illinois Department of Commerce and Community Affairs. Dennis R. Whetstone, Director.<p>

