<CENTER><H2>February, 1996</H2></CENTER>
<HR>
<H3>NEW AND EXPANDING BUSINESSES CHOOSING ILLINOIS</H3>

More and more, Illinois is the location of choice for new and expanding
businesses.  Over the past few months, Gov. Jim Edgar has announced several
impressive projects that will create hundreds of new jobs for Illinois
workers.  Among the companies choosing to expand in Illinois are Motorola
and U.S. Robotics -- high technology companies that are contributing to
Illinois' emergence as the "silicon prairie."<P>
     
Motorola recently chose Elgin for the worldwide headquarters of its
Messaging, Information and Media Sector (MIMS).  The $40 million plant is
expected to create 1,500 jobs.  At the official ceremonies announcing the
project, the Governor said, "Illinois is becoming known as the Silicon
Prairie because we deliver on our promise to provide the well-trained
workforce, infrastructure improvements and excellent transportation system
these companies require."<P>

MIMS is a world leader in the manufacture of cutting-edge communications
products associated with pagers and wireless communications.  The
headquarters will be built on a 130-acre parcel near I-90 in Elgin.  It is
slated for completion in 1997.<P>

U.S. Robotics is one of the world's leading suppliers of products and
systems that provide access to information.  The company designs,
manufacturers, markets and supports remote access servers, enterprise
communications systems, desktop/mobile client products and modems.  Gov. Edgar recently participated in
dedication ceremonies for the company's new $30 million manufacturing and
operations facility in Morton Grove, and announced that U.S. Robotics will
continue its investment in Illinois through expanding its Mt. Prospect
facility.<P>

The new Morton Grove plant employs more than 1,400 workers.  Constructed on
a 23-acre site, the 302,000 square-foot plant received a High Impact
Business designation from DCCA, enabling the company to realize an
estimated $1.3 million in business incentives, including an investment tax
credit and an exemption from state utility taxes.  DCCA also provided
$500,000 in job training assistance through the Industrial Training Program
(ITP).  The $40 million Mt. Prospect expansion, expected to create 1,500
jobs, also received a High Impact Business designation from DCCA, which
will provide an estimated $2.1 million in business incentives, as well as
commitment from DCCA to provide training assistance to workers.<P>

Lt. Gov. Bob Kustra, the Governor's senior economic development adviser,
said, "As the world-wide demand for information access devices continued to
escalate, we will work with U.S. Robotics and other high technology firms
to ensure that Illinois is a place where these companies can thrive."<P>

Illinois is not only the choice for high-technology industries; it also is
attracting investment from global leaders like McDonald's Corporation,
which is undertaking one of the largest business retention and expansion
projects in the state's history.<P>

McDonald's, which operates 17,400 restaurants in more than 86 nations, will
expand its Oak Brook headquarters, adding as many as 7,000 new jobs over
the next 20 years to the 3,000 jobs currently at the facility.  Mike
Quinlan, McDonald's Chairman and CEO, said," With its excellent business
climate and emphasis on infrastructure improvements, Illinois provides us
with a strong foundation from which we can maximize our Oak Brook home
office support to our global food service business.  We appreciate state
and local government officials working together to support our investment
in Illinois."<P>

Three other recent announcements also solidified Illinois' strength as the
choice for business locations and expansions.<P>Menard, Inc. operates more than 100 retail stores in nine states, including
more than 30 stores in Illinois.  DCCA staff worked closely with company
officials for several months to settle on a location for a new distribution
facility to serve the company's needs.  That search ultimately led to
Plano, where the area's infrastructure (close proximity to rail, three
major interstates and an airport) made it an ideal location for a $20
million distribution center that will serve up to 80 Menard's Home
Improvement stores throughout the Midwest.   The new facility, which will
be completed in two phases, is expected to employ at least 300 people.
GE Lighting, a long-time corporate resident of Mattoon, announced plans in
December to invest $100 million in new production lines at the company's
lamp manufacturing plant.  The modernization project, which will be
assisted through $650,000 in Industrial Training Program (ITP) funds
provided by DCCA, is expected to create 50 new jobs during the next four
years.  An additional 150 jobs will be upgraded and 400 jobs will be
retained at the Mattoon plant, which will produce some of the company's
most sophisticated lighting products.<P>

And Moline's downtown area will benefit with John Deere Health Care's
announcement that it will undertake a $38 million development project,
including a 100,000 square-foot building to house John Deere Health Care's
corporate headquarters, a 15,000 square-foot John Deere Visitor Pavilion
and a new Community Transportation Center.  Plans also call for a new
first-class hotel to accommodate overnight visitors to the area.  Three-
hundred current John Deere Health Care employees and 100 new employees will
work in the new headquarters.  The Pavilion will feature displays and
historic exhibits and is expected to draw up to 400,000 visitors annually.
The Transportation Center will serve as an intercity bus transfer center
and staging area for bus tour groups.  The downtown development project is
being undertaken with more than $1 million in state assistance, including a
$600,000 loan to the City of Moline through DCCA's public infrastructure
program, up to $300,000 in job training funds to assist John Deere Health
Care with worker training, and a $100,000 tourism attraction program grant.
The Illinois Department of Transportation is also expected to provide
infrastructure assistance to help accommodate increased demand for parking
and increased traffic flow on the Arsenal Island Bridge.<P>

<CENTER>###</CENTER>

<HR>
<H3>BRAZILIAN TRADE MISSION HIGHLIGHTS ETHANOL USE</H3>

As the nation's leading producer and consumer of ethanol, Illinois has a
vested interest in the development of ethanol-fueled vehicles for use both
here and abroad.  In keeping with that goal, Norm Marek of DCCA's Bureau of
Energy and Recycling recently participated in a Brazilian trade mission
designed to further efforts to develop and utilize more ethanol-fueled
vehicles in the U.S. and other nations.<P>

Marek joined Wisconsin Gov. Tommy Thompson, Nebraska Gov. Benjamin Nelson
and 15 others, including representatives from two Illinois corporations
that are leading ethanol suppliers, on the six-day Brazilian trade mission.
Participants toured a giant sugar and alcohol production facility at Barra
Bonito and inspected new ethanol/gasahol/flexible fuel vehicles at the
General Motors do Brasil factory at Campanis.  They also attended a
conference on Brazil's experience using ethanol as a transportation fuel.<P>

"Brazil sees a great future for ethanol, especially with known petroleum
reserves dwindling," Marek said.  "Many of their thoughts echoed the
thoughts of those in the Governors' Ethanol Coalition."<P>

A highlight of the trade mission was the announcement by Gov. Thompson that
a cooperative work agreement has been reached between the Governors'
Ethanol Coalition and the State of Sao Paulo, Brazil on the worldwide
promotion of ethanol.<P>

Marek plans to regularly correspond with his Brazilian counterparts to
share information about current ethanol projects underway in Illinois and
keep up with new developments in Brazil.  "I was particularly impressed by
the discussions with the GM-Brazil engineers.  They're currently working on
a compressed natural gas (CNG)/ethanol flexible fuel vehicle.  This could
be an ideal project for Illinois, as it would help to bridge the gap
between ethanol and CNG factions."<P>

<CENTER>###</CENTER>

<HR>
<H3>DCCA ANNOUNCES TENTATIVE 1996 CDAP DEADLINES</H3>

DCCA's Bureau of Community Development has set tentative deadlines for
communities to apply for the 1996 round of grants available through the
popular Community Development Assistance Program (CDAP).<P>

CDAP is a federally-funded block grant program that provides funds to units
of local government, such as cities, villages, townships and counties, that
have  populations of 50,000 or less and are not located within one of the
seven urban counties (Cook, Lake, DuPage, Will, McHenry, Madison and St.
Clair) that receive funds directly from Washington.  Grants are available
for a wide range of projects that benefit low- and moderate-income people,
such as economic development projects that help create new jobs, public
facilities projects that address threats to public health and safety, and
housing rehabilitation.<P>

1996 programs and application deadlines include:<P>

<EM> Economic Development</EM> - Grant funds up to $500,000 are available.  Local
governments may use the funds to loan to a business locating or expanding
in the community to pay for machinery and equipment, working capital, or
building construction and renovation.  As loans are repaid, funds are
deposited into a locally-administered revolving loan fund to be used for
future economic development projects in the community.  Economic
Development grants may also be used to fund infrastructure improvements
directly related to the location or expansion of a business in a community.
These grants are awarded on an as-needed basis throughout the year.<P>

<EM> Planning Assistance</EM> - Local governments may seek grants up to $25,000 to
fund planning activities for future public facilities improvements,
including studies, analyses, data gathering, identification of
implementation actions and preparation of specific plans.  Applications are
judged on a competitive basis and are due on April 16, 1996.  A total of
$500,000 has been allocated for the 1996 round.<P>

<EM> Removal of Architectural Barriers</EM> - Grants up to $150,000 are available to
help local governments remove architectural barriers that restrict those
with disabilities from accessing publicly-owned buildings.  Applications
are judged on a competitive basis and are due on May 6, 1996.  A total of
$1 million is available in 1996.<P>

<EM> Public Facilities Construction/Design Engineering</EM> - Local governments may
compete for grants up to $50,000 for design engineering and up to $400,000
for public facilities construction projects needed to address threats to
public health and safety, such as inadequate water systems or unsafe sewage
treatment facilities.  In 1996, $1 million has been allocated for Design
Engineering grants and $20,860,570 has been earmarked for Public Facilities
Construction grants.  The deadline to apply is July 30, 1996.<P>

<EM> Housing Rehabilitation</EM> - To help ensure that safe, decent housing is
available for low- and moderate-income citizens, local governments may
compete for Housing Rehabilitation grants.  The grants, up to $400,000, are
used to upgrade and expand housing stock in the community.  Applications
are due on October 15, 1996.  A total of $7 million has been allocated for
this component.<P>

<EM> Emergency Public Facilities</EM> - Grants of up to $100,000 are available to
assist local governments when emergencies strike.  Grant funds may be used
to undertake projects that improve public infrastructure and eliminate
threats to public health and safety.  As emergencies may strike at any
time, grants are available on an as-needed basis.  DCCA has allocated $1
million for these grants during 1996.<P>
     
DCCA is also undertaking a three-year transition effort toward a goal of
starting the CDAP Program Year on January 1 of each calendar year.  This
effort is designed to enable DCCA to more expeditiously obligate and expend
CDAP funds.  Program years will be as follows:<P>

Program Year 1995 - June 1, 1995 to March 31, 1996<BR>
Program Year 1996 - April 1, 1996 to December 31, 1996<BR>
Program Year 1997 - January 1, 1997 to December 31, 1997<BR>

To ease problems associated with compressing Program Year 1996 and the
early start of Program Year 1997, DCCA will use its unfunded, eligible
Program Year 1996 Public Facilities applications as the projects to be
funded under Program Year 1997.  This means local governments that
submitted Program Year 1996 Public Facilities applications will not have to
re-submit them in Program Year 1997.<P>

Local governments may contact DCCA to receive CDAP application materials
and guidelines.  Contact Kay Wallwork at DCCA, 620 E. Adams, Springfield,
IL  62701, phone 217/785-7546 (TDD users call 800/785-6055).  For further
information about the Community Development Assistance Program, contact
Jean Thomas at 217/782-6136 (TDD users call 800/785-6055.)<P>

Watch next month's DCCA News for tips on creating a competitive public
facilities grant application!<P>

<CENTER>###</CENTER>

<HR>
<H3>MACLEAN, VER KUILEN NAMED TO KEY POSTS</H3>

Two DCCA veterans have recently been appointed to management positions in
the agency.  Ron Ver Kuilen, whose 15 years at DCCA have included service
as a field scout and manager of the Film Production Unit, has been named
Director of the Illinois Film Office.  Margaret MacLean, who joined DCCA's
International Business Division in 1991 and served as an international
marketing specialist and export promotion officer, has assumed the post of
Division Manager.<P>

As Film Office Director, Ver Kuilen will oversee the state's efforts to
market locations, talent, labor and production expertise to the national
and international film industry.  It's a big job -- since the film office's
inception in 1975, 523 productions have filmed in Illinois contributing
more than $700 million direct cash to the state's economy.<P>

Ver Kuilen has already served as project coordinator for more than 200
productions, including "Home Alone,"  "Field of Dreams," and Groundhog
Day."  But his work is not all glamorous Hollywood lunches and escorting
movie stars.  Most of it involves working with labor, government, business
and community leaders to ensure that doors open for filmmakers, such as
convincing building superintendents to leave the lights on at the Wrigley
Building for a special nighttime shot.  Ver Kuilen has also worked nights,
weekends and even Christmas Day to help filmmakers achieve the effects they
want.<P>

A native of Milwaukee, Ver Kuilen holds bachelor's and master's degrees
from  Northeastern Illinois University.  He is a member of the Association
of Film Commissioners International, manager of his softball team, and was
named 1994's "Facilitator of the Year" by Screen Magazine.<P>

Margaret MacLean's background serves her well as Managing Director of the
International Business Division.  A graduate of Dartmouth College, MacLean
has studied at the Chinese University of Hong Kong through a program
sponsored by Yale University, and at Scripps College in Claremont, CA.  She
also completed a year in Tokyo studying the Japanese language.  She is
conversant in Japanese, Chinese and French.<P>

MacLean comes to her post after five years with the Division, where she
advised Illinois manufacturers on export strategies for Asian markets,
researched and analyzed trade issues, developed and maintained contacts and
relations with government and business officials in the U.S. and Asia,
provided training for small business exporting under NAFTA, orchestrated
official visits for foreign dignitaries, and coordinated trade shows and
trade missions overseas.<P>

As Managing Director, she oversees operations of the state's six foreign
offices, and manages a staff of international trade professionals
headquartered in Chicago and Springfield.  Under her direction, the
Division also is administering a $450,000 grant awarded through the federal
government's Market Development Cooperator Program.  As one of only three
states to receive the grant, Illinois is using its funds to provide direct
financial assistance to enable Illinois companies to participate in trade
missions and trade shows overseas.<P>

<CENTER>###</CENTER>

<HR>
<H3>DCCA'S "ON THE WEB"</H3>

Internet users "surfing" on the World Wide Web can now access information
about DCCA's programs and services!<P>

Located at http://www.accessil.com/dcca/, or through the State Agencies
pick on the State of Illinois home page (http://www. state.il.us.), DCCA's
home page is designed to give Internet users quick, easy access to program
summaries; fact sheets detailing important statistics and information about
Illinois; community profiles; legislation affecting small businesses; and
calendars detailing program deadlines, workshops and other important
information.  In addition, users can access the First-Stop Business
Information Center of Illinois, a new DCCA service that offers valuable
assistance to start-up and small businesses.  First-Stop provides
businesses and individuals with access to information and referral
assistance to guide them through the permitting, licensing and regulatory
processes.  First-Stop also can link them to other available resources that
can help them comply with government regulations and enhance their
competitiveness.<P>

Over the coming months, DCCA will be making other additions and
improvements to its Web site.  One of the most exciting is the anticipated
February debut of a new Illinois Tourism pick specifically designed to help
users plan travel in Illinois.<P>

DCCA also continues to make information available through the Access
Illinois bulletin board system.  Anyone with a PC, modem and communications
software can utilize Access Illinois by calling 217/787-6255, settings
ANSI, 8, N, 1.  The only charge to bulletin board users is for the cost of
the telephone call.<P>

<CENTER>###</CENTER>

