<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>DCCA: 1995 Annual Report -- Bureai of Administration</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#0080C0" ALINK="#0080C0">

<img src="/dcca/graph/logosm.jpg" alt="DCCA Logo" width=165 height=82 align=left>
<img src="/dcca/graph/cbar.gif" width=410 height=4><p>
<h3>
Department of Commerce & Community Affairs<p>
</h3>
<img src="/dcca/graph/cbar.gif" width=410 height=4><p>
<FONT SIZE=+3>1995 Annual Report: Bureau of Administration</FONT>
<BR CLEAR=RIGHT>
<HR>
<p>

DCCA's Bureau of Administration is responsible for the agency's fiscal and
operational functions.  The Division of Fiscal Management includes the
Accounting Office, the Expenditure Planning and Control Office and the
Budget Office.  The Division of Agency Services includes the Office of
Human Resources, the Office of Management Operations and the Office of
Information Resource Management (OIRM).  The Deputy Director of
Administration is also responsible for the activities of the Financial
Commitment Committee, maintaining its master files, meeting minutes and
other paperwork.<p>

<strong>
<a href="#Fiscal Management">Division of Fiscal Management</a><p>
<a href="#Agency Services">Division of Agency Services</a><br>
<ul>
<li><a href="#Human Resources">Office of Human Resources</a><br>
<li><a href="#Management Operations">Office of Management Operations</a><br>
<li><a href="#Information Resource Management">Office of Information Resource Management</a><p>
</ul>

</strong>

<a name="Fiscal Management"><hr></a>
<h3>Division of Fiscal Management</h3>

The Division of Fiscal Management is responsible for DCCA's financial and
budgetary operations.  The Division's three offices include the Budget
Office, the Expenditure Planning and Control Office, and the Accounting
Office.  These offices provide vital links in serving the needs of DCCA's
bureaus and programs.<p>

During Fiscal Year 1995, the Expenditure Planning and Control Office
developed and implemented a pilot program at DCCA that is designed to save
the state thousands of dollars in interest liabilities each year while
reducing paperwork and speeding payments to those receiving state
assistance.  The program, developed by DCCA staffers in partnership with
staffers from the Office of the Comptroller, enables DCCA to send grant
vouchers electronically to the Comptroller's Office and have the payments
electronically deposited directly into grantees' bank accounts.<p>

This action was spurred by the federal Cash Management Improvement Act
(CMIA) that requires states to minimize federal cash on deposit.  Under
CMIA guidelines, the state must pay interest from the moment the federal
funds reach it until the check is cashed and actually clears the treasury.
By reducing the time these funds are kept on deposit, the state's CMIA
liability is reduced.  In Fiscal Year 1995, DCCA realized related savings
of $15,340 by using the pilot electronic vouchering program for grants
subject to CMIA.  DCCA estimates a related savings of more than $150,000 in
Fiscal Year 1996.<p>

Another plus for the new electronic deposit process is an improvement in
the timeframe for processing cash payments.  It enables grantees to receive
funds in about one week as opposed to the three weeks averaged under the
prior manual system.  The success of the pilot program has led DCCA to
expand the process to all programs administered by the Department.  DCCA
staffers also are providing assistance to other state agencies interested
in adopting the process.<p>

In Fiscal Year 1995, DCCA's Budget Office was successful in its efforts to
help obtain increased levels of funding for the agency's Tourism,
International Business, Weatherization and Industrial Services programs for
Fiscal Year 1996.  The Budget Office also played a key role in preparing
for the July 1, 1995 transfer to DCCA of the duties and responsibilities of
the Department of Energy and Natural Resources (ENR) Offices of Energy
Conservation and Alternative Energy, and Coal Marketing and Development,
brought about through Executive Order Number Two.  Through the legislative
appropriation process, the Office of Recycling and Waste Management also
transferred from ENR to DCCA.<p>

During Fiscal Year 1995, electronic cost reporting and payment request
submissions became reality for DCCA subgrant administrators participating
in the pilot Grant Reporting System program.  The efforts were coordinated
by DCCA's Accounting Office.  The test was successfully completed and
support equipment was installed to enable dial-in communications via local
personal computers.  DCCA expects to begin expanding the system to other
subgrantee sites and to extend utilization to additional DCCA programs late
in Fiscal Year 1996.<p>


<a name="Agency Services"><hr></a>
<h3>Division of Agency Services</h3>

<a name="Human Resources"><br></a>
<h4>Office of Human Resources</h4>

During Fiscal Year 1995, the Office of Human Resources processed more than
650 transactions for agency employees.  Office staff reviewed more than 165
files to ensure compliance with the Rutan decision in agency hiring
practices.  The files were found to be in good order when pre-audited by
staff from the Illinois Department of Central Management Services.  The
Office also was involved in ensuring a smooth transition for staffers of
the former Illinois Department of Energy and Natural Resources who became
DCCA employees as a result of the agency consolidation ordered by Gov.
Edgar.<p>

Ongoing services provided by the Office of Human Resources during Fiscal
Year 1995 included announcements of training available to employees,
assistance with insurance and payroll concerns, and services provided to
citizens of Illinois and surrounding states regarding employment
opportunities with the State of Illinois.<p>

<a name="Management Operations"><br></a>
<h4>Office of Management Operations</h4>

The Office of Management Operations provides support to DCCA, including
facility management, printing and graphic services, publication management
and distribution, the Illinois Business Hotline, property control,
purchasing and mail/messenger services.<p>

In Fiscal Year 1995, Management Operations facilitated the upgrading of
several agency motor pool vehicles, thus ensuring access to safe,
reasonably-priced transportation for DCCA personnel operating in the field.
The Office processed 3,197 purchase requisitions for DCCA's goods and
negotiated and maintained more than 50 service and maintenance agreements.
Mail and messenger services processed in excess of 400,000 pieces of mail
and completed more than 2,821 special deliveries in and around Springfield.<p>

Management Operations also upgraded its in-house printing plant.  The new
equipment will enable the printshop to meet the growing demand for
professionally prepared brochures and publications that support the
agency's programs and projects.  The Graphics Unit processed more than 435
work orders including complete in-house development and production of
program reports and the agency's Annual Report.  The in-house printing
plant produced nearly nine million impressions in response to 663 work
orders.  The unit also prepared more than 11 customized presentation
booklets for use in response to inquiries from various businesses and
industries.<p>

The Information and Distribution Center handled more than 180 work orders
involving more than 340,000 pieces of material for distribution.  Although
approximately 90,000 pieces were handled by in-house staff, handling
250,000 pieces as bulk mail through a contract mail house saved thousands
of dollars in postage.  The Information and Distribution Center provided
more than 10,000 labels and listings to partners from outside the agency,
responded to more than 15,000 school children from around the world who
requested information on Illinois, and prepared and mailed more than 3,600
general tourism packets in response to written requests.<p>

The warehouse rebuilt shelving and restructured record storage allowing for
more effective utilization of space.<p>

<a name="Information Resource Management"><br></a>
<h4>Office of Information Resource Management</h4>

In Fiscal Year 1995, DCCA entered the world of E-mail and automation via
the Local Area Network (LAN) arena.  Implementation of the LAN-based
environment began early in Fiscal 1994 and, by the conclusion of Fiscal
Year 1995, approximately half of DCCA's staff were part of the new
environment.<p>

DCCA's shift during Fiscal Year 1995 into technological high gear has led
to consideration of the productivity gains possible from utilizing office
suite packages, the Internet, and Geographical Information Systems (GIS),
enhanced communications and information exchange, geographical presentation
of information and to transient computing and communications.<p>

During the fiscal year, OIRM completed projects providing computer support
for Fiscal Management systems, provided the general computer support for
the CMS host mainframe system, including IHWAP and LIHEAP energy systems,
and was involved in the planning of JTPA system changes.<p>

OIRM continues to focus on:<p>

<ul type=square>
<li> providing an improved level of responsiveness and technical support for
the DCCA LAN and CMS host-based environments.<p>
<li> providing timely development and maintenance of the computer systems and
applications.<p>
<li> providing recommendations for future products, projects and directions for
DCCA.<p>
</ul>


The solid foundation has now been built that should allow for continued
technological growth, with plans underway to complete the LAN
implementation and move forward to LAN-based applications and systems.<p>


<P>
<HR>
<STRONG>| <A HREF="http://www.ilcommerce.com">DCCA Home Page</A> | <A HREF="/dcca/menus/95annrep.htm">1995 Annual Report</A> |</STRONG>
</BODY>
