<li><a href="#Energy Audit Training">Energy Audit Training</a><br>
<li><a href="#PIE">Partners in Environmental Education (PIE)</a><p>
</ul>
</h4>


<a name="Office of Recycling"><hr></a>
<h3>OFFICE OF RECYCLING AND WASTE REDUCTION</h3>


<a name="Materials Recycling"><br></a>
<h4>Materials Recycling Unit</h4>

The goal of the Materials Recycling Unit is to increase the quantity of materials recycled in Illinois and to establish self-sufficiency in the recycling industry.  Since its inception in 1987, the Materials Recycling Unit and Recycling Grants Program have awarded more than $12 million in recycling collection and processing grants to more than 300 applicants.  These grants have leveraged well over $50 million in matching investments.<p>

More than $1 million in state funds were awarded to 22 grant applicants in Fiscal Year 1995.  Funded projects included:<p>
<ul type=square>
<li> A $100,000 grant to help Laidlaw Waste Systems in Rockford develop a modern primary processing recycling facility to service more than 400,000 citizens.  Grant funds are being used to purchase a high-technology baler.  This facility will incorporate state-of-the-art technology, including co-mingled sort lines and a pneumatic baler feed stream to convey sorted plastics and metals to densification equipment.  Five different material streams will be processed at the facility.<p>
<li> A $50,000 grant to the U.S. Postal Service to implement a commercial collection recycling project in its Northern Illinois district.  This project will collect materials from approximately 200 U.S. Post Offices in Northern Illinois.  It is projected that 56 tons will be diverted from landfills each day.<p>
<li> A $44,000 grant to the City of Mattoon to implement a city-wide drop-off project.  Funds were used for the purchase of compartmentalized collection containers and educational materials.  The project features three controlled drop-off sites for the citizens of Mattoon and the surrounding areas.  The City contributed more than $86,000 in matching funds.<p>
</ul>


<a name="Market Development"><br></a>
<h4>Market Development</h4>

The Recycling Market Development Program encourages private-sector investment in the development, manufacture and marketing of products containing recycled materials.  Through this program, more than $1 million in grants and loans were awarded during Fiscal Year 1995, matched by more than $4.5 million in private investment.<p>

Projects funded in Fiscal Year 1995 included:<p>
<ul type=square>
<li> A $90,000 grant to the J. M. Hoffman Company of Joliet.  The grant will help purchase specialized equipment to be used to re-mill salvageable lumber from industrial and commercial buildings being demolished.  The company remanufactures the lumber into high quality decorative paneling and flooring for residential and commercial construction.<p>
<li> Five new projects totaling $130,365 were funded under a legislatively-mandated market development program promoting the use of recycled materials by businesses located in economically depressed areas.  Future Generations in Taylor Springs, Molten Glass in Chicago, Laser Smart in Mt. Carmel, Innovative Components in Arlington Heights, and The Chicago Lighthouse for the Blind were the companies that received grants in Fiscal Year 1995.<p>
<li> The Container Recycling Alliance in Chicago received a $150,000 grant to assist with the purchase of specialized sorting equipment that will be able to optically separate container glass by color.  This new technology, believed to be the first of its type to be used in Illinois, will help eliminate the problem of mixed color broken glass.  The color-sorted glass will be easier to use in the remanufacture of glass containers.<p>
</ul>


<a name="ICAP"><br></a>
<h4>Illinois College Assistance Program (ICAP)</h4>

This program provides Illinois public colleges with technical and financial assistance to support waste education and recycling activities. <p> 

In Fiscal Year 1995, ICAP provided $104,000 to various colleges for planning and implementation grants.  Approximately $1.45 million has been earmarked for grants to these institutions to implement waste reduction plans during Fiscal Year 1996 and Fiscal Year 1997.<p>


<a name="Used Tire Recovery"><br></a>
<h4>Used Tire Recovery</h4>

The Used Tire Recovery Program provides financial assistance to units of government and private industry to identify innovative and cost-effective alternatives to stockpiling and/or landfilling scrap tires.  Grants and loans totaling more than $2.2 million were awarded in Fiscal Year 1995 to projects reusing, processing and recycling discarded tires into new products, such as retreaded and remanufactured tires, tire chip playground material, rubber-modified asphalt and tire-derived fuel.  These funds leveraged an additional $2.39 million for project costs.<p>

During Fiscal Year 1995, the program:<p>
<ul type=square>
<li> Awarded a $457,380 grant to Illinois Power Company to assist in the purchase and installation of tire-derived fuel handling and metering equipment, as well as slag cleaning equipment.  Waste Recovery - Illinois will be providing Illinois Power with 60,000 tons of tire-derived fuel per year, or the equivalent of 7.5 million passenger tire equivalents.  Waste Recovery - Illinois received a $500,000 grant from the Used Tire Recovery Program in Fiscal Year 1994 for tire-derived fuel processing equipment.<p>
<li> Provided a $500,000 grant to Pace-Mat, Inc. of Genoa to assist in the purchase and installation of crumb rubber processing equipment and recycled tire-derived rubber mat production equipment.  Products that will eventually be produced include anti-fatigue mats, gymnasium mats, anti-corrosive liners, highway culvert liners, animal mats, floor protection mats, and noise reduction flooring.  At full production, an estimated 665,000 passenger tire equivalents will be used annually.<p>
<li> Awarded a $210,000 grant to Achievor Tire, L.P. of Chicago to expand the existing manufacturer of used tires.  Remanufacturing differs from normal retreading in that new rubber is placed not only on the tread portion, but the shoulder and sidewall as well.  The tire casing is then put in a mold similar to how a new tire is produced.  The funds provided assisted in the purchase of new molds and sidewall plates for tire sizes that Achievor could not produce.  With the tire industry constantly producing new tire sizes and creating a demand for replacement tires, Achievor must buy new molds to remain competitive.  Achievor Tire has predicted that as many as 500,000 remanufactured tires could be produced over a five-year period by the equipment that was purchased with this grant.<p>
</ul>

<a name="Solid Waste Management"><br></a>
<h4>Solid Waste Management Research</h4>

The Solid Waste Management Research Program provides the foundation for future developments and improvements in solid waste management.  Funded research projects not only extend to the basic scientific, engineering, economic and sociological information available to planners, but also provide training and education for today's graduate students who will become tomorrow's solid waste experts.<p>

During Fiscal Year 1995, the University of Illinois Institute for Environmental Studies received a $400,000 grant to continue its competitive solid waste research grants.  This program offers two grant rounds annually.  Research programs may span the entire spectrum of solid waste management from reducing the environmental impact of landfilling and incineration, to expanding the uses of recycled materials, to understanding the public response to waste reduction education.<p>

The research program also provides funding for the Illinois State Geological Survey's (ISGS) landfill siting assistance program.  The Fiscal Year 1995 grant of $188,897 will allow ISGS to use its experts in Illinois Geology and computer Geographic Information Systems (GIS) to assist counties in locating geologically-capable sites for landfills.<p>

The Solid Waste Management Research Program provided a $127,342 grant to the University of Illinois at Chicago School of Public Health to publish a technical newsletter intended to transfer information and research results to the government and industry planners who can put it to use.  An in-depth report on the conflicts and compatibilities of recycling and incineration is currently in preparation.<p>  

<a name="Tech Demonstration"><br></a>
<h4>Technology Demonstration</h4>

The Technology and Practices Demonstration Program supports the development and application of technologies and practices that minimize the land disposal of solid waste.  During Fiscal Year 1995, approximately $735,000 was awarded, which was matched by more than $1.1 million in private investment.<p>

Among projects awarded were:<p>
<ul type=square>
<li> A $150,000 grant to Eaglebrook Products, Inc. for the purchase of a twin extruder system to determine effective methods of compounding mixtures of high-melt, post-consumer, non-bottle plastic packaging waste with softwood fibers.  The intended end-market uses for the composite products include, but are not limited to, door and window substrata, millwork, agricultural and playground equipment, transportation equipment, and industrial flooring.<p>
<li> A $149,991 grant to Brookfield Zoo for the demonstration of an enclosed, aerated static pile composting system to control odor in the composting of animal wastes and bedding.<p>
<li> A $99,000 grant to the City of Streator for testing of "glasphalt" as an alternative aggregate for use as a durable road material.<p>
</ul>

<a name="School Education"><br></a>
<h4>School Education Program</h4>

The School Education Program provides financial and technical assistance to Illinois schools to implement recycling and waste reduction activities in the schools.<p>

The 1995-96 School Grant program awarded more than $220,000 to 20 projects involving 531 Illinois schools with approximately 250,000 students.  The grant money is used to purchase collection containers, implement source reduction activities, provide teachers and classroom training, and for trips and assemblies for the students to learn about the "3Rs" -- Reduce, Reuse and Recycle.  Vermi composting for classrooms at the elementary level was the most popular source reduction activity during the year.  Nearly 200 composting bins were purchased with funds from the grant, and several schools received grants to purchase reusable cafeteria dishes and serviceware, as well as slates for individual use, thus reducing waste at their schools.  In addition, grantees will spend a minimum of $22,000 toward the purchase of products with recycled content.<p>

The School Education Program also develops educational materials for teachers to help them address the 3Rs, provides teacher training on the 3Rs at various locations around the state, and publishes a quarterly newsletter.<p>

A program offered to all public and private Illinois schools is the Earth Flag program.  To earn an Earth Flag, schools must:<p>
<ul type=square>
<li> Recycle white paper.<br>
<li> Provide teacher training on the 3Rs.<br>
<li> Implement one schoolwide source reduction activity.<br>
<li> Implement at least one schoolwide reuse activity.<br>
<li> Instruct at least one grade level or science class or ecology club on the 3Rs.<br>
</ul>

More than 350 schools have registered to receive an Earth Flag.<p>


<a name="Energy Conservation & Alternative Energy"><hr></a>
<h3>OFFICE OF ENERGY CONSERVATION AND ALTERNATIVE ENERGY</h3>

During Fiscal Year 1995, the Office of Energy Conservation and Alternative Energy continued to promote the efficient and economic use of Illinois' energy resources.  The Office tests and demonstrates energy technologies, identifies innovative means of financing energy efficiency improvements, and uses a variety of educational programs to transfer these cost effective technologies and information to both the private and public sectors of the Illinois economy.<p>


<h4><a name="Affordable Housing">Affordable Housing Programs</a></h4>

The Office has conducted a number of programs designed to demonstrate the vital role of energy efficiency in the design, construction or rehabilitation of affordable housing units.  During Fiscal Year 1995, in cooperation with not-for-profit developers, the Office provided grants and technical assistance for the energy efficient rehab of 53 multi-unit structures with more than 1,000 dwelling units.  The grants upgraded this low-and moderate-income housing to ensure that it is truly affordable by producing savings averaging 60 percent and lowering annual utility bills to under $200. <p>

The Office also demonstrated energy efficient building technologies in newly constructed homes.  More than 200 new homes were designed and constructed in cooperation with the City of Chicago under the "New Homes for Chicago Program."  These homes were developed and marketed to moderate income families in the city.  The energy efficiency improvements dramatically lowered annual utility costs, which greatly enhances the affordability of the homes.<p>

In cooperation with the Illinois Department of Public Aid, the Office provided grants and technical assistance to homeless shelter providers.  Grants of up to $20,000 per shelter were given to enable shelter providers to reduce their utility costs by up to 40 percent and utilize the savings for supplementing budgets to provide actual services to the homeless.<p>

During Fiscal Year 1995, the Office also disseminated information and efficiency technology demonstrated by the Affordable Housing projects to the homebuilding industry and other housing providers through seminars, conferences and housing-related workshops.  For example, a major homebuilding conference was held in the Greater Chicago area in February 1995, and the Office will sponsor the nation's largest weatherization conference, the "Affordable Housing Conference," in March 1996.<p>


<h4><a name="Ethanol Programs">Ethanol Programs</a></h4>

The Office of Energy Conservation and Alternative Energy worked with Illinois agricultural organizations during Fiscal Year 1995 to actively promote and expand the use of ethanol as a clean burning, renewable transportation fuel.  Illinois leads the nation in the annual production of ethanol, and ranks first or second in the production of corn each year.<p>

The Office manages numerous ethanol test and demonstration projects designed to encourage economic growth in industrial manufacturing and rural communities.  The agency also sponsors the research and development of new and innovative technologies to help reduce ethanol production costs.  A few milestones during Fiscal Year 1995:<p>
<ul type=square>
<li> The state continued to promote E-85 flexible-fuel vehicles by purchasing 71 1995 Ford Taurus sedans for use in the state fleet.  These vehicles were manufactured at Ford's south Chicago assembly plant.  Illinois operates the largest E-85 fleet in the nation.<p>
<li>  The number of state E-85 refueling facilities in Illinois was expanded and plans were completed for the first public E-85 refueling facility at Dwight.<p>
<li> Plans were announced for the state to begin testing three of the first flexible fuel E-85 Chevrolet S-10 pickup trucks for General Motors Corporation.  GM has announced that, beginning in 1997, all Chevrolet S-10 and GMC Sonoma trucks equipped with the 2.2-liter four-cylinder engine will be flexible fuel vehicles optimized for ethanol fuel.<p>
<li> Office staff laid plans for the organization and sponsorship of the Ethanol Exposition at the 1995 Illinois State Fair.<p>
</ul>


<h4><a name="Assist to Agriculture">Assistance to Agriculture</a></h4>

Through the Office of Energy Conservation and Alternative Energy, direct energy conservation, energy management, environment and renewable resource information was provided to more than 17,000 Illinois farmers and agricultural professionals through a series of 140 conferences, seminars and meetings.
Staffers worked closely with the Illinois Cooperative Extension Service and more than 30 Illinois farm organizations and groups to provide Illinois farmers with sound environmental practices and proven, practical methods of reducing energy costs on the farm.<p>

The Office also provides incentives to farmers to conduct on-farm sustainable agriculture research to demonstrate methods to maintain farm profits while reducing the environmental impact of conventional farming practices.<p>


<h4><a name="Energy Wise Homes">Energy Wise Homes of Illinois</a></h4>

The Office of Energy Conservation and Alternative Energy promotes a residential energy rating system called "Energy Wise Homes of Illinois."  The ratings help builders and homeowners understand the overall energy costs associated with a home.  Letting people know where their energy dollars are being spent helps them make financial decisions concerning energy products during new construction or in retrofitting their homes.  The rating is an essential tool when applying for energy efficient mortgages.<p>


<h4><a name="Energy Performance">Energy Performance Contracting</a></h4>

The Office of Energy Conservation and Alternative Energy promotes energy performance contracting for larger institutional or industrial energy users.  Performance contracting is an innovative arrangement for financing and installing energy improvement projects where the savings generated are guaranteed to amortize the project over the life of the agreement.<p>  

During Fiscal Year 1995, the office staff initiated a $20 million investment in energy efficiency capital improvements in state facilities.  Gov. Edgar's Energy Efficiency Pilot Initiative demonstrated the cost effectiveness of utilizing energy performance contracts in state buildings.  The pilot program utilized private certificates of participation to finance the projects, which will produce energy savings of more than $21 million annually in seven state agency and university facilities.<p>  

In addition, staffers continued to provide technical assistance and information transfer to other units of federal, state and local government, as well as school districts which are interested in exploring energy performance contracting arrangements.<p>


<h4><a name="Energy Efficiency">Energy Efficiency in State Buildings</a></h4>

Operators of state facilities were provided energy engineering assistance and ongoing energy efficiency training during Fiscal Year 1995.  These efforts resulted in documented savings of $6 million in operation and maintenance costs at 38 participating facilities.<p>  

Development of databases involving refrigerants and electronically transferred utility information continued.  This information will aid facilities in tracking their energy use.<p>


<h4><a name="ICP">Institutional Conservation Program (ICP)</a></h4>

ICP is a grant program for schools and hospitals to help them reduce energy consumption.  The program has completed 17 grant cycles totaling $56.4 million, and provides two types of energy grants:  Technical Assistance Grants and Energy Conservation Measures Grants.  Technical Assistance grants are available to institutions to hire Illinois registered architects or engineers to complete a detailed energy study.  Energy Conservation Measures grants provide funds for the actual retrofits.  Both types of grants require matching funds.<p>


<h4><a name="Telecommuting">Telecommuting and Transportation Programs</a></h4>

The Office of Energy Conservation and Alternative Energy actively worked with Chicago area agencies during Fiscal Year 1995 to reduce motor fuel consumption and air emissions through distribution of an office-produced video on vanpooling, as well as technical assistance provided to the Chicago Area Transportation Study.  Office staffers actively worked to organize and provide leadership to the Metro Chicago Telecommuting Advisory Council, an organization of telecommuters, employers, vendors and other agencies that see telecommuting as a strategy for air quality improvement, as well as motor fuel conservation.<p>


<h4><a name="Energy Emergency Preparedness">Energy Emergency Preparedness</a></h4>

The Office provides direct energy emergency preparedness support to the Illinois Emergency Management Agency (IEMA) during emergency and disaster situations.  Provided under the requirements of the Illinois Emergency Operations Plan, the Office coordinates information and communications regarding the availability and distribution of energy resources within Illinois and throughout the region.  This support is guided by national program objectives established by the Federal Emergency Management Agency (FEMA) and the U.S. Department of Energy.<p>


<h4><a name="ILEED">Illinois Energy Education Development (ILEED)</a></h4>

ILEED is an effective energy and environmental education program for students in kindergarten through grade 12 that incorporates all disciplines and learning styles and promotes leadership and organizational skills.  More than 2,500 members are active in student-developed energy and environmental projects that benefit students, their schools and communities.<p>  


<h4><a name="High School Internships">High School Internships</a></h4>

The Office coordinates internships for high school students who work as paid professionals with energy and environmental organizations in their communities.  Opportunities include:<p>
<ul type=square>
<li> Working as a public servant in various government agencies, such as the U.S. Forest Service.<p>
<li> Establishing various solid waste programs for city governments and for a mental health facility.<p>
<li> Performing various tasks in federal and private laboratories.<p>
</ul>

In Fiscal 1995, the office coordinated efforts that enabled 10 students to participate in the internship program.<p>  


<h4><a name="Energy Audit Training">Energy Audit Training</a></h4>

Student and teacher representatives from more than 40 Illinois junior high and high schools participate in EnergyNet.  EnergyNet provides a real life context for teaching math, science, business and telecommunications skills.  Students and teachers are provided in-depth, hands-on energy management training, as well as up-to-date information on telecommunications.  These skills are used to train other students to work in programs that save their schools energy and money.<p>

In Fiscal Year 1995, the Office and Ameritech's EnergyNet program provided a computer networking system for all participating schools.  Students shared energy auditing data through the EnergyNet system.<p>


<h4><a name="PIE">Partners in Environmental Education (PIE)</a></h4>

The Illinois Chamber of Commerce and the Office of Energy Conservation and Alternative Energy have established a partnership between businesses and schools to promote environmental education.  Partners in Environmental Education (PIE) links schools with companies and businesses that offer equipment, internships, training, instructional materials, facility tours or expertise in natural resource conservation and environmental protection.<p>

During Fiscal Year 1995, PIE provided: <p>
<ul type=square>
<li> Outdoor classrooms on Illinois Power property where students learned to create prairies and protect wetlands.<p>
<li> Funding for biodegradable plastic bags by Abbott Labs to be used in conjunction with the Illinois Department of Conservation's "Kids for Conservation" program.<p>
<li> Preparation of a solid waste curriculum supported by Kraft General Foods Environmental Institute.<p>
</ul>


<hr>
<strong>
* Programs of the Bureau of Energy and Recycling were under the direction of the Illinois Department of Energy and Natural Resources during Fiscal Year 1995.  The programs became a part of DCCA in Fiscal Year 1996. 
</strong>

<P>
