<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>DCCA: Outlook for the Illinois Coal Industry</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#000000" VLINK="#8080C0" ALINK="#000080">

<img src="/dcca/graph/logosm.jpg" alt="DCCA Logo" width=165 height=82 align=left>
<img src="/dcca/graph/cbar.gif" width=410 height=4><p>
<h3>
Department of Commerce & Community Affairs<p>
</h3>
<img src="/dcca/graph/cbar.gif" width=410 height=4><p>
<FONT SIZE=+3>Outlook for the Illinois Coal Industry</FONT>
<BR CLEAR=RIGHT>
<HR>


<h2 align=center>EXECUTIVE SUMMARY</h2>


<h4 align=center>Prepared by

Gary R. Philo<br>
and Daniel E. Keefe<br>
Illinois Department of Commerce & Community Affairs<p>

and<p>

David W. South<br>
and Koby A. Bailey<br>
Argonne National Laboratory<p>

December 1995<p>
</h4>
<hr>
<h3 align=center>NOTE</h3>

This report was prepared by the authors for the Illinois Coal Development Board. Neither the Illinois Department of Commerce and Community Affairs nor any of its subcontractors, nor the Illinois Coal Development Board, nor any person acting on behalf of either makes any warranty or representation, express or implied, with respect to the accuracy or completeness of the information contained in this report, or assumes any liabilities with respect to the uses of, or for damages resulting from the use of any information disclosed in this report. Reference herein to any specific commercial enterprise does not necessarily constitute or imply its endorsement, recommendation or favoring by the Illinois Coal Development Board.<p>

A portion of this report was prepared by researchers at the Argonne National Laboratory that has since moved on to new positions. David South is now affiliated with Energy Resources International, Inc., a consulting firm in Washington, D.C. Koby Bailey is now affiliated with the Illinois Commerce Commission with his office in Chicago, Illinois.<p>

Copies of this report may be obtained from:<p>

Illinois Department of Commerce & Community Affairs<br>
Office of Coal Development and Marketing<br>
325 W. Adams Street, 3rd Floor<br>
Springfield, IL  62704-1892<br>
(217) 782-6370<br>
TDD: (217) 785-0021<p>

<hr>
<h3 align=center>
The Illinois Coal Development Board<br>
December 1995
</h3>

Dennis R. Whetstone, Illinois Department of Commerce and Community Affairs, Chairman of the Illinois Coal Development Board<p>

Brent Manning, Illinois Department of Natural Resources<p>

Richard J. Brooks, Freeman United Coal Company<p>

Linda Denton, Rend Lake Community College<p>

Carolyn J. Ehlert, Deere & Company<p>

Edgar Hale, Arch of Illinois<p>

Richard E. Newtson, A.G. Edwards & Sons, Inc.<p>

Representative David Phelps, Illinois General Assembly<p>

Carol L. Rowe, CW3M Company<p>

Don Tolva, BHC Company<p>

Porter Womeldorff, Illinois Power Company<p>

<hr>

<h2 align=center>Executive Summary</h2>


The Illinois coal industry experienced limited recovery in 1994 from the depressed production levels of 1993.  The 1993 United Mine Workers strike and RAIL curtailment from flooding resulted in an 18.5 million ton drop in production and deliveries that year.  Annual coal production rebounded to 54 million tones in 1994, ten percent off the 1970-1990 historical average of 60 million tons.  A declining market for Illinois coal is projected through 2000, as a result of strict limits on emissions of sulfur dioxide (SO2) placed on utilities by Title IV of the Clean Air Act Amendments of 1990 (CAAA).  After 2000, implementation of Phase II of the CAAA, as well as growing demand for electric capacity should help to reverse this trend.  Even so, Illinois coal production is not likely to approach 60 million tons per year within the foreseeable future to satisfy the domestic market.  A penetration of off-shore markets could mitigate the downward trend.<p>

Utility sales in the U.S. account for 90 percent of coal sales.  Near-term forecasts for domestic utility purchases during Phase I of the CAAA (1995-1999) are not encouraging.  Under there present scenario, utility purchases of Illinois coal are projected to drop to 36 million tons in 1995 and 29 million tons in 2000.  During Phase II, Illinois coal should rebound somewhat based on projected growth in coal-fired generation, although these gains are not expected to return Illinois coal to pre-1990 utility consumption levels unless non-traditional markets are accessed.  Furthermore, as spot purchases become more common and log-term contracts dwindle, the economic foundation for many Illinois coal producers will erode.<p>

Several companies announced mine closures during 1994 and 1995.  Peabody Coal closed its No. 10 Mine on August 5, 1994, ending 43 years of operation.  Three hundred forty miners were released.  Peabody cited its inability to find new customers for the high-sulfur coal.  Old Ben No. 24 and Zeigler No. 11 will be idled in the first quarter of 1996 while Old Ben No.26 will be idled in the third quarter of 1996.  Freeman said the suspension was the result of weak demand caused by environmental restrictions on the use of Illinois high-sulfur coal.<p>



<h3>ACTUAL AND PROJECTED UTILITY PURCHASES OF ILLINOIS COAL</h3>
<pre>
<strong>                               Illinois Coal Purchases (thousands of tons)
