</pre>

<hr>
<center><img src="/dcca/graph/coal1.gif" width=429 height=300></center><p>
<p>



Mine employment for the year continued a historical decline that began in the early 1970s.  Illinois coal mines employed 10,129, 9,667 and 8,831 miners in 1990. 1991 and 1992, respectively.  Illinois mine employment in 1993 dropped to a low of 4,257 at the peak of the UMWA strike, but ended with 7,389 miner employed.  By the end of 1994, total mine employment dropped to 6,663 miners, reflecting two trends in the Illinois coal industry - shrinking employment due to increased productivity and a declining number of mine operations as a consequence of the CAAA.  Projection estimate that mine employment will drop to 5,800 miner by 1995 and 5,250 miner by 2000 (roughly half the 1990 level).<p>

As a result of shrinking number of mine operations and employed miners, annual personal income for Illinois is expected to fall from 1994 levels by $183 million in 1995 and $309 million in 2000.  Consequently, annual state tax revenues are projected to decline from 1994 levels by as much as $13 million in 1995 and $22 million by 2000.  Reductions in coal operator contributions to the state unemployment insurance program show a similar pattern.  At the same time as these contribution fall, benefits paid out by the state for displaced mining jobs will increase and could potentially reach a cumulative total of $135 million for the 1990-2000 period.<p>


<center><img src="/dcca/graph/coal2.gif" alt="Actual and Projected Mine Employment in Illinois" width=433 height=273></center>

<p>
The CAAA will be a dominant factor shaping utility fuel decisions over the next five to ten years.  Phase I of Title IV of the CAAA, which took effect in 1995, covers 110 generating stations; 263 units nationwide.  affected utilities have largely implemented their phase I compliance plans for SO2; and NOx compliance will be required in 1996.  Phase I (and Phase II) SO2 compliance can be accomplished through fuel-based controls, post-combustion emission controls, reduced emission generation technology or strategic compliance planning (incorporating a combination of strategies).<p>

Phase I compliance choice across the nation is dominated by fuel switching/blending have chosen to completely eliminate the use of high-sulfur interior coals.  twenty-seven units have or will install flue gas desulfurization equipment (fgds), 31 units switched fuels completely to comply with prior state regulations, one unit has been repowered, seven will be retired and the remainder (52) of phase I units will employ allowance-based compliance strategies exclusively.<p>

Phase II of the CAAA affects 958 fossil fuel-fired generating stations (2,913 units) beginning January 1, 2000.  Preliminary Phase II compliance plans on file generally indicate a preference for further fuel switching/blending with lower sulfur coals or potential co- or seasonal-firing with natural gas.  use of banked phase I SO2 allowances appears to be a popular Phase II compliance strategy while repowering and FGD installation are not prominently featured.<p>


<center><img src="/dcca/graph/coal3.gif" alt="Utility Purchases of Illinois Coal" width=475 height=323></center>
<p>

Other environmental issues linger for Phase II compliance beyond SO2 control.  Title IV of the CAAA established a national standard for annual SO2 emissions.  CAAA NOx regulations, on the other hand, are contained in both Title IV and Title I.  Although implemented at a later date, no control decisions will have an impact on SO2 compliance decisions.  Similarly, Title III hazardous air pollutant (HAP) standards may impact Phase II units using Illinois coal,  depending on the type of HAP regulated and the level of HAP emission control required.  Regional haze or visibility controls and greenhouse gas emission standards (CO2 regulation) could also impact Phase II compliance strategies and subsequently, Illinois coal sales.<p>

As electric utilities move through Phase I and into Phase II, restructuring will emerge as the major issue.  Any changes in the structure of the electric utility industry will affect Phase II compliance decisions.  Competition between utilities, capacity decisions and stranded investment rulings are projected to force generators to minimize generating costs.  There may be opportunities for Illinois coal to penetrate these evolving electricity markets.  A competitive electric utility industry, driven by the need for efficient generation and Phase II compliance decisions, may place a premium on an efficient fuel source such as Illinois coal in conjunction with emission control technology.  However, if utilities are uncertain that the capital cost of fuel or technology can be recovered, there may be a reluctance to employ this strategy in favor of switching to a low cost, low emission fuel source.<p>

While the trends in Illinois coal production have been negative, there are occasional sign of hope.  Catlin Coal Company has initiated efforts to open a new mine in Vermillion county.  Initial permitting for the Riola Mine began with approval by the Illinois Mining Board in August, 1995.  The first coal from this operation is expected in mid-1996.  Lauhoff Grain Company of Danville will be the principal customer for the riola coal.<p>

Other opportunities to mitigate market losses do exist.  Phase II will affect practically all coal fired units nationwide.  utilities which use their so2 emission allowances for Phase I compliance can delay a fuel choice decision until Phase II.  At that point, these units may be persuaded to retrofit or repower in order to continue using illinois coal.  an innovative so2 emission allowance policy could be developed by the state as an incentive for purchasers of illinois coal.. international marketing opportunities are also being explored.  Many nations are in desperate need of new electric generating capacity.  Illinois coal should be poised to take advantage of these expanding markets.<p>

Illinois must make sacrifices to preserve its coal industry and the socioeconomic stability of its mining communities.  Economic incentives to stimulate illinois coal sales should be explored to maintain illinois coal markets for illinois coal while generating jobs and revenues for the state.<p>

Consideration should be given to the increased us of SO2 allowances to encourage Illinois coal use.  The State of Illinois should assess SO2 allowance alternatives to determine whether they can become a component of incentive packages for current and potential domestic consumers of Illinois coal.  Allowances are a unique financial instrument created by the CAAA to regulate compliance with emission reduction requirements.  They can be purchased in several ways, sold, traded or baked for future use, and there are no ownership restriction.  One option which has been discussed in the past is "Bundling" allowances with coal at the point of sale to offset resulting SO2 emissions.  Another option would have the state purchase, hold and distribute allowances to encourage the use of Illinois coal.  There are many potential scenarios worth investigating for using SO2 allowances as incentives for marketing Illinois coal.<p>



<center><img src="/dcca/graph/coal4.gif" alt="Growth in World Coal Consumption, 1992-2005" width=369 height=298></center>


Preserving market share is an important objective of the state's coal policy.  Another equally important objective should be to seek out new international markets for Illinois coal.  According to the Energy Information Administration, worldwide demand for electricity is projected to increase by six trillion kilowatt-hours by the year 2010, with coal retaining the primary share of the generating market (>35 percent).  Additionally, the United States Department of Energy projects that by 2010, worldwide demand for power generating technologies and services will create a $200 billion export market.  The Office of Coal Development and Marketing, now associated with the Department of Commerce and Community Affairs, is ideally positioned to collaborate on a coal export initiative.  Increasing Illinois coal exports and international market share will be a critical factor in the preservation of the industry.<p>

The state should continue to support development of markets through research on high-sulfur coal, development of promising techniques and processes and commercial demonstration of proven clean coal technologies.  State programs should be modified to: accelerate refinement and commercialization of advanced coal combustion technology; broaden the scope of potential clean coal demonstration projects for state participation to include those which serve to promote or preserve the use of Illinois coal and coal byproducts; support Illin ois industries involved in the design, engineering, manufacture and installation of clean coal technologies.<p>

The CAAA are proving costly for the Illinois coal industry.  This federal legislation gained widespread support due in large part to emotional arguments rather than scientific facts.  The lessons for Illinois to learn is the importance of closely monitoring national environmental initiatives that could further threaten the Illinois coal industry.  Where feasible, the state should actively participate in the development of federal legislative and regulatory proposals that are favorable to the producers and consumers of Illinois coal.  The state should continue to discourage an incremental approach to pollutant regulation which could disproportionately impact Illinois and further deteriorate its already weakened competitive position.<p>

One important national policy debate currently underway centers on reform of the electric utility industry.  Whatever reforms eventually emerge will affect the coal industry.  The state should closely monitor electric utility regulatory reform efforts at both the federal and state levels.  New opportunities for Illinois coal will appear in a competitive electricity market, where fuel choice decision will be made based on long -term efficiency instead of short-term cost advantage.  The overriding concern of Illinois coal interests must be to ensure that reform in the name of a more competitive electric utility sector does not come at the expense of coal.<p>

Illinois coal producers are major consumer of electric power.  Existing and new mine operations in the state should be eligible for favorable rate structures.  The Illinois Commerce Commission (ICC) should encourage Illinois electric utility companies to adopt flexible contract terms for Illinois coal producers who have been adversely impacted by the Clean Air Act Amendments.  Flexible contracts will benefit coal producer through lower costs, as well as utility companies who will be securing a prime revenue source.<p>

Likewise, electric generators should be granted additional flexibility in long-term planning to achieve the most cost-effective compliance strategies for all pollutants regulated under the CAAA.  When analyzing long-range energy forecasts and compliance plans, the ICC should take into account that clean coal technologies do provide several benefits to the state, including multiple pollutant control, demonstration opportunities for corporations engaged in clean coal technology research, positive short- and long-term employment opportunities for Illinois worker, and market opportunities for the Illinois coal industry.<p>

Finally, the Office of Coal Development and Marketing should continue to enhance its Coal Education Program.  This program distributes valuable, factual information regarding the production and utilization of coal to classrooms around the state.  It helps to foster an awareness and understanding of coal, such as formation, historical growth of the industry, coal mining and safety, as well as environmental issues.  Because the education program demonstrates the relationship between coal and everyday life, the Board strongly encourages the Office of Coal Development and Marketing to maintain and enhance its efforts in this regard.<p>

The growth of the information highway offers unique opportunities for education and information sharing.  Business information important to the mining and utility industries can be made readily available through electronic media.  For instance, international marketing would be facilitated by on-line assistance through a number of market analysis systems.  Additional information of interest to coal industry analysts could be made readily available through Access Illinois network and the Internet.  The state should explore various options for information sharing that are now available through electronic media.<p>


<HR>
