<HEAD><TITLE>DCCA: Just for Kids -- Illinois Heritage</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#0000A0" LINK="#0000A0" VLINK="#FF0000" ALINK="#FF0000">


<center><img src="/dcca/graph/heritage.jpg" alt="Illinois Heritage" width=306 height=238 ></center>

<p>

Thank you for contacting the Department for information on our great state.  We are pleased to provide you with Illinois Heritage, an overview of our state's history and Illinois facts.  We hope this publication helps you with your school work.<p>

We would like to encourage you to share this information with your family to plan your next vacation in and around our state. You can call the Illinois Tourism Hotline, 800/2CONNECT (TTY: 800/406-6418), to receive additional information and material about various sites, activities and special events happening throughout Illinois.<p>

Read and enjoy Illinois!<p>

<strong>PLEASE NOTE: You can click on any picture to view it full size.</strong>

<hr>
<h3>
<a href="#Illinois History">Illinois History</a><br>
<a href="#Geography">Geography</a><br>
<a href="#Population">Population</a><br>
<a href="#Government">Government</a><br>
<a href="#Commerce">Commerce</a><br>
<a href="#Chicago">Chicago</a><br>
<a href="#Famous Illinoisans">Famous Illinoisans</a><br>
<a href="#Abraham Lincoln">Abraham Lincoln</a><br>
<a href="#State Symbols">State Symbols</a><br>
<a href="#State Flag">State Flag</a><br>
<a href="#State Song">State Song</a><br>
<a href="#Use Your Library">Use Your Library</a><p>
</h3>


<a name="Illinois History"><hr></a>
<h3>Illinois History</h3>

Indians hunted in Illinois as far back as 5000 B.C. and today you can still view the remains of their civilization at places such as Cahokia Mounds - North America's largest and most valuable prehistoric earthenwork relic. Dickson Mounds Indian Museum near Lewistown features special exhibits which chronicle the Indian's valuable place in Illinois history.<p>

The first European explorers in Illinois were Jacques Marquette and Louis Jolliet, Frenchmen who paddled by birchbark canoe along the Mississippi and Illinois Rivers. They traveled the length of the state - from what is now Chicago to the southernmost reaches of Illinois.<p>

<a href="../../graph/kids/fortdech.jpg"> <img src="../../graph/kids/fortdechs.jpg" width=75 height=59 align=right></a>
More French explorers followed, building military outposts and establishing a fur trading empire with local Indians. In 1763, at the close of the French and Indian War, the Treaty of Paris ceded to England all lands France had claimed east of the Mississippi River, except for New Orleans in Louisiana.<p>


The British continued to control what is now Illinois until 1778 when George Rogers Clark, a Revolutionary War hero, and his band of American colonists captured Fort Kaskaskia. The Illinois country became a possession of Virginia until 1787 when it joined the Northwest Territory under the government of the United States. Kaskaskia became Illinois' first capital in 1818. Two years later the seat of Illinois government was moved to Vandalia. In 1839, largely through the efforts of a young legislator named Abraham Lincoln, the capital was again moved - this time to Springfield, where it is now open to the public as an historic site. The Capitol in use today dates back to 1868, when ground was broken for its construction. Although the General Assembly moved in eight years later in 1876, it took 20 years to complete the building at a cost of $4.5 million. During 1988, Illinois celebrated the centennial of the completion of the Statehouse.<p>

<a name="Geography"><hr></a>
<h3>Geography</h3>

<a href="../../graph/kids/river.jpg"> <img src="../../graph/kids/rivers.jpg" width=72 height=50 hspace=10 vspace=10 align=right></a>
Illinois' total land area is about 56,400 square miles. There are 282,000 acres of ponds and lakes, not counting Lake Michigan. Among its 430 permanent rivers are 2,000 miles of navigable canoe routes. The state's largest inland water system is Carlyle Lake, which covers 26,000 acres in Southern Illinois. Major Illinois rivers include: the Mississippi, which forms the entire western border of the state, the Illinois, Ohio, Wabash, Rock, Vermilion, Fox, Des Plaines, Sangamon, Spoon, Embarras, Big Muddy, Kaskaskia, Kankakee, Pecatonica and the Kishwaukee.<p>

<a href="../../graph/kids/winter.jpg"> <img src="../../graph/kids/winters.jpg" width=110 height=50 hspace=10 vspace=10 align=left></a>
Illinois stretches 385 miles from north to south, and 218 miles from east to west at its widest point. The state is bordered by Indiana to the east, Wisconsin to the north, Iowa to the west, and Kentucky and Missouri to the south. Illinois has four distinct seasons which offer a variety of temperatures. The highest ever recorded was 117 degrees Fahrenheit; the lowest was 35 degrees below zero.<p>

There are over 100 state parks and conservation areas in Illinois, as well as federal wildlife areas and refuges. The Shawnee National Forest, which includes Illinois' dramatic Ozark Mountain foothills, covers 240,000 acres and offers some of the Midwest's best camping and fishing areas.<p>

<a href="../../graph/kids/coalman.jpg"> <img src="../../graph/kids/coalmans.jpg" width=73 height=60 align=right></a>
Besides its rich farmland and recreational sites, Illinois' geography yields large amounts of limestone, silica clay, lead, zinc and fluorite along with valuable oil, coal and natural gas.<p>
<br clear=all>

<a name="Population"><hr></a>
<h3>Population</h3>

<a href="../../graph/kids/galena.jpg"> <img src="../../graph/kids/galenas.jpg" width=74 height=50 hspace=10 vspace=10 align=left></a>
Total population of Illinois in 1990 was estimated at 11,430,602. A selection of the most populated Illinois cities includes: Chicago (2,783,726); Rockford (139,426); Peoria (113,504); Springfield (105,227); Decatur (83,885); Joliet (76,836); Waukegan (69,329); Champaign (63,502); Bloomington  (51,972); Belleville (42,785); Moline (43,202); East  St. Louis (40,944); Rock  Island (40,552); and Urbana (36,344).<p>

<a name="Government"><hr></a>
<h3>Government</h3>

<a href="../../graph/kids/capitol.jpg"> <img src="../../graph/kids/capitols.jpg" width=74 height=50 hspace=10 vspace=10 align=right></a>
Illinois is represented in the United States Congress by two senators and 20 representatives, which also gives the state 22 votes in the Electoral College. Illinois has 102 counties and 11,629 voting precincts, 5,367 of which are in Cook County, which contains the city of Chicago. <p>

Illinois' state government is based on two legislative chambers - the Senate and the House of Representatives - which together are called the General Assembly. Illinois has 59 State Senators and 118 State Representatives.<p>

<a name="Commerce"><hr></a>
<h3>Commerce</h3>

<a href="../../graph/kids/farmroad.jpg"> <img src="../../graph/kids/farmroads.jpg" width=80 height=50 hspace=10 vspace=10 align=left></a>
Miles of neatly planted farm fields are a  familiar sight in Illinois, even though the state's southern reaches include some of the Midwest's most rugged and rocky hills.<p>

This same geography of gently rolling prairie boasts some of the most productive and fertile soil on earth. Illinois is among the leading agricultural export centers of the nation and is a leading state in the production  of  corn, soybeans and hogs. Other important Illinois crops include alfalfa, peaches, apples and melons. Beef, dairy and poultry products also rank high.<p>

<a href="../../graph/kids/xway.jpg"> <img src="../../graph/kids/xways.jpg" width=75 height=50 hspace=10 vspace=10 align=right></a>
Some other facts about Illinois commerce:<p>

<ul type=square>

<li>Illinois ranks third in the nation in the number of interstate highway miles.<p>

<a href="../../graph/kids/coalshov.jpg"> <img src="../../graph/kids/coalshovs.jpg" width=74 height=50 hspace=10 vspace=10 align=right></a>
<li>Approximately three percent of U.S. exports come from Illinois.<p>

<li>Illinois mines 60 million tons of coal each year, 6 percent of U.S. production.<p>

<a href="../../graph/kids/taffy.jpg"> <img src="../../graph/kids/taffys.jpg" width=76 height=50 hspace=10 vspace=10 align=right></a>
<li>Tourism is a big business. Each year visitors spend over $15 billion during their trips to and within Illinois, making it among the ten most traveled states in the country.<p>

<a href="../../graph/kids/utilwork.jpg"> <img src="../../graph/kids/utilworks.jpg" width=76 height=50 hspace=10 vspace=10 align=right></a>
<li>Illinois also ranks among the leaders in the production of the following products:  construction machinery, farm equipment, radio and TV sets and other electric housewares, commercial printing, nuts and bolts, metal coating, polishes and sanitation goods, surgical appliances and supplies, sanitary food containers, metal stamping, printing trades machinery, electric coils and transformers, environmental controls, confectionary products, flavoring extracts and syrups, shortening and cooking oils, flour and other grain mill products, and dog, cat and other pet food.<p>
</ul>

<a name="Chicago"><hr></a>
<h3>Chicago</h3>

<a href="../../graph/kids/chicago.jpg"> <img src="../../graph/kids/chicagos.jpg" width=68 height=50 hspace=10 vspace=5 align=right></a>
Chicago is the nation's third largest  city and was first settled by the French in 1696. No lasting town, however, was formed until 1779 when  Jean Baptiste Pointe DuSable arrived from Canada with his Indian wife to start a fur trading post at the mouth of what is today the Chicago River. The name "Chicago" is derived from the Indian word "Che-Cagou."<p>

Nudged against one of the world's largest fresh water systems, Lake Michigan, Chicago's 29-mile shoreline, is devoted mostly to public beaches, harbors, parks and some of the nation's best museums. Among the city's nearly 230 square miles lie 430 parks that cover 7,000 acres. Chicago's "forest preserve" system takes up 35,000 additional acres of public wooded landscape. Even more forest preserves (65,000 acres) surround Chicago with a ring of picnic and recreation areas.<p>

<a href="../../graph/kids/ohare.jpg"> <img src="../../graph/kids/ohares.jpg" width=75 height=50 hspace=10 vspace=10 align=left></a>
<a href="../../graph/kids/rail.jpg"> <img src="../../graph/kids/rails.jpg" width=88 height=50 hspace=5 vspace=1 align=right></a>
Chicago is a "number one" city in many ways: convention business, commercial printing, mail order business, candy making, vending machines manufacturing, metal products and chemicals manufacturing. O'Hare International Airport is the world's busiest airport, and as the leading transportation center Illinois boasts over 20,000 miles of in-state railroad.<p>

<a href="../../graph/kids/picasso.jpg"> <img src="../../graph/kids/picassos.jpg" width=57 height=75 hspace=10 vspace=10 align=right></a>
Chicago's rise from the ashes of the Great Fire of 1871 also saw the birth of American modern architecture. The city today mirrors the efforts of great master builders such as Frank Lloyd Wright, Mies van der Rohe, and Sullivan and Adler. Skyscrapers line Chicago's shore. Sears Tower, its 110 stories soaring 1,454 feet above the city, is the world's tallest building. The Standard Oil Building at 80 stories and the John Hancock Center with 100 stories are other significant giants. The First National Bank, its plaza graced with an original mosaic by Russian artist Marc Chagall, is the tallest bank building on earth.<p>

The Chicago area is visited by twenty million people each year, many of them convention and trade show delegates and tourists who flock to lakeside museums and such cultural attractions as the Art Institute of Chicago, Field Museum, Alder Planetarium and John G. Shedd Aquarium.<p>

Here are more facts about Chicago which might surprise you:<p>

<ul type=square>
<li>Western Avenue, extending for 24.5 miles, is the longest continuous city roadway in the world.<p>
<li>The Chicago area accounts for a majority of the Illinois Gross State Product of $283 billion.<p>
<li>The Chicago area is the corporate home to 48 of the nation's Fortune 500 companies. As a financial center it boasts the Chicago Board of Trade, the Midwest Stock Exchange, the Mid-America Commodity Exchange, the Chicago Board of Options Exchange and the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.<p>
<li>Chicago has 3,679 miles of streets, and the busiest stretch of road in the world is on the Dan Ryan Expressway. If you stood at its 59th Street juncture you could count 250,000 vehicles as they passed you during one day.<p>
<li>O'Hare International Airport handles more than 160,000 passengers every day. Two flights depart or arrive every minute.<p>
</ul>

<a name="Famous Illinoisans"><hr></a>
<h3>Famous Illinoisans</h3>

<a href="../../graph/kids/lincolnh.jpg"> <img src="../../graph/kids/lincolnhs.jpg" width=69 height=50 hspace=10 vspace=10 align=left></a>
<a href="../../graph/kids/linctomb.jpg"> <img src="../../graph/kids/linctombs.jpg" width=36 height=50 hspace=10 vspace=10 align=right></a>
Illinois' most famous past resident was Abraham Lincoln, the 16th President of the United States. Lincoln came to Illinois from Indiana when he was 20 years old. He worked here as a riverboat captain, store clerk, postmaster, county circuit lawyer, land surveyor, state legislator and U.S. Congressman. The towns where he lived and worked - New Salem Village, Springfield and others - are visited by hundreds of thousands of people each year. Lincoln's home, in which he lived with his family for 17 years, is located in Springfield. Abraham Lincoln is buried in a tomb at Oak Ridge Cemetery just north of Springfield.<p>

<a href="../../graph/kids/reagan.jpg"> <img src="../../graph/kids/reagans.jpg" width=81 height=50 hspace=10 vspace=10 align=left></a>
Illinois was also the home of President Ulysses S. Grant, whose home is preserved in Galena. The 40th President, Ronald Reagan, was born in Tampico and spent his youth in Dixon.<p>

Other famous Illinoisans: Cyrus McCormick, A. Montgomery Ward, George W. Ferris, Enrico Fermi, Jane Addams, Jack Benny, Gail Borden, William Jennings Bryan, Hillary Clinton, Clarence Darrow, John Deere, Stephen A. Douglas, Marshall Field, Benny Goodman, Wild Bill Hickock, Oscar Mayer, George Pullman, Frank Lloyd Wright, Philip Wrigley and Brigham Young. Writers such as Ernest Hemingway, Carl Sandburg, Edgar Lee Masters, Vachel Lindsay, Ray Bradbury, Gwendolyn Brooks, Saul Bellow, James T. Farrell and Nelson Algren all lived and worked in Illinois.<p>

<a name="Abraham Lincoln"><hr></a>
<h3>Abraham Lincoln</h3>


<a href="../../graph/kids/lincstat.jpg"> <img src="../../graph/kids/lincstats.jpg" width=47 height=50 hspace=10 vspace=10 align=left></a>
Abraham Lincoln was a young man of 20 when he arrived in Illinois in 1830. A replica of the Lincoln family's first Illinois log cabin can be seen at Lincoln Homestead State Park near Decatur.<p>

After a hard winter, Lincoln's parents decided to settle in a new home in Coles County. The final home of Thomas and Sarah Lincoln is now the site of Lincoln Log Cabin State Historic Site.<p>

Young Abe, deciding not to stay at the Coles County farm, struck out on his own and settled in the tiny frontier village of New Salem. He lived here for six years, trying his hand at many trades - store clerk, steamboat pilot, postmaster - until he finally decided on a career as a lawyer. The old log cabin house where Lincoln first studied law books by the light of a hearth fire can still be seen today.<p>

Lincoln successfully campaigned for a seat in the Illinois House of Representatives in 1834. He remained as a legislator from Sangamon County until 1841.<p>

During this time Lincoln joined a group of fellow statesmen who called themselves "the long nine" because each man measured well over six feet tall.<p>

Lincoln married Mary Todd in 1842. By 1844 they had settled into their first home, a frame house still located on 8th Street in Springfield.<p>

Following eight years as an Illinois State Representative, Lincoln was elected to the U.S. Congress in 1846. After serving his term, he returned to Illinois to become a traveling attorney and sometimes judge on the Eighth Judicial Circuit. He made many friends during his backcountry trips. One of the towns he frequented, Postville, was renamed "Lincoln" in his honor in 1853. Abe himself christened the new town with the juice of an Illinois watermelon.<p>

With the passage of the Kansas-Nebraska Act of 1854, which allowed slavery in the new  western  frontier, Lincoln once again delved into politics. He began to speak out strongly against slavery and his views resulted in the formation of the Republican Party in Illinois.<p>

Lincoln challenged Stephen A. Douglas for the U.S. Senate seat from Illinois during the state's Republican Convention of 1858. A series of famous debates between the two candidates followed. Lincoln lost the race, but his eloquence gained him a national reputation.<p>

Two years later Lincoln became a candidate for President. He received word of his nomination in the parlor of his Springfield home. As President-Elect, he left his Illinois hometown on February 11, 1861 - just one week before Jefferson Davis became President of the newly formed Confederate States of America. The Civil War began on April 12, 1861, when Confederate troops fired on Fort Sumpter.<p>

During his years in the White House Lincoln is credited most often for ending the Civil War and abolishing slavery in the United States with a document called The Emancipation Proclamation.<p>

Fifty months after leaving his beloved Springfield, Lincoln was shot by John Wilkes Booth as he sat in Ford Theater. Returning to Illinois as a martyred president, Lincoln is buried in a massive monument in Oak Ridge Cemetery along with his wife and three of his four children.<p>

<a name="State Symbols"><hr></a>
<h3>State Symbols</h3>

The Official State Symbols of the State of Illinois are designated by acts of the General Assembly.<p>

<a name="State Flag"><hr></a>
<h3>State Flag</h3>

Illinois has had two official state flags since becoming the 21st state to join the union on December 3, 1818. The first flag was designed by Lucy Derwent of the Rockford Chapter of Daughters of the American Revolution. She received a prize of $25 for her efforts. The flag was adopted on July 6, 1915.<p>

A move to design a new state flag came in the late 1960's by Chief Petty Officer Bruce McDaniel who requested that the new flag carry the  state's name. Mrs. Sanford Hutchison submitted a design for a new flag which was accepted. On July 1, 1970, her design became the official flag of Illinois.<p>

<a name="State Song"><hr></a>
<h3>State Song</h3>

By Act of the Fifty-fourth General Assembly the song "Illinois" became the official State song. The bill was introduced in the Senate by Senator Florence Fifer Bohrer, daughter of the late Governor Joseph W. Fifer and the first woman to serve as member of the Illinois Senate. The bill passed both houses without opposition and became law by executive signature."Illinois" had long been the State song, but it had been given no official recognition prior to the passage of the bill. The song was written by Charles H. Chamberlin some time between 1890 and 1894, in connection with plans for securing the World's Columbian Exposition for Chicago. Many states were attempting to secure the exposition, Illinois making strong efforts herself with the able assistance of U. S. Senator Shelby M. Cullom and U. S. Senator John M. Palmer. Colonel O. B. Knight, a friend of Mr. Chamberlin, in the meantime, was singing throughout Illinois and in Washington, D. C. and so the song was written primarily for him to sing. The Iyric was composed by Mr. Chamberlin, but the music had been written by Archibald Johnston in 1870 with another Iyric by Charles Machay. In its original form the name of the song was "Baby Mine," under which title it won great popularity in the `70s.<p>

<a name="Use Your Library"><hr></a>
<h3>Use Your Library</h3>

Do you want to know more about Illinois - its people, history, plus some places you might like to visit? Your local library is the best source for researching current and reliable information on almost any facet of our state's rich past and promising future. Magazines, specialty publications, plus contemporary books and brochures can also be obtained by just asking your librarian.<p>

And best of all, ask your parents to let you see first hand what Illinois and its land and people are all about - take an Illinois vacation!<p>

<hr>
