<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>DCCA: Community Development Programs</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#8080C0" ALINK="#004080">


<img src="/dcca/graph/logosm.jpg" alt="DCCA Logo" width=165 height=82 align=left>
<img src="/dcca/graph/cbar.gif" width=410 height=4><p>
<h3>
Department of Commerce & Community Affairs<p>
</h3>
<img src="/dcca/graph/cbar.gif" width=410 height=4><p>

<font size=+3>Community Development Programs</font>
<br clear=right>
<hr>

<img src="../../graph/afford.jpg" width=171 height=75 align=right>

<CENTER><H3>Affordable Financing of Public Infrastructure Program</H3></CENTER>
<HR>
<p>

The Affordable Financing of Public Infrastructure (AFPI) program authorizes the Department of Commerce and Community Affairs (DCCA) to provide financial assistance to or on behalf of local governments, public entities, medical facilities and public health clinics for the purpose of making affordable the financing of a community's public infrastructure.  DCCA has recognized the importance of adequate infrastructure to the economic viability of communities.<p>

Under the Small Project Loan Component, up to $100,000 is available for a maximum of three years at an attractive interest rate for acquisition, construction and improvements of local public facilities and associated equipment.  Units of local government, local public entities, and medical facilities and public health clinics may apply for funding.<p>


<h3>Illinois Department of Commerce and Community Affairs</h3>

DCCA has joined with the Illinois Rural Bond Bank, Illinois Development Finance Authority, the Illinois Environmental Protection Agency and the Illinois Department of Public Health to facilitate this project.  DCCA can provide financial assistance directly or through one of these intermediaries.  Depending upon the type of project, a community would apply to one of these agencies for AFPI assistance.  Applications are accepted on an on-going basis.  DCCA staff is available to work with a community to identify which agency is best suited to help with its financing needs.<p>


<h3>Illinois Environmental Protection Agency</h3>

IEPA provides loans to upgrade, expand or otherwise provide wastewater treatment and collection facilities.  AFPI funds are available for planning and design costs.  Also, IEPA has funds available for wastewater construction costs under the Illinois Water Pollution Control Revolving Fund.<p>


<h3>Illinois Rural Bond Bank</h3>

The Illinois Rural Bond Bank will provide loans up to $100,000 for infrastructure improvements and related public purpose projects outside the Chicago metropolitan area.  Eligible projects include water system improvements, school building repairs, fire protection district building improvements and equipment purchases, road improvements, ADA building improvements, and other public use projects.<p>


<h3>Illinois Development Finance Authority</h3>

The Illinois Development Finance Authority will make loans of up to $100,000 to a community for infrastructure improvements necessary to attract, retain or expand a business;  the business must be located within the borrowing community and must need the infrastructure improvements to operate.  Loans are also available to non-rural communities for projects where public purpose financing is not available.<p>

For more information call 217/785-6142.<p>

<HR>
<STRONG>| <A HREF="http://www.ilcommerce.com">DCCA Home Page</A> | <a href="../../menus/commasst.htm"> Local Government & Community Assistance</a>  |</STRONG>
</BODY>
