<CENTER><H3>High School Energy / Environment Intern Programs</H3></CENTER>
<HR>

Would you like to spend the summer of 1997 working as a paid energy or environmental professional in either the private or public sector?<p>

If you are a high school junior or senior during the 1996-1997 school year, you are eligible to be one of the ten interns selected statewide by ILEED.<p>

<hr>
<h3>ILEED Energy/Environment Intern Program</h3>

ILEED provides verifiable energy and environmental education and promotes independent thought enabling students to better meet the needs of the future.  ILEED emphasizes communication skills, problem solving and goal setting.<p>

ILEED's Energy/Environment Intern Program offers high school students the opportunity to acquire leadership skills and the opportunity to consider future career choices in the energy/environment field.<p>

Through the summer intern program, you can learn the relationship between education and your future by getting some "real life" job experience.  Your internship experience will enhance your resume.<p>

<blockquote>
"The intern is a very bright and energetic young woman.  In fact we offered to hire her as a part-time student helper for the fall..."<br>
<em>1993 Host Organization</em><p>
</blockquote>

Former interns are enthusiastic about the program.<p>

<blockquote>"This was one of the greatest experiences in my life!"</blockquote>

<blockquote>"It's the best experience you can get!"</blockquote>

<blockquote>"The Intern Program showed us a lot of career choices we did not know existed."</blockquote>

<hr>
<h3>How Much Will I Be Paid?</h3>

Interns will receive a stipend for two months' work.  Each assignment will last eight weeks.  Starting dates vary according to the needs of the interns and host organizations.

<blockquote>
"I would have done it for less."<br>
<em>1992 intern</em>
</blockquote>

<hr>
<h3>How Do I Apply for an Internship?</h3>

Send for your free copy of the Directory of Internship Opportunities, which lists job available in each county and includes an application form and complete instruction for submission.  Just fill in the attached form and you will receive the Directory in January 1997.<p>

Application requires the students to complete two brief essays, obtain three letters of recommendation, list their extra curricular activities and identify their current career interests.  Special attention is paid to these four requirements during the review process.<p>

The deadline for completed applications will be February 28, 1997.<p>

<hr>
<h3>Need More Information?</h3>

Call or write to the ILEED Intern Program:<p>
<ul>
Illinois Department of Commerce and Community Affairs<br>
325 West Adams Street, Room 300<br>
Springfield, IL 62704-1892<br>
217/785-3411; TDD 217/785-0211<p>
</ul>

