<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>DCCA: Site Selection Assistance</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#8080C0" ALINK="#8080C0">

<img src="/dcca/graph/logosm.jpg" alt="DCCA Logo" width=165 height=82 align=left>
<img src="/dcca/graph/cbar.gif" width=410 height=4><p>
<h3>
Department of Commerce & Community Affairs<p>
</h3>
<img src="/dcca/graph/cbar.gif" width=410 height=4><p>
<FONT SIZE=+3>Site Selection Assistance</FONT>
<BR CLEAR=RIGHT>
<hr>
<h2 align=center>The Executive's Guide to Site Selection</h2>

<h3 >
<a href="#Intro">Introduction</a><br>
<a href="#Section 2">Section 2: The Site Selection Process</a><br>
<a href="#Section 3">Section 3: Common Mistakes & Misconceptions</a><br>
<a href="#The Illinois Advantage">The Illinois Advantage</a><br>
<a href="#The Site Selection Scorecard">The Site Selection Scorecard</a><p>
</h3>

<a name="Intro"><hr></a>
<h2 align=center>Introduction</h2>

The selection of a site for a new facility is among the most complex and challenging of business decision. <p> 

For one thing, the planning for a new facility requires not only consideration of virtually all of the factors that affect a business today, but also calls for taking into account the factors that are likely to become important during the expected life span of the facility.<p>
                
Nor is the process made any easier by the manifold social, economic and technological changes that are redrawing today's business maps and further complicating the site selection process.  Considerations that once were of prime importance have declined; new factors have emerged and become paramount.  Moreover, even after the important factors - current and future - are identified, it is the rare facility location problem that can be solved entirely through a formal analysis.  Inevitably, the final decision requires the balancing of a combination of quantifiable and non-quantifiable factors.<p>

And, to top it off, site selection is a relatively rare event at most companies, with only the largest of firms able to retain a full-time specialist to oversee its facility location tasks.  Few executives have been trained in "economic geography," and, at most companies, the manager who is given responsibility for guiding the company to this important decision never has selected a site before and most likely never will again.<p>

This guidebook has been prepared as a natural extension of what we see as an important part of our mission at the Illinois Department of Commerce and Community Affairs: to assist companies in their site selection efforts involving our state.  We have helped hundreds of firms expand their facilities or settle here for nearly two decades.  With this guidebook, we hope to share some of the lessons that we have learned and to help companies become better prepared to undertake the daunting task of site selection.<p>

There are no hard-and-fast rules, no easy universally applicable answers.  Every site selection project is distinct and involves a different balance of factors and consideration - and this uniqueness is especially accentuated in today's increasingly competitive environment in which strategies call for firms to differentiate themselves from their competitors as much as possible.  Our aim is not to provide a blueprint, but rather to present a set of guidelines that firms can adapt to their own particular needs, as well as to give tips regarding common mistakes that companies should try to avoid.<p>

Some of the information here will apply to your project, some will not.  Nevertheless, by sharing what we have learned from the many site selection projects with which we have been involved, we expect this guidebook will help you be better prepared to undertake the particular task that faces you.<p>


<a name="How to Use this Book"><hr></a>
<p>
<img src="../../graph/business/sshowto.jpg" alt="How To Use this Book" width=195 height=37 vspace=8 hspace=8 align=left>



Our guidebook is divided into four distinct sections.  First, is an executive briefing that provides an overview of past trends in site selection, as well as a discussion of issues that are likely to rise in importance in the future and that might play an important role in your location decision.<p>

The second section - and the heart of the guidebook - presents a step-by-step framework for the site selection process, an outline that you can tailor to the special needs of your particular search.<p>

<img src="../../graph/business/ss1.jpg" width=194 height=117 hspace=8 vspace=8 align=right>
Section three discusses some common misconceptions about site selection and some common mistakes to avoid.<p>

And, at the very end of the guidebook, we have included a site selection "scoresheet" that you can use to help organize the evaluation of the sites under consideration.<p>
<br clear=all>

<a name="Overview & Executive Briefing"><hr></a>
<p>
<img src="../../graph/business/ssover.jpg" alt="Overview & Executive Briefing" width=187 height=51 vspace=8 hspace=8 align=left>

Real estate is generally a company's longest-term asset, and, as a result, identification of the most advantageous sites for new facilities can be done only by projecting future corporate needs.  Unfortunately, trying to extrapolate future physical and operational requirements directly from past experience can be a dangerous effort.  Significant changes are virtually certain - for example, many forecasters predict that much of the technology that will be used at the turn of the century is still being invented-and future plants most likely will bear little resemblance to present operations. <p>

Nevertheless, it is possible to disconcern signs of some of the more important changes ahead and some of the factors that should be kept in mind when making site selection decisions today.  A quick look at the way that site selection patterns have shifted in the past can help us get a perspective on some of the changes underway today and can help us develop a better sense of what the future is likely to hold in store.<p>

<img src="../../graph/business/ss2.jpg" width=260 height=189 hspace=8 vspace=8 align=right>

In the late 19th century, for example, the development of the nation's railroad network encouraged corporations to move to major financial, communications and transportation centers like Chicago and New York.  After World War II, the development of the interstate highway system and the growth of the suburbs helped convince many companies to move from central cities to suburban areas.  During the 1970s, many companies took advantage of further advances in transportation and in communication technologies to pursue lower-cost labor.  First, they moved their operations to less expensive areas of the United States.  Ultimately, many companies went so far as to move their manufacturing operations overseas.<p>

During the 1980s, site selection trends became much more complex.  consider, for example, the impact of low-wage competition from overseas that has made it very difficult for assembly type operations to remain viable in the higher-wage U.S. environment.  In response, increasing number of U.S. manufacturers abandoned emphasis on purely cost-based competition and turned to strategies that emphasize flexibility and the ability to be the first to produce new, specialized products.<p>

One result of the embrace of these strategies is that in the 1990s, a site is more attractive if it seems likely to be able to adapt to the changing needs of the future.  For example, many strategies involve application of advanced computer and telecommunications technologies, and this new level of factory automation has begun to change the nature of the labor component of much manufacturing.  In particular, the implementation of robotics, flexible manufacturing, computer aided design, computer aided manufacturing technologies has greatly increased the need for highly skilled technical worker.  In turn, these changes already are beginning to have discernible effects on location requirements.  For instance, many low-wage communities might be excellent for staffing unskilled and semi-skilled positions, but finding technical and skilled talent in these areas can be more problematic.  Recruiting professionals and managers for such locales can be especially difficult.<p>

<img src="../../graph/business/ss3.jpg" width=329 height=223 hspace=8 vspace=8 align=left>

As a result, the increasingly sophisticated us of computers at most organizations has resulted in greater site selection emphasis.  This is especially so in areas in which companies feel confident that they will be able to find the kinds of highly skilled labor and specialized maintenance support services that they expect they will need in their new plants.<p>

The growing emphasis on flexibility also has prompted an increasing number of companies to consider the quality of the educational system offered by a community under site consideration.  Today it is important that a community has not only a well trained labor force, but one that is also retrainable and that will be able to satisfy anticipated, as well as existing, labor needs.  Yet another consequence has been an increased interest in proximity to colleges and universities.  As manufacturers shift from labor-intensive production to sophisticated automation that requires almost constant education and retraining, businesses are increasingly attracted to communities in which they can find tailored training courses that can meet the growing need to bring together classroom and workplace.<p>

Generally, site selection interest is virtually certain to shift toward communities with cooperative government authorities who understand the needs of the business community and who are prepared to move quickly to help the members of its business sector respond to the fast changing world.<p>

Other factors to keep in mind during the site selection process include:<p>

<strong>ELECTRONIC DATA INTERCHANGE (EDI) and JUST-IN-TIME (JIT) strategies:</strong><p>

Many suppliers are letting their most important customers plug into their inventory information systems and place orders via EDI.  The embrace of JIT by many organizations-especially those in the auto industry-has influenced location decisions by fostering closer ties and increasing the importance of customer and supplier proximity.  Every site selection effort needs to consider the importance of these developments in the company's line of business.  In particular, all firms should be sure to inquire as to whether the sites they are considering are in an area served by trucks and rail on the EDI program.<p>

<img src="../../graph/business/ss4.jpg" width=167 height=174 hspace=8 vspace=8 align=right>

<strong>WATER:</strong><p>

Spot shortages of water occasionally arise, and it seems likely that water availability will take on increasing importance.<p>

<img src="../../graph/business/ss5.jpg" width=134 height=172 hspace=8 vspace=8 align=left>
<strong>ELECTRIC UTILITIES:</strong><p>

It is important not to simply focus on today's electric power costs, but to look at future rates as well.  Many electric utilities have reached their peak capacities, and are likely to be forced to sharply increase their rates in order to make the necessary investments in new generating facilities.  As a result, any company considering a new site would be well advised to make at least a quick check of rate-hike requests that are pending with state regulatory commissions.  The increasing reliance on computers also has placed a greater value on reliability of electrical services.  Spikes and surges can have disastrous effects on sensitive instruments and computer controls, and the cost of power interruption can more than outweigh the payment of a slightly higher rate for a more reliable power source.<p>

<strong>DEMOGRAPHY:</strong><p>

Two career households and the aging of the workforce have had a growing impact on site selection decisions. Such families tend to be less willing to move to smaller, secondary communities in which career opportunities for either partner might be limited particularly as they get older and further into their careers.  Moreover, these households are not totally dependent on one income and are in a strong position to decline to move or to refuse to relocate.<p>

<img src="../../graph/business/ss6.jpg" width=190 height=110 hspace=8 vspace=8 align=left>
<strong>GRIDLOCK IN FAST DEVELOPING AREAS:</strong><p>

Suburban transportation is expected to be an increasingly intractable problem, and there is a growing body of evidence that suggests the advantages enjoyed by many suburban fringe areas that do not currently suffer from traffic congestion will be shortlived.  The speed with which outlying areas become developed and congested can be astounding.<p>

<strong>TRANSPORTATION DEREGULATION:</strong><p>

Deregulation is rewriting many of the rules of site selection, with more changes likely.  The advent of multimodal services, for example, is making it increasingly advantageous to be near a site that is close to a full scale multimodal transportation hub.  There also has been a proliferation of short-line railroads, resulting in more railroads operating in the U.S. than ever before.  Deregulation also allows negotiations of individual rates and contracts, and diminishes the attractiveness of those communities that do not offer transportation services from a variety of competing vendors.<p>

<strong>TELECOMMUNICATIONS:</strong><p>

Telecommunications is playing an ever-increasing role in business operations and the availability of fiber optic lines and specialized telecom services is beginning to figure more significantly in corporate site selection decisions.<p>


<a name="Section 2"><hr></a>
<h2 align=center>Section 2: The Site Selection Process</h2>

As with any complex undertaking, advance planning is crucial to the successful search for and selection of the location for the new facility.  Some site selection efforts require more planning, others less.  This section sketches out the major steps that should be considered in formulating a site selection plan-of-action and provides a general framework that can be adapted to meet the needs of a particular situation.<p>

<br>
<img src="../../graph/business/ss7.jpg" alt="Step 1: Guidance from Top Management" width=190 height=46 align=left vspace=10 hspace=10>


The first step for any site selection project is to get a clear sense of the project mission from top management, and particularly to get explicit direction regarding the prime objectives for the new facility.  Is it intended:<p>

<ul type=square>
<li>To address a need for more production space?<p>
<li>To facilitate movement into a new market?  Or to expand service to an existing market?<p>
<li>To escape high labor costs at existing facilities?<p>
<li>To introduce new production processes?  Or to fulfill some other strategic mission?<p>
</ul>

Top management particularly needs to make clear such parameters as the production capacity of the new facility, the markets it will serve, and the expected life span of the facility.  Moreover, these parameters must include not only the expectations regarding the facility's initial operation, but also how it is anticipated that they will change over time.  Often, there is a tendency to focus on the initial concerns and start-up projection, but the new facility must also be able to meet future needs, and it is crucial to take into account these long-term considerations as well.  Inevitably, discussion of the new facility will involve significant consideration of the company's long range strategic plans.<p>

The planning stage also should involve a general discussion of how the site selection plan is to proceed, including agreement on the general issues that will be considered, and how the preliminary and final evaluation will be made.<p>

<br>
<img src="../../graph/business/ss9.jpg" alt="Step 2: The Site Selection Team" width=187 height=44 hspace=10 vspace=10 align=left>

In addition to getting input from the CEO and top management, it is also important to draw on the expertise of in-house specialists in finance, manufacturing and operations, sales and marketing, logistics and distribution and human resources.  Whether done formally or informally, it is crucial that all the company's operations be represented on a site selection team and in the site selection process.<p>

<img src="../../graph/business/ss10.jpg" width=190 height=112 hspace=10 vspace=10 align=right>

The site selection team should be briefed on the project mission, and you need to make it clear that each team member is expected to identify, analyze and take into account the relevant economic and industry trends, technological changes and company plans that might have an impact on the site selection decision.  This stage in the process of planing a new facility provides an opportunity to consider a variety of new directions for the company, including: changes in manufacturing, marketing and administration; automation or introduction of a new production process; and development of new markets or ways to better serve old markets.  If top management concurs, you might well consider encouraging team members during this initial period of analysis to challenge the original top-management assumptions regarding the project.<p>


<img src="../../graph/business/ss11.jpg" width=184 height=120 hspace=10 vspace=10 align=left>

In any case, make sure to promote discussion and interaction among the in-house experts.  For example, lack of communication can cause a company to make the mistake of basing a site selection decision on the belief that it will be hiring the same kinds of employees at the new facility as it employs at its existing plant, when, in fact, new technologies might well mean that the company will need a work force with new kinds of skills,  The existing plant might, for example, employ 200 people, 80% of whom are unskilled and 20% semi-skilled, whereas, in the new facility, the same amount of production might call for only 100 employees, 50% of whom are highly skilled, 30% of whom are semi-skilled and only 20% unskilled.  Such differences in the composition of the labor force could, for instance, have important implications regarding the kind of labor market, as well as the size and character of the community, in which the new facility might need to be located.<p>


<br>
<img src="../../graph/business/ss12.jpg" width=190 height=30 hspace=10 vspace=10 align=left>

The key to a successful site selection effort is the translation of the insights of the team of in-house experts into a good set of requirements/criteria that can be used to screen site candidates and, ultimately, to choose the site for the new facility.<p>

The first thing to do is to tap the expertise of the location team and answer a number of important questions.  These might include:<p>

<img src="../../graph/business/ss13.jpg" width=189 height=191 hspace=10 vspace=10 align=right>
<ul type=square>
<li><em>What size does the new facility need to be in order to handle the planned production capacity?</em>
<li><em>What kinds of raw material will be needed and how will these inbound material be delivered?  Are there key raw materials that might not be available at all locations?</em>  You might want to sit down with existing suppliers, tell them that you are considering opening a new plant, and ask them which markets they service.
<li><em>What will it need in the way of electrical power? Water? Gas? Telecom?</em>
<li><em>What about environment concerns and constraints?  Will you need to dispose of waste water into a municipal sewer system that might require pre-treatment?  Are there wastes that not all systems will be able to accept?  Are there air emission considerations?</em>
<li><em>What markets will it serve and how will the outbound products be delivered?</em>  The specific products to be produced and shipped; the markets to be served; and the   distribution pattern of products to be shipped from the new location all need to be taken into consideration.
<li><em>How many employees will the new facility require and what kinds of skills will they need to have?</em>
<li><em>What kinds of transportation facilities are particularly important?</em>  As we continue to move toward a global economy, for example, the need to serve far flung overseas markets might call for a location which has rail service to both and East Coast and a West Coast port.
<li><em>Is it important to be able to have face-to-face dialogue between employees and customers?</em>  If it is, then location near an airport or an interstate highway system might rise in importance.
<li><em>Are customer service, delivery times and reliability important site considerations?  Are there any vendors, suppliers or customer to whom it is particularly important to have good access?</em>
<li><em>What impact will just-in-time (JIT) strategies have on your site?</em>  If there are important customers whom you have to be able to reach within, say, three hours, this consideration should come into play early in the site search.
<li><em>Is the availability of intermodal transportation facilities important?</em>
<li><em>Are there any special telecommunications capabilities that will be needed, e.g. fiber optic cable or special digital transmission services?</em>
<li><em>How large and what kind of an employee population will be needed at the new facility?</em> This includes not only the number of employees in each job classification, but also their relative importance and how the employee population might change over time.
<li><em>What quality of life factors are important?  Are they an important consideration in you ability to recruit the kind of talent you will need?</em>
<li><em>How important is proximity to colleges and universities?</em>  Many companies are finding it increasingly valuable to make use of the research and educational facilities offered by    colleges and universities.
<li><em>What markets are you going to penetrate and what impact will the location of the new facility have on the way that sales will be divided up among your factories?</em>
<li><em>How much space for employee parking will be needed?  </em>
</ul>

Again, make sure to warn the team members against basing their projections for the future plant exclusively on information gathered from the existing facility.  Any new facility will differ significantly from the existing one, and while such projections might be helpful as rough first approximations, they run the risk of not sufficiently factoring in new technologies or production methods that are likely to introduced in the new facility.  For example, a common error is to extrapolate future electricity usage simply buy looking at electrical usage for the last 12 months in the existing plant rather than to try to develop projections for how much power will be needed for the new manufacturing process that is planned for the new facility. One good way to avoid this mistake and to develop better projections is to consult with the suppliers who will be providing the new equipment that you will be installing.<p>

There are many other factors that could be important to a company, depending on how it envisions its business.  The point of this effort is to clearly define the characteristics desired for the new facility and the community in which it will be located, so that those attributes can be sued to effectively screen site candidates and choose the appropriate site.<p>

<br>
<img src="../../graph/business/ss14.jpg" alt="Step 4: The Requirements Matrix" width=193 height=54 hspace=10 vspace=10 align=left>


The next step is to use the information about the site requirements to develop fairly well-defined set of site criteria, which then can be organized into a format that can e efficiently use to go out and begin the long process of systematic evaluation and screening of site candidates.<p>

Maybe the best way to organize the information provided by the in-house team of experts is to put it into a matrix of rows and columns, with site factors/requriements listed along the left-hand side and candidate sites listed across the top. (See the matrix we have provided in the back of this guidebook.)  Where possible, information regarding specific sites should be translated into financial terms, e.g. labor costs for a specific location for the types of labor that will be needed, current and projected electric power costs for the required power levels, expected transportation costs.<p>

The use of the matrix format will make it easier to score the sites and keep track of the particular considerations that are going to eliminate some locations and keep others in.  In this way, the matrix will provide a framework that will help clarify and organize the site selection process.<p>

Although each site selection project will develop its own set of criteria, we have provided a "generic" checklist at the end of this guidebook that has been designed so as to be easily tailored to your particular situation and needs.<p>


<br>
<img src="../../graph/business/ss15.jpg" alt="Step 5: The First Cut" width=196 height=31 hspace=10 vspace=10 align=left>

Now comes the time to begin the actual search.<p>

The process of collecting the recommendations of the site team and of putting together the evaluation matrix should begin to provide a general sense of the kinds of sites that will be most appropriate for the facility in question.  Often, the general shape of the constraints that emerges makes it possible to quickly eliminate large portions of the country.  The next task is to narrow the search further by focusing on the most important requirements that are likely to be hardest to accommodate.<p>

In some cases, a single, highly restrictive requirement will serve this function, e.g. the need for particular special services or for exceptionally high levels of electric power will automatically narrow the search.  Most site searches, however, will not involve such obvious restrictions.<p>

<img src="../../graph/business/ss16.jpg" width=217 height=185 hspace=10 vspace=10 align=right>

<em><strong>NOTE:</strong></em> One common misconception is that tax considerations and government incentives should play an important role in steering the selection process at this point.  In fact, taxes and incentives generally affect businesses only marginally and should b, at most, secondary or even tertiary considerations.  Occasionally, up-front incentives can provide a short-term "hit" capable of making a very bad location look good for a year or two.  Ultimately, however, there is a price to be paid for distorting the traditional economies that should be sued for the site selection decision.  Incentives are something to keep in mind- particularly in the final stage of the site selection effort-but they shouldn't drive the process.<p>

In most cases, the key drivers in site selection are transportation and labor costs, which taken together, generally represent roughly 80% of operating cost.  Often, the best approach is to begin with a set of preliminary transportation analyses in which in-house transportation experts generate rough calculations for a handful of location scenarios.  This might, for example, involve:<p>

<ul type=square>
<li>assuming that the new facility will be located somewhere in the proximity of Chicago, St. Louis, Atlanta, Dallas or Denver
<li>then, for each of those cases, splitting up the company's existing facilities
<li>and, finally, calculating the transportation costs for each of the scenarios.
</ul>

What makes this approach particularly useful is that transportation costs tend to vary in a stable, continuous manner.  As a result, it is possible, for example, to produce rough computations of shipping costs from one metro area to another and to create transportation cost "isobars."  By running through such computations, isobar patterns will begin to emerge, e.g. it may turn out that transportation costs for a particular facility will be the same for any point in a region stretching between Cleveland and Milwaukee.  The subsequent search then can be narrowed to the low transportation cost isobar areas revealed by these calculations.  One caveat: Avoid the mistake of restricting the search too severely at this point.,  Just because a computation shows, for example, that the lowest transportation cost point is Columbus, Ohio, does not necessarily mean that the site search should be restricted to locations within 50 miles of Columbus, since even a $50,000 higher cost of transportation could easily be mad up by an area in which labor costs were significantly lower.<p>

At this point, the site selection process probably has gone as far as it effectively can go without outside help.  The problems is that the other major site selection driver-labor cost and availability-is much less easily calculated and evaluated than is transportation cost.<p>

<img src="../../graph/business/ss17.jpg" width=237 height=155 hspace=10 vspace=10 align=left>
Regional labor cost generalizations have been unraveling for quite some time, and , by the end of the 1980s, the few regional partners that had persisted finally had disappeared as a result of the economic turmoil and dislocations of the preceding decade.  Today, the geographic variation in wage rates has become much more complex, with, for example, an increasing number of situations in which labor cost and availability actually vary significantly within a single metropolitan area.<p>

At the same time, a national market now exists for some of the most sophisticated skills.  If you need to hire someone for a position requiring special computer programming skills for the particular applications that you use in you manufacturing plant, it is likely that the amount you pay will not vary significantly according to where you are located.  In fact, it very well could turn out to be harder and more expensive to fill skilled positions in what normally would be considered low-wage areas.<p>

<br>
<img src="../../graph/business/ss18.jpg" alt="Step 6: Outside Help" width=190 height=32 hspace=10 vspace=10 align=left>

Having narrowed the site search-via transportation considerations-to an area that might stretch across parts of as many as half a dozen states, the time has come to go to outside sources to help you identify communities within that area that might have sites that would be appropriate for your needs.<p>

In the case of a facility with a unique requirement - e.g. special access to rail transportation or special electric power needs-a company might decide to turn to the industrial development operations of, say, railroads or electrical utilities for help.<p>

Generally speaking, however, the most appropriate outside sources to contact are the economic development agencies for the states which have areas which still remain under consideration for your potential site.  Though the level of sophistication of the agencies varies somewhat from state to state, most have a variety of resources that can greatly facilitate your site selection efforts.  For example, a number of economic development agencies have computerized data bases that quickly can provide-often within 24 hours-complete, current information about buildings and industrial sites that are available in their states, as well as detailed information about the utilities, labor forces, educational facilities, industries, tax structures and other community information that companies need to make site selection decisions.  Illinois, in fact, makes community profiles and many sites and available through this Internet web page.<p>

The most effective way to use our state agency staff is as an extension of the site search team.  Give them as much specific information a possible about what you are seeking.  This could include, for example, providing them with detailed information about labor needs, site acreage requirements, ranges of community size, any special training programs (e.g. a welding program in the community college), transportation requirements and tax information.  It is especially important to fully inform these professional about the factors that will be key in your site selection decision-and particularly to give them clear and complete information about the "knock-out factors" that you will be using.  Armed with such information, the specialists are the agencies will be in a good position to come up with site candidates that will come closest to meeting your needs.<p>

<img src="../../graph/business/ss20.jpg" width=209 height=132 hspace=10 vspace=10 align=right>

There also is another way that state economic development agencies can help companies that are involved in site selection.  Once word gets out that a company is planning a new facility, the floodgates open, and the organization inevitably is deluged with glossy brochures and beseiged by officials from communities interested in landing the new plant.  Some companies actually find that the attention becomes so intense that it interferes with the day-to-day operations at their existing location.  In this kind of situation, many firms have found it helpful to use the sate economic development agencies as ab buffer and to tell anyone who contacts the m directly that the firm is working with the state and that nay information should be submitted though the agency.  You even can try to preempt the attention by contacting the state agencies anonymously and concealing your identity during the early stages of your site search.<p>

<br>
<img src="../../graph/business/ss19.jpg" alt="Step 7: Visitation Rights and Wrongs" width=190 height=50 hspace=10 vspace=10 align=left>

When the information about the most appropriate communities and sites begins to come in from the state agencies, use of the evaluation matrix can be a big help in organizing the material.  Unfortunately, no matter how detailed the set of criteria and how extensive the site selection planning, there is no easy way to proceed on the site evaluations.  The process of eliminating sites and narrowing the field of candidates inevitable involves the weighing of complicated trade-offs and the balancing of hard to compare considerations.<p>

From the communities and site candidates that the state agencies nominate, the site selection tam should choose a dozen or so prime contenders that qualify for visits by site team members.  Each member of the site selection team typically is assigned three to four communities to evaluate in the first round of community visits.<p>

<img src="../../graph/business/ss21.jpg" width=181 height=98 hspace=10 vspace=10 align=left>

The in-person evaluations are important for several reasons.  For one thing, there is no substitute for direct, first hand examination of prospective sites,  The visits also are unsurpassed opportunities to find out about the community's business environment.  It can be particularly helpful to talk with executives at local businesses and to find out which kinds of companies have been moving into the community and which have been leaving.  This kind of information can provide extremely valuable insights into the community and can make it possible to learn a great deal from the experiences of the organizations already there.<p>

In-person visits can serve at least one other important function: to provide an opportunity to get a clearer sense of the "personality" of the community in which a prospective site is located.  There is a surprising amount of variation among communities that, at least on paper, might seem very similar, and the best way to learn about a community is to visit it.<p>

After the visits, the dozen or so candidates should be narrowed to three or four finalists, which then would receive another round of visits.  At this time, it generally facilitates the process to have team, rather than individual, visits.  It is at this point that the issue of incentives is best raised.  If the process has gone as it should, all the finalists should offer attractive sites and locations, and incentives might well tip the balance.<p>

<a name="Section 3"><hr></a>
<h2 align=center>Section 3: Common Mistakes and Misconceptions</h2>

Probably the most common mistake companies make is to focus exclusively on initial concerns and start-up considerations-and to not take into account the dynamic nature both of business needs and of the sites under consideration.  This can result in the selection of sites in communities that appear attractive today, but whose advantages will soon disappear.  Some of the ways this can occur-and tips for avoiding such mistakes-already have been mentioned in earlier portions of the text.<p>

Other common errors include:<p>
<ul type=square>
<li>Excessive concern with avoiding unions.<p>
Unionism has declined as an issue over the last decade, with most management/labor relationships having advanced far beyond the simplistic adversarial approaches of the past.  In addition, technological changes are making it feasible to operate smaller facilities than in the past and will permit more personal, hands-on management, a development which diminishes the importance of unionization.<p>
<li>Placement of too much emphasis on state and local taxes.<p>

There is a large body of evidence that indicates that the magnitude of other costs dwarfs the impact of sate and local taxes.  Moreover, companies located in higher tax communities could very well benefit from the physical and educational infrastructure, as well as the governmental services that those taxes pay for.  Studies suggest that, overall, state and local business taxes generally do not seem to have a significant impact on after-tax rates of return, and that they usually should be of secondary consideration in site selection decisions.<p>

<img src="../../graph/business/ss22.jpg" width=155 height=121 hspace=10 vspace=10 align=right>

<li>Use of "business climate" rankings.<p>

Though business climates studies often get a lot of publicity, the methodologies used to determine "business climate" ranking are controversial, and the results are often of dubious value.  For one thing, the rankings generally are done on a state-by-state basis.  As a result, they are usually so general as to be, at best, of little use, and, at worst, misleading.
</ul>

In the end, companies planning a new facility should always remember that they are looking for a site, not for a state.<p>


<a name="The Illinois Advantage"><hr></a>
<h2 align=center>The Illinois Advantage</h2>

At the Illinois Department of Commerce and Community Affairs (DCCA) we are proud of our record of responding to the needs of businesses engaged in the search for sites for new facilities and plant expansions.<p>

Take our computerized database, one of the first in the nation to provide site seeking firms with complete, up-to-date and accurate information about currently available industrial sites and the communities in which they are located.  Today, our computerized Site and Buildings Inventory can help you located and identify appropriate sites and buildings by providing almost instantaneous access to such information as the size of building and site, ceiling height, rail access, shipping and receiving facilities, crane availability, acreage, utilities, waterway access, zoning, rail access, highway access, EPA attainment and ownership.  Similarly, our computerized Community Profile Inventory provides access to data about community assets, including information about such things as municipal services, climate, population, utilities, local industry, tax structure, commercial services, transportation, health facilities, education facilities, labor force and location services.  Community Profiles and information on many sites and buildings are accessible via this Internet page.<p>

Or consider how our recognition of the growing importance of advanced telecommunication services has enabled us to identify locations where companies can get access to fiber optic transmission, digital switching and other telecommunications services.<p>

<img src="../../graph/business/ss23.jpg" width=299 height=213 hspace=10 vspace=10 align=right>

Moreover, the site selection resources we offer go far beyond just our data bases.  In fact, our most important resource is the depth and breadth of our experience with site selection efforts.<p>

For well over three decades, DCCA and its predecessors have helped businesses with their site selection efforts.  We have helped hundreds of businesses find sites for new facilities or for expansions in Illinois.  This experience has enabled our DCCA professionals to gain an understanding of the site selection process and has enabled us to design and implement programs that can help organizations looking for industrial sites.  We think of ourselves as an extension of your site selection team, and we are confident that our experience enables us to make suggestions, anticipate problems and generally facilitate your site selection efforts.<p>


<a name="The Site Selection Scorecard"><hr></a>
<h2 align=center>The Site Selection Scorecard</h2>

Because of the complexity of the site selection process, it can be extra helpful to have a convenient way to organize the mass of information you will be collecting about sites and to keep track of the criteria that are going to eliminate some locations and keep others in.<p>

Based on our experience with numerous site selection projects, we have put together a "scorecard" that is designed to fit the needs of most site selection efforts and that you can use to help you navigate through the systematic evaluation and screening of site candidates.  Needless to say, every site selection project is distinct and involves a different balance of factors and considerations, and this scorecard is intended to be easily tailored to meet the special needs of your particular search.<p>

The basic organization of the scorecard is quite straightforward.  A list of requirements and criteria that commonly arise in site selection runs down the scorecard, while room has been left across the top of the scorecard for the listing of site candidates.<p>

The criteria are, for the most part, self-explanatory.  The first column, right of the criterion/requirement, is intended for description of the ideal site.  Each of the subsequent columns are intended for information about sites under consideration.  Most of the criteria are easily quantified, but the last section of the scorecard also includes a number of factors that, although important, are harder to measure.  One way to handle these types of considerations is to try to "rate" each candidate site on a scale of 1-10 (worst to best) according to how well you feel that site fits your needs with respect to that factor.<p>

We also have included a column of boxes on the far left of the scorecard to be used to rate each of the criteria according to its importance, e.g.:<p>

A--essential<br>
B--important<br>
C--nice to have<br>

<h3>Ideal Site Requirements</h3>
<pre>
<strong>Importance    Criteria                             Site Requirements         </strong>                  

              <strong>Community Criteria</strong>

              Minimum/maximum size
              Maximum price/acre
              Additional acreage available?
              Zoning
              Date site is needed/available


              <strong>Building Requirements</strong>
 
              Minimum/maximum square footage
              Freestanding required?
              Type of construction
              Single story required?
              Office space needed?
              Buy/lease?
              Special facilities (e.g. freezer)
              Drive-in doors
              Minimum number of truck bays
              USDA approval needed?
              Floor thickness
              Floor load capacity
              Compressed air required?
              Cranes
              Elevators & capacity
              Clear ceiling height
              Sprinkler requirements
              Minimum parking spaces


              <strong>Electric Power</strong>

              Project connected load (KW&cost)
              Maximum projected demand anticipated
                  (KW&cost)
              Monthly projected use (KW&cost)
              Reliability
              Radial or loop service
              Power factor %


              <strong>Other Utility Requirements</strong>

              Water (gal/day&cost)
              Sanitary sewer (gal/day&cost)
              Process sewer (gal/day&cost)
              Natural Gas (MCF/month&cost)
              Waste treatment&disposal 
                  (availability/cost)
              Telecommunications
              -Cost
              -Special requirements (e.g. digital 
               switching, fiber optical transmiss  
               satellite transmission capability)

              <strong>Transportation</strong>
            
              Proximity to critical facilities
                  (miles&time)
              Airport
              -Commercial service
              -Air cargo service
              -Private
              Interstate highway
              Rail
              Water
              Intermodal facility
              Suppliers
              Customers
              Major city
              University
              Est. annual transportation cost


              <strong>Other Important Criteria</strong>
 
              State and local taxes
              Environmental considerations
              Special incentives
              -Enterprise Zones
              -Foreign Trade Zone
              -TIF district, special service area,
               or special purpose district


              <strong>Community Criteria</strong>
 
              Minimum/maximum size of community
              Labor force costs: critical job
                  classification and wages
 
              Special business services
              (type needed and number available)
              (e.g. machine shops, tool&die shops,
               local media, financial services,
               hotels and meeting facilities,
               computer programming, specialized
               engineering consultants)
              Special education/training programs needed


              <strong>Community Information List (Qualitative Evaluations)</strong>

              Services & Resources
              Local industry
              -Major employers, number of employees
              Type of government
              Local tax structure
              Fire department
              -Size
              -Capabilities
              -Insurance class
              Industrial waste pick-up?
              Private contractor?
              Location services


              <strong>Community Facilities</strong>

              Recreational and cultural amenities
              Health care
              Education
              Higher education
              Day care availability
</pre>
<hr><p>
For additional information on the following topics, see the "<a href="../../menus/facts.htm"> Facts About Illinois</a>" section of this web site.<p>

Building Costs<br>
Education<br>
Energy<br>
